<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Milton's Intro Page</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#EEFFFF">
<IMG ALIGN="Top" SRC="girl.gif" ALT="">If you aren't familiar with the World Wide Web, then...<P><h1>Welcome to Milton's Introduction Page!</h1>
<p>
The purpose of this page is to help acquaint new users with the World Wide Web (Web, WWW, or W3).  If you are reading this page, you already know how to connect to the Web.  There are two main concepts to learn in order to understand what the Web does and how to use it.
<P>
<B>The first is the concept of Hypertext</B>.  Hypertext (as opposed to regular text) provides a link to further information about the words or pictures in a given document.  When a word is <A HREF="link.htm">highlighted</A> (like the word highlighted is), it indicates the word has a link to another document that will tell you more about it.  If you take you mouse and point at the word, many browsers will show you an address.  This address is where the linked document is located.  It could be anywhere in the world.  When you click on the hyperlink, the new document is downloaded for your examination.  It may also contain links to other documents.  This process goes on and on creating a network (or web) of linked documents that are stored in millions of computers all over the world.
<P>
<B>The other concept to learn is that of the <A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/demoweb/url-primer.html">URL</A>.</B>  URL (Uniform Resource Locator) is just a fancy name for the electronic addresses of the documents I just described.  If you pointed (or jumped) to the word highlighted above, you might have seen its URL:
<P>
<CENTER>http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/help/link.htm</CENTER>
<P>
This URL has three parts.  The first part "http:" specifies that you are interested in a <U>H</U>yper<U>T</U>ext <U>T</U>ransfer <U>P</U>rotocol type of document (i.e. a web document).  The second part "www.psych.med.umich.edu" specifies the server or the Internet address of the computer that you want information from.  This computer is located at the <U>U</U>niversity of <U>Mich</U>igan in the <U>Psych</U>iatry Department.  The last part specifies the file you want.  The name of the file is "<U>link.htm</U>"  and it is located in the <U>help</U> folder which is inside the <U>web</U> folder.
<P>
If you click on the link above, the file "link.htm" is downloaded onto your computer from the computer in the psychiatry (psych) domain of the medical (med) domain of the University of Michigan (umich) domain.  You could also reach this URL anytime by typing the full URL into your browser where it says "open location" or "open URL."
<HR>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>If you would like to learn more</B></FONT> about the Web and Psychiatry, please read the article, <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/psytimes/psychwww.htm"><B>Psychiatry Navigates the Web</B></A>, reprinted from the Psychiatric Times.
<P>
For those who want to start jumping around, check out our page of <A HREF="/web/psychref/">References in Psychiatry</A> that you can access from the <A HREF="/web/UMpsych/">UM Psychiatry Home Page</A>.  Our home page also provides a link to a list of <A HREF="/web/medref/">References in Medicine</A>.  It isn't as up to date as the <A HREF="/web/psychref/">psychiatry reference page</A>, so if you find new resources for me to add, let me know.
<P>
For those interested in exploring the Web in general, try one of these links...
<UL>
<LI>the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/">Yahoo</A> pages
<LI>the <A HREF="http://www.einet.net/galaxy.html">EINet Galaxy</A>
<LI>the <A HREF="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/DataSources/bySubject/Overview.html">WWW Virtual Library</A> maintained by W3 consortium.
</UL>
<P>
If you find anything interesting on the Web you think I should add, or if you have problems with this page, click on the <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A> link and write to us.
<HR>
<B><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>

