<HR>

<H1> <A NAME="What we are doing">What we are doing</A></H1>

</P>

	Since its creation in 1953 with fewer than 100 members, the AACAP has been a growing and dynamic organization, giving direction to and responding quickly to new developments in the health care environment, and addressing the needs of children, adolescents and families. </P>

 Examples of the Academy's responses to national concerns over the years include : <UL>
<LI>establishing guidelines for the clinical evaluation of child sexual abuse,
<LI> amicus statement before the Supreme Court on Supplemental Security Income (SSI) for children with disabilities,
<LI> suggested questions for parents to ask when psychiatric hospitalization is recommended for their child, and
<LI>scientific initiatives on children and AIDS.</UL><P></P>



<HR>
<H2>1. <A NAME="public education and prevention">Public Education and Prevention</A></H2>

<H4><A HREF="/web/aacap/factsFam/index.htm">Facts for families</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/pubs.htm">Publication on Prevention</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A></H4>

	To help educate parents and families about psychiatric disorders affecting children and adolescents, the Academy publishes <A HREF="factsFam/">"Facts for Families"</A> - over 52 informational sheets which provide concise and up-to-date material on issues such as the depressed child, teen suicide, helping children after a disaster, discipline, learning disabilities, and child sexual abuse.  Thousands of these publications are distributed weekly, and the "Facts for Families" has been cited and recommended by such publications as Better Homes & Gardens, Ladies Home Journal and USA Today.</P>
	Closely tied to the need for public education is the importance of prevention of mental illnesses.  The Academy's three-year Project on Prevention identified the knowledge base for the prevention of psychiatric disorders in children and adolescents.  The project culminated in the publication of two monographs, 
<UL>
<LI> Prevention of Mental Disorders, Alcohol and Other Drug Use in Children and Adolescents, and
<LI> Prevention in Child and Adolescent Psychiatry: The Reduction of Risk for Mental Disorders. 
</UL>
<P>

<H4><A HREF="/web/aacap/factsFam/index.htm">Facts for families</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/pubs.htm">Publication on prevention</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A>
</H4></P>




<HR>
<H2><A NAME="clinical affairs">2. Supporting  Clinical Practice</A></H2>

<H4><A HREF="/web/aacap/meeting/">Upcoming meetings and events</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/pubs.htm">Parameters of practice</A> | 
 <A HREF="http://pub.wwilkins.com/waverly/periodicals/DATA/0890-8567.html">Journal of the AACAP</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A></H4></P>

<B>The Annual Meeting of the AACAP</B></P>

	Integral to the goal of assuring optimal psychiatric services for children, adolescents and families, is continuing medical education.  The Academy's scientific Annual Meeting attracts over 2500  specialists in child and adolescent psychiatric care, presenting the most recent findings in research, diagnosis and treatment.  In addition, scientific institutes educate child and adolescent psychiatrists about the state-of-the-art in areas such as forensics, psychopharmacology, psychotherapy, neuropsychiatry and the biopsychosocial aspects of mood disorders.  An Annual Review provides an overview and integration of the most recent knowledge regarding a wide range of illnesses and treatment modalities.</P>

<B>The parameters of practice</B></P>

	In keeping with a new initiative within the medical profession, the Academy's Office of Clinical Affairs has begun developing <B>parameters of practice</B> which will serve as guidelines for the generally accepted level of practice for the assessment and treatment of various psychiatric disorders.  The first parameters focus on :
<OL>
<LI> Attention-Deficit Hyperactivity Disorders, 
<LI> Conduct Disorders,
<LI> Anxiety Disorders.
</OL>


 Others parameters, currently in production, include, assessment and treatment of children and adolescent with schizophrenia; substance abuse; assessing infants; diagnostic assessment of children and adolescents; treatment of children and adolescents with mood disorders; treatment of infants and children with eating disorders.  <P>

<B>Publications of the Academy</B></P>

	In addition, the Academy is responsible of the following publications:
<UL>

<LI> Research Notes in Child and Adolescent Psychiatry
<LI> Managed Care Report 
<LI> AACAP News, a bi-monthly membership newsletter
<LI> Journal of the American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry,the distinguished journal.
</UL>

 The <A HREF="http://pub.wwilkins.com/waverly/periodicals/DATA/0890-8567.html">Journal of the American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry</A>, a bi-monthly publication for members and non-members, includes articles and special sections which combine treatment information and current research on scientific topics and related issues in child and adolescent psychiatry.  Special sections in recent years have focused on:
<UL>
<LI>issues in child and adolescent psychiatric hospitalization.
<LI>learning disabilities.
<LI>developments in child psychiatric epidemiology.
<LI>suicide in children and adolescents.
<LI>children's reactions to severe stress.
<LI> Research Initiatives.     
</UL>
</P>

<H4><A HREF="/web/aacap/meeting/">Upcoming meetings and events</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/pubs.htm">Parameters of practice</A> |  <A HREF="http://pub.wwilkins.com/waverly/periodicals/DATA/0890-8567.html">Journal of the AACAP</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A></H4></P>



<HR>
<H2> <A NAME="research">3. Supporting Research</A></H2>

<H4><A HREF="/web/aacap/rptcard.htm">Research Report Card</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/pubs.htm">Publication</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/meeting/">Upcoming meetings and events</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A></H4></P>


	The Academy's Office of Research promotes and supports research careers, publicizes research training opportunities, and works with the research community to establish and support a research infrastructure in child and adolescent psychiatry.</P>

  The Office of Research publishes the tri-annual <B>Child and Adolescent Research Notes</B>, a comprehensive newsletter providing information on ongoing research, research training programs, and funding opportunities in private or federal agencies. </P>

 The Office of Research administers the<B> James Comer/NIMH Minority Recruitment Program </B>to recruit minority medical students and general psychiatry residents into research careers. </P>

 The Office also directs the <B>NIMH/AACAP Research Career Development Award Program</B> which provides qualified junior faculty a unique opportunity to gain extensive research training experience at major research centers across the country.</P>

 The Office of Research sponsors <B>the Research Forum at the Academy's annual meeting</B> for the dissemination and discussion of current issues in child and adolescent psychiatric research.</P>

  In addition, the Office works to secure funding for research fellowships, sponsors grant writing workshops, works with pharmaceutical companies to support psychopharmacology studies, and publicizes the research efforts of Academy members.<P>

<H4><A HREF="/web/aacap/rptcard.htm">Research Report Card</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/pubs.htm">Publication</A> |<A HREF="/web/aacap/meeting/">Upcoming meetings and events</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A></H4></P>



<HR>
<H2>		4.<A NAME="government affairs">	Government and National Affairs</A></H2>

<H4>| <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/legalert.htm">Current legislative alerts</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/">Government affairs</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A></H4></P>

<B> National Health Care Reform and The Academy</B><P>

	The Academy is involved in a very important struggle to ensure that psychiatrists and their patients are equitably treated in the national health care reform bills that are currently circulating through the U.S. Congress, particularly that there are adequate services included for children and adolescents.  In dealing with the Congress and the administration, the Academy is working closely with the American Medical Association, The American Psychiatric Association, and the National Consortium for Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services.  <P>

	Through government education efforts and liaison with national organizations, the Academy works for the improvement and expansion of psychiatric services for The Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations, and the evaluation of criteria for managed care companies.</P>

 The Academy founded the<B> National Consortium for Child Mental Health Services</B>, a coalition of 22 professional, provider and consumer organizations.  <P>

	The AACAP is a member of the House of Delegates of the American Medical Association and actively participates in the AMA regarding policies for better treatment of children and adolescents.<P>

	On Capitol Hill, the Academy continually educates about legislation which provides appropriations and treatment services for youngsters and families with mental illnesses.
<UL>
<LI> Members testify before congressional committees on topics such as psychiatric hospitalization, health insurance and youth violence. 
<LI> The Academy participates in class- action suits and submits amicus statements on behalf of children and adolescents in cases before district courts and the Supreme Court.
</UL>
</P>
<H4>| <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/legalert.htm">Current legislative alerts</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/">Government affairs</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A></H4></P>



<HR>
<H2>5.<A NAME="need for service and managed care"> Need for services and Managed Care</A> </H2> 

<H4>| <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/legalert.htm">Legislative alert</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A></H4></P>

<B>Improving the Managed Care</B> </P>

 In just the last few years, all of medicine has been caught in the rapid spread of managed care, the monitoring of medical care decisions for the authorization of reimbursement.  It comes as the business community has stepped in to control the escalating costs of medical care.	The challenge of managed care and its effects on the practice of child and adolescent psychiatry has been an on-going struggle for the Academy for the past several years.  Through the diligent efforts of our members and special task forces involving managed care, the Academy continues to make progress in this area. <P>

	Through the Academy's work on practice parameters and outcomes research, practitioners are seeing changes. </P>

The AACAP's Appellate Review Program</P>

 The Academy has also embarked on a pilot<B> Appellate Review Program</B> designed to improve the quality of care in managed care systems.  This program is an appeal review service available for contracted managed care companies to resolve certification disputes when internal appeal processes have been exhausted. </P>

 The appeal reviews are limited to inpatient, residential, or partial hospitalization cases in which the patient is under the age of 20, or outpatient cases in which care is provided by or under the supervision of a psychiatrist to patients under the age of 20.  </P>

Reviewers are board certified child and adolescent psychiatrists with a minimum of five years of experience in inpatient and alternative treatment settings.  Panels of three reviewers will review and discuss each case to ensure the quality of the final decisions and reports.<P>



<H3>Addressing the Need for Services</H3>



 The number of child and adolescent psychiatrists has tripled to more than 6,000 over the past 30 years, but there are still too few to treat the disorders of children and adolescents.  Part of the Academy's mission is to increase the number of child and adolescent psychiatrists available to meet the need.  The Academy sponsored a national recruitment conference in 1987 to develop strategies to increase the number of qualified professionals in this field.<P>

	According to an Institute of Medicine report at least 7.5 million, or 12% of U.S. youngsters have a diagnosable mental illness.  Yet because appropriate services are not available, only about one-third of these receive treatment.

<H4>| <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/legalert.htm">Legislative alert</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A></H4></P>


<HR>



<H1><A NAME="who we are">Who we are</A>.</H1>

<H4><A HREF="/web/aacap/contact.htm">Directory</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/members.htm">How to join the AACAP</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/maillist.htm">Mailing list</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A>|<A HREF="/web/aacap/factsFam/wherehlp.htm"> Contact for families</A></H4>

<H3>A representative association of Child and Adolescent Psychiatrists in United States and worldwide.</H3>

	The Academy represents over 5,600 child and adolescent psychiatrists - physicians with at least five years of additional training beyond medical school in general and child and adolescent psychiatry.  AACAP members actively research, diagnose and treat psychiatric disorders affecting children and adolescents and their families, and the Academy is dedicated to supporting this work through a variety of programs including government liaison, national public information and continuing medical education.<P>


<H3>A task force on Child and Adolescent Psychiatry and related fields</H3>

 The Academy has established several work groups and task forces to address new challenges: 
<UL>
<LI>The Work Group on Quality Issues develops practice parameters for the profession. 
<LI> The Work Group on Consumer Issues educates the public about psychiatric disorders and related issues, and
<LI> the Work Group on Research oversees the activities of the Office of Research and initiates new programs to increase the level of research in child and adolescent psychiatry.
</UL>
<P>

	The Academy sponsors 45 committees which work to increase the knowledge base about specific areas of interest for Academy members and the public, and help the Academy disseminate information on a wide range of topics affecting children and families. </P>
 The Academy's committees have developed position statements on various issues such as adolescent psychiatric hospitalization, corporal punishment in schools, adolescent pregnancy prevention, and protecting children undergoing abuse investigations and testimony. 
</P> Among the Academy's Committees are:
<UL>
<LI>computer utilization
<LI>psychotherapy
<LI>substance abuse
<LI>training
<LI>rights and legal matters
<LI>peer review
<LI>continuing education
<LI>HIV issues
</UL>

<H3>A federation of regional organizations throughout United States</H3>

	The Academy, a non-profit 501(c)(3) organization, is governed by an elected Council of 16 members. 
<UL>
<LI> Five members of Council are elected by the Assembly of Regional Organizations, which consists of 64 delegates of 54 regional councils of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry from throughout the U.S. 
<LI> The other 11 Councillors, including the Executive Committee, are elected by the general membership.
</UL>
 </P>

 The Academy's Assembly of<A HREF="/web/aacap/factsFam/wherehlp.htm"> Regional Organizations</A>, a network of state and local councils, meets twice a year and monitors child and adolescent psychiatric services at the local level and provide opportunities for information exchange about new programs, improved treatment methods and legislative developments.     <P>


<H4><A HREF="/web/aacap/contact.htm">Directory</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/members.htm">How to join the AACAP</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/maillist.htm">Mailing list</A> | <A HREF="#introduction">up</A> |<A HREF="/web/aacap/factsFam/wherehlp.htm"> Contact for families</A></H4>



