<A NAME="legislative_update_104">Legislative Update 104-19, March 29, 1996</A><p>

<h3>Senate Passes Parity Amendment</h3>


		104th 2nd Session of Congress<br>


			104 - 20<br>


1-800-333-7636, ext 117<br>
<center><H3><b>
MENTAL ILLNESSES EQUAL PHYSICAL<BR> 
ILLNESSES IN HEALTH CARE REFORM
BILL</b><p>


<b>Amendment Under Attack by Insurers</b><p></H3></center>
<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=40></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=350>





On Thursday, April 18, the Senate approved (65 to 33) Senators Domenici (R-NM) and
Wellstone's (D-MN) amendment to a health care reform bill that was approved 100 - 0 on the
23rd.  The amendment's purpose is: To ensure that parity is provided under health plans for severe
mental illness services.  <p>


Academy members and staff  have worked for several years to push this amendment into law. It
has been approved at different levels and in different forms before but never made it into the final
version.  We now have another chance to try to get it into law, but serious opposition is forming.<p>

<IMG vspace=2 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR><IMG vspace=2 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>
<b>Background and Status</b>	The health care reform bills (S.1028 and H.R.3130) introduced in this 	Congress are far smaller in size and scope than the major reforms debated 		during 1993 - 1994.  Aimed at covering workers when they leave or change jobs (portability) and
when they have pre-existing conditions, the bills have now been considered by both houses of
Congress.  The House added several amendments to its basic bill, including the controversial
medical savings account (MSA) provision.  The Senate adopted fewer amendments, defeating the
MSAs and Senator Jefford's increase in lifetime limits amendment but approving parity for mental
illnesses coverage.  <p>


<p>
<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

The Senate parity amendment prohibits two specific practices:<p>


1.  Day and visit limits -- health insurers will no longer be permitted to limit outpatient care  to ten
visits or inpatient hospital services to thirty days.<p>


2.  Discriminatory Copayments -- Insurance companies would also be barred from charging $10
per visit to see an OBGYN or a pediatrician, but $25 to see a child and adolescent psychiatrist.<p>


The next step is a conference between the House and the Senate to write a single bill.   Conferees
have not been named, but the leadership has indicated a desire to have a final bill through
conference by the end of May.<p>

<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>
<b>Problems:</b>	President Clinton said he will not sign a reform measure that includes medical savings 		accounts.  His objections include the inability of all workers to participate and the tax 		losses from the deductibility of the account contributions.<p>


	It appears that a conference agreement could center around dropping the House provision on
MSA's and the Senate provision on parity for mental illnesses.  Senator Kassebaum, the sponsor
of the Senate health care reform bill, said of the parity amendment that, "it was likely this
amendment would be dropped in conference with the House."  Senator Dole indicated in a press
conference that the parity amendment would likely be dropped in conference.<p>


	The ERISA Industry Committee and many other business community leaders are strongly
opposing the amendment by withdrawing support for the entire bill.  The USA Today reported the
amendment as "the biggest federal health benefit mandate ever..... it could endanger health
coverage rather than enhance it."  The Wall Street Journal reported that the amendment, "has set
off a furor among big employers who are worried their insurance costs will explode."<p>


<p>
<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

<b>Goal: 	TO RETAIN THE PARITY AMENDMENT IN THE HEALTH CARE 			REFORM BILL AND HAVE THE BILL SIGNED INTO LAW.<p>
<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

What can I do?<p>


WRITE, CALL OR E-MAIL YOUR MEMBERS OF CONGRESS,  SENATOR NANCY
KASSEBAUM AND THE SENATE MAJORITY LEADER ABOUT THE CRITICAL
NEED TO KEEP THE DOMENICI/WELLSTONE PARITY AMENDMENT IN THE
HEALTH CARE REFORM BILL DURING CONFERENCE</b>.  If your Senator voted not to
table the parity amendment, please thank him or her (see attached list of votes).  <p>


<b>Call:  </b>You can reach your members Washington offices by calling the Capitol Operator at
(202)224-3121.  When you call, be sure to mention that you are a constituent and a child and
adolescent psychiatrist.  (See letter below for talking points.)<p>


<b>E-mail:</b>  The e-mail address for on-line congressional offices can be accessed through the
document center's web site: gopher://una.hh.lib.umich.edu/o/socsci/poliscilaw/uslegi/conemail.<p>


<b>Write/Fax:</b> Write or fax a letter or postcard to your members' Washington office.  Addresses are
included below. To find out if your senators' have a public fax number,  call the Academy's
Department of Government Affairs at 1-800-333-7636. We have included a sample letter below
and addresses for your members' and Majority Leader Dole.<p>


<p>


The Honorable (Senator's name), U.S. Senate, Washington, DC 20510		The Honorable (Representative's name), U.S. House of Representatives, Washington, DC 20515<p>


			Majority Leader Bob Dole			U.S. Senate			Washington, DC 20510<p>


<u><b>Sample letter that includes talking points:</b></u><p>


Dear Representative/Senator:<p>


 ( please personalize the letter however you want)<p>


I am a constituent and a child and adolescent psychiatrist who supports Senators Domenici and
Wellstone's proposed mental illness parity amendment to the Health Insurance Reform Act
(S.1028).  The amendment would provide coverage and cost-sharing for severe mental illnesses
on the same basis as other medical conditions<p>


The Domenici-Wellstone amendment will give children and adolescents with mental illnesses, such
as schizophrenia, attention deficit disorder, depression, obsessive compulsive disorder, and
conduct disorder, an equal chance to receive the appropriate services they need to live healthy
productive lives.  As the health care system and its financing are now structured, inequitable
allocation of health resources places many children and adolescents with severe mental illnesses at
an extreme disadvantage.  <p>


<p>
<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

<b>The Cost Monster</b>	The perceived cost to the insurers for non-discriminatory coverage is the major issue.  The 	insurers are reporting at least a 10 percent increase in premiums, and the amendment's 			supporters have studies showing minimum increases of 1.6 percent to 5 percent.  Two studies
released in the last two weeks by respected consulting firms of Coopers &amp; Lybrand and Milliman
&amp; Robertson show that the amendment will only increase premiums by about 3.2 percent.  That is
the equivalent of $3.75 pre month or $45 per year.  In addition, Coopers &amp; Lybrand found that
mental health parity will actually save federal, state  and county governments a combined total of
$16.6 billion in public sector mental illnesses costs.  Major employers such as Xerox,
Sterling-Winthrop, Conoco, and Alcan Aluminum, who have eliminated either arbitrary service
limits or discriminatory copayments and deductibles have reported 40% net savings in the
delivery.  In another example, a 1994 MIT study reported that clinical depression alone costs
American businesses $23.8 billion annually in worker absenteeism and lost productivity.<p>


<p>
<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

Successful diagnosis and treatment is a wise investment, given the pain, long-term disadvantages,
and financial costs associated with untreated childhood behavioral and emotional disorders.  I
urge you to support the right for children and adolescents with mental illnesses to receive health
coverage, just like other children and adolescents.  Children must have access to the appropriate
treatment and services needed to live as productively and independently as possible.	<p>


<p>


Thank you for your consideration of children and adolescents with severe mental illnesses. If I can
help you in any way, please call me at (your number).<p>


<p>


Sincerely,<p>


(Your name), M.D.<p>


<p>


Enclosed, for your information, is the transcript from the floor debate on the amendment and
articles from the Washington Post and Wall Street Journal.  We will contact you with more
information when the conferees are named.<p>



</TD> </TR> </TABLE>

If you have any questions, please call the Department of Government Affairs at 1-800-333-7636.	<p>
<IMG vspace=8 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>













<HR noshade>
<A NAME="legislative_update_104">Legislative Update 104-19</A><P>
<center><H2>IDEA, FDA, Welfare, and Health Care
Reform Part of 104th Congress' Full
Legislative Plate</H2></center>




<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>






Department of Government Affairs Legislative Update 104-19, March 29, 1996<p>




<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=40></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=350>



<b>IDEA</b><p>


<b>Status: </b>(since 2/13/96 Leg. Alert)<p>


<b>Senate:</b>  The Senate has begun the reauthorization of the Individuals with Disabilities Education
Act (IDEA).  The bill (S. 1578) was written (marked-up) in the Labor and Human Resources
Committees last week, and approved by a 16-0 voice vote.  Although there is strong bi-partisan
support for the bill, it did not go through unamended. <p>


Discipline in schools has been a key issue in this reauthorization.  Due to the extreme controversy
over this issue, the Senate bill (S. 1578), as introduced, did not include language on discipline.  In
an eleventh hour compromise agreement, Senator Frist (R-TN) introduced a discipline
amendment. The amendment, which, also passed by a voice vote of 16-0, removes a child with a
disability from his or her current placement when the behaviors seen as "seriously disruptive," or
"substantially likely" to engage in violence.<p>


Senator Frist (R-TN) introduced another amendment that would limit parents' rights to collect
attorney's fees.   The amendment provides for a reduction in attorney's fees if parents fail to notify
school districts of their intent to file for a due process hearing.  This amendment puts the burden
of notification on the parents.  Many parents are not aware of this provision and are immediately
placed at a disadvantage.<p>


Senate floor debate is anticipated for mid-April.  We know that there could be unfriendly
amendments around the issues of related services, attorney's fees, and discipline introduced on the
floor.  These amendments promise to weaken current law and will discriminate against children
and adolescents with mental illnesses.  <p>


There is a pattern of backlash hostility against children with mental illnesses because they are seen
as violent and disruptive toward other children in schools.  Some legislators believe that these
children should be unilaterally removed from the classroom and moved permanently to an
alternative educational placement.  Current law has provisions to avoid this, but the discipline
amendment introduced in the mark-up is just the start of weakening the law and denying children
with disabilities their right to a free and appropriate public education. <p>


<b>House:  </b>The House plans to introduce its bill in mid-April.  Subcommittee mark-up is scheduled
for the end of April.  <p>



<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

<u><b>What should I do?</b></u><p>


<b>It is imperative that you contact your Senator and express your (1) support for the existing
law and, (2) concern that its protections will be weakened. </b>The following are some key points
to make when talking to, or writing your senators and representatives:<p>



<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

<u><b>Talking Points:</b></u><p>


* <i><b>Don't use disciplinary measures as an excuse to improperly exclude or expel children with
disabilities: </b></i>IDEA already contains adequate disciplines for all children with disabilities. 
Inappropriate segregation or expulsion solves nothing; it just increases lifelong costs to society. 
Children with serious emotional disorders should be receiving treatment.  Providers and parents
should have a part in decisions to move these children.<p>


* <i><b>Don't dismantle IDEA just to reduce costs: </b></i>Everyone is concerned about reducing waste and
increasing efficiency, but do not randomly, carelessly, or haphazardly alter the law in the name of
reducing costs.  It is critical to adequately provide for the educational needs of children with
disabilities within their local public schools. <p>


* <i><b>Education is the best investment anyone can make in the life of a child with a disability:</b></i> By
receiving a good education, children with serious emotional disturbances will be best prepared to
fully participate in and be an asset to society.  Effective education and related services save money
by reducing lifelong dependency.  IDEA is a good investment, which will be recouped many times
over.<p>

<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>



<u><b>FDA REFORM</b></u><p>


<u><b>Status: </b></u>(since 2/13 Leg. Alert)<p>


<b>Senate: </b>On March 27, the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee began writing an FDA
reform bill introduced by Senator Nancy Kassebaum (R-KS).  Pediatric pharmacology research
provisions are included.  The bill provides a 6-month additional period of exclusivity (period when
generic versions of drugs may not be introduced) to any company that includes pediatric
information in the labeling.  It also gives the FDA commissioner the ability to require pediatric
labeling information be included in the review process.  As noted in previous Legislative Alerts
(104-15), the original bill allowed drug companies to disseminate off-label use information, from
journals and textbooks, with very little oversight by the FDA.  During the mark-up, the committee
decided to delete all information regarding off-label use information dissemination.  The language
will be reworked by Senators Christopher Dodd (D-CT) and Bill Frist (R-TN), and will probably
be back in the bill before it reaches the Senate floor.  The bill will next be debated on the Senate
floor prior to a vote.  <p>


<b>House:</b>  Also on March 27, the House Commerce Committee held a press conference announcing
the House's FDA reform bill.  The legislation will be introduced as three separate bills covering
drugs, medical devices and food.  Some of the provisions common to the three bills include:<p>


* Providing an annual report to Congress describing the FDA performance in the review process. 
* Requiring the FDA to set up an accreditation system for third-party reviewers of applications.<p>


* Establishing an accessible internal tracking system for applications.<p>


* Allowing off-label use information to be disseminated but only if it promotes an approved drug
use.<p>


<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>


<u><b>HEALTH CARE REFORM</b></u><p>


<u><b>Status: </b></u>(since 2/27/96 Leg. Alert)<p>


<b>Senate:  </b>S. 1028, Senator Kassebaum's (R-KS) Health Care Reform Act of 1995 is scheduled for
floor debate on April 18.   Senator Jefford's (R-VT) amendment on preventing health plans from
imposing lifetime caps, and Senators Wellstone (R-MN) and Domenici's (R-NM) amendment on
mental health parity are possible amendments to the bill.  Although it is still unclear whether
Senator Kassebaum will accept any floor amendments to the bill, an oral agreement was
supposedly made between Senator Kasseubaum and Senator Jeffords on the acceptance of his
amendment on the floor if he did not introduce it in committee.<p>


<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>


<b>House:  </b>The House committees on Commerce, Ways and Means, and Economic Opportunities
have been hard at work marking-up narrow health care reform legislation provisions that fall
under the jurisdiction of their respected committees.  All these bills have been folded into a
broader, fast-track health insurance bill, HR 3160, the Health Coverage Availability and
Affordability Act of 1996.  Like the Senate bill, the House GOP bill will improve portability of
health insurance, place limits on exclusions for preexisting conditions, guarantee renewability for
groups, and make health insurance more accessible to small businesses.  As of this writing, floor
debate on HR 3160 is scheduled for  March 28.  No amendments will be accepted during debate.<p>


House Democrats are urging the passage of a narrower, straightforward bill - similar to the
Kassebaum bill.  Their alternative bill will take language from the Kassebaum counterpart in the
House, sponsored by Representative Roukema (R-NJ) (HR 2893), and include a provision that
would increase the tax deduction for health insurance costs of the self-employed from 30 percent
to 80 percent.<p>


There is strong bi-partisan support for health care reform legislation to be enacted this Congress. 
Because of this support, it is likely that a bill will pass the House and Senate, and receive
Presidential approval.<p>


<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>


<u><b>MEDICAID REFORM<p>


Status:</b></u> (since 3/22/96 Leg. Alert)<p>


<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>


GOP leaders announced last week that they were close to a compromise with the governors on
Medicaid reform legislation and had asked staff to begin making final edits to the bill.  Plans have
now been postponed due to disagreements among the governors, and a backlog of legislation
waiting to be drafted by Congressional staff.  Introduction of Medicaid legislation has already
slipped from the original date of March 25 and could be delayed until after recess (mid-April)<p>


<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>


The major point of disagreement between the governors and the GOP is over the financing
mechanism.  The latest draft proposal from the governors includes a growth factor that combines
an increase for expected case load growth with an adjustment for increases in health care costs,
and an open-ended umbrella fund that states would be able to tap into if costs increase for reasons
beyond their control. GOP staffers are concerned that this proposal could maintain an open-ended
federal commitment to Medicaid spending because there would be no aggregate cap on
expenditures.<p>


<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>


<b>With less than 50 legislating days left in this Congress and a backlog of legislation still
waiting to be drafted and marked-up, it grows more and more unlikely that we will see a
Medicaid reform bill pass this year.  But, political pressure and campaign promises could
put this on the fast-track and force a vote, and eventually Presidential approval.  <p>


<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>


<u>CONGRESSIONAL RECESS</u></b><p>


Congress will be in recess from April 1-12.  Now is the time to visit your Representative and
Senators while they are home.  <u><b>We urge you to call or visit your congresspersons and express
your concern for the issues that affect children and adolescents with mental illness.  </b></u>If you
need additional information about any of these issues, please contact the Academy's Department
of Government Affairs at 800-333-7636.

</TD> </TR> </TABLE>







<HR noshade>
<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>
<center><B>Legislative Update <A NAME="104-18">104-18</A></B><P>
<H2>Support for Appropriations Needed<BR>
Academy Testimony Heard by Subcommittee</H2>
</center><P>

<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>
Support is needed to persuade both House and Senate legislators to increase NIMH and
SAMHSA funding.<p>


Please contact your Senators and Representative to request critical NIMH funding for mental
illnesses research and SAMHSA funding for services.<p>


Children and adolescents with mental illnesses are benefitting from the research generated by the
1991 -1995, National Plan for Research on Child and Adolescent Mental Disorders.   As Dr.
Ritvo testified, "You have given NIMH the money to plant the orchard.  Now you must give the
money for the water and fertilizer if we are to harvest the fruit."  Rep. Porter complimented her
on, "your excellent testimony," but reinforcement is needed to assure a Fiscal Year 1997 increase
in both the research or services agenda.<p>

<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>
<b><u>ACTION NEEDED</u></b><BR>
	The House and Senate have not decided on any FY 1997 funding levels, so now is the time to
contact legislators.  Enclosed is a copy of the Academy's testimony and a list of the House and
Senate appropriations subcommittee members.  If you live in their states or districts, it is
especially important they hear from you.  A Congressional recess is scheduled for April 1-12. 
Legislators will be in their states and districts and available for individual or group meetings or at
town hall meetings.  There are less than 50 legislative days left in this Congress.<p>
<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

<u><b>GOAL</b></u><BR>
	To increase the NIMH appropriations to $711 million, a 7.5 percent 		jump from FY 1996, and to increase the Substance Abuse and Mental Health Administration's
Children's Mental Health Services Program to $80 million.<p>

<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>
<u><b>WHAT TO DO?</b></u><BR>
	Whether you call, visit, write or e-mail, the message is brief but important:<p>


	Research into the mental disorders of childhood and adolescence is at a critical stage.  Federal
funding, through NIMH, has played a major part in the infusion of support for investigating the
causes and most effective treatments for these disorders.  This support should not be diminished. 
The exciting breakthroughs are waiting in the wings and should not be delayed.  (If you want to
personalize the communication, insert or mention a personal case that benefitted from research or
points to the need for research.)  <p>


Other suggestions:<p>


- Mention the future research priorities (listed in the testimony) and stress what they mean in
terms of the lifetime of a child, adolescent, and the family dealing with a serious mental illness.<p>


	- Follow the research request with a plea for expanded services, specifically, the Substance Abuse
and Mental Health Services Administration's (SAMHSA) Children Mental Health Services
Program, which is now funded in 22 sites across the country and provides funding for states and
communities to create coordinated service systems for youngsters with serious mental disorders.<p>


<u>For FY 1997, the Academy is supporting a 7.5 percent increase for NIMH over FY 1996 ($711
million), and $80 million for the Children's Mental Health Services Program ($59.2 million in FY
1996)   </u><p>

<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>
<b>LAST YEAR, ORGANIZATIONAL UNITY, HARD WORK AND GRASSROOTS
ADVOCACY RESULTED IN REMOVING RESEARCH FUNDING FROM THE
GOVERNMENT SHUTDOWN CHAOS AND PROVIDING A 5.7 PERCENT INCREASE
FOR THE NATIONAL INSTITUTES OF HEALTH.  THIS WAS A NEAR MIRACLE. 
THIS YEAR WILL BE JUST AS ARDUOUS.  THANKS FOR HELPING.<p>


-</b>------------------------------------------<p>
<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

<B>What can I do?</B><p>


Call:  You can reach your representative's and senators' Washington offices by calling the Capitol
Operator at (202)224-3121.  When you call, be sure to mention that you are a constituent and a
child and adolescent psychiatrist with concerns about continued federal support for NIMH
research.  <p>


E-mail:  The e-mail address for on-line congressional offices can be accessed through the
document center's web site: gopher://una.hh.lib.umich.edu/o/socsci/poliscilaw/uslegi/conemail.<p>


Write/Fax: Please use the suggested messages and your own personalized comments.  The House
and Senate addresses are listed below:<p>


To write:<p>


Your Congressional representative: <p>


The Honorable ____________, U.S. House of Representatives, Washington, DC 20515            <p>


<p>


Your Senators: <p>


The Honorable ______________, U.S. Senate, Washington, DC 20510<p>


<p>


