<IMG SRC="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/images/pstaricn.gif" align="left"><H1>The HELP Homepage</H1>
Note that this section is still under development.  The list below contains proposed areas for HELP.  If you have suggestions, send us a <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">comment</A>.<BR CLEAR=ALL>
click on the area you need help with:
<FONT SIZE=+1>
<DL>
<DD><IMG SRC="/web/images/purpstar.gif">
<A HREF= "/web/help/internetbis.htm"></A><B>What is the Internet?</B></A>

<DL>The International Standards Organization (ISO) created standards to interconnect various computer and communications systems. A seven layer
model, open systems interconnect (OSI) model was adopted in 1978.  At the bottom layer was the actual physical transmission of electrons and at the top
were protocols for software such as E mail or the Web.
<P>
</DL>
<P>
Background
<DL> A land mark agreement was made to use what is called the TC/IP, a Transmission Control Internet Protocol. What was first available to the Defense Department and Research laboratories, is now available to the public.
<P>
Cerfing the Web (from an Interview reported in the WSJ, June 17, 1996) <BR>

Mr Spencer Cerf is commonly regarded as the father of the Internet, the global network of networks that provides the foundation for the WWW and electronic commerce. Many people think he earned that title for his work in co-inventing the computer language, introduced in 1974, that is the Internet's genius.
<P>

But the real reason is the two decades he spent....to promote the lingua franca so that they could seamlessly swap large amounts of information 
regardless of its type, the users location, the variety of computer hardware or software, or whether the medium was wired, satellite or mobile communications.
The result was adoption of the TC/IP. the Transmission Control Internet 
Protocol.
<P>
As a Stanford professor, and then a key manager at the government-funded Defense Department's Advanced Research Projects Agency ,a co-developer of electronic mail at MCI Communications Corp., independent researcher, and finally president of the Internet Society.
<P




  

</FONT>
