<IMG SRC="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/images/pstaricn.gif" align="left"><H1>The HELP Homepage</H1>
Note that this section is still under development.  The list below contains proposed areas for HELP.  If you have suggestions, send us a <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">comment</A>.<BR CLEAR=ALL>
click on the area you need help with:
<FONT SIZE=+1>
<DL>
<P>

<B>World Wide Web<P></B><P>
The World Wide Web, or WWW, uses a graphics intensive application.The WWW is now a massive network of files. 
<P>
<B>Background information </B>written by Web Weaver, Evan Ramstead,
Associated Press: reprinted in the Ann Arbor News, November 9, 1995
<P>
Comments made by Tim Berners- Lee, developer of the WWW, during a recent interview at this office at the MIT Laboratory for Computer Science: On the 
original program that formed the basis for the technical standards that now define the WWW.
<P>
"When I arrived (at CERN in 1980) ..I found people who were collaborating in all sorts of informal ways.  Before that, I'd been playing with programs to represent data as random association, as random links.  In 1980, simply to keep track of what was going on, the people I'd been introduced to, the software they'd written, the hardware they'd designed; all these interconnections, I wrote a program for myself that allowed random associations.
<P>
<B> Hypertext (HTTP)</B><P>
Background information from Michigan Today
June 8, 1996
Information Technology
In 1965, a computer scientist Theodor Nelson conceived the "hypertext" technology that 30 years later became the system which Internet users of the WWW can point their cursors and click their mouses to move instantly from document to word to picture to document in any combination.
<P>
From that success, Nelson embarked on a visionary project he calls Xanadu, a universal electronic library and publishing system that would link every book, movie, poem, song and software program ever written.



</FONT>
