<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Introdution</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>Welcome</H1> <IMG SRC="jgreden.gif" ALIGN="left" HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5> 
<A HREF="/web/psi/mtg/gredenBib.htm">  John Greden, M.D.,</A> Professor and Chair<P>

	In order to best address you, I sought to place myself in the position of an applicant, and three fundamental questions immediately surfaced.  Why choose psychiatry?  Why now?  Why Michigan?<P>

	Why choose psychiatry?  Despite sentiments to the contrary, I cannot imagine a more exciting time to enter this specialty.  There is growing recognition that mental illnesses are prevalent, reliably diagnosed, treatable, and that psychiatrists possess unique expertise in developing, teaching and delivering effective interventions.  A staggering 20 percent of people in this country will develop a mood disorder sometime in their lives.  Nearly 30 percent struggle with substance abuse problems.  A quarter of the general population must cope with anxiety, panic and related diseases.  In responding to such disorders, psychiatry has protected the humanitarian aspects that have traditionally been integral to all of medicine, has successfully incorporated new technologies without being overwhelmed by them, and has developed an impressive array of treatment advances.  Quite simply, most of our patients get better.  For anyone in the health sciences, there are few things more gratifying.  Perhaps this explains why physicians changing specialties tend to enter psychiatry more than any other field.  I have never been surprised by these data; I know psychiatry's pleasures.<P>

	Why now?  Timing is everything, and health care reform has revealed that mental health and substance abuse services must be better disseminated, better integrated and better reimbursed if we are to improve quality of life and reduce overall health care costs.  These viewpoints portend good things to come for psychiatric services - long overdue - but to be enjoyed.  Sadly, advances in psychiatric diagnosis and treatment have not enjoyed widespread distribution.  Most people with mental health problems continue to present to family physicians, gynecologists, pediatricians, ambulatory clinics, geriatric and cancer centers or other points of entry, and too many still go undiagnosed and untreated.  It is there where effective interventions must be introduced.  It is there that psychiatrists must share and distribute their expertise.  Psychiatry is facing a unique opportunity to influence and improve the entire healthcare delivery system.  Why enter psychiatry now?  Timing is everything...<P>

	Why Michigan?  In this medical center, the special role of psychiatrists in educating and consulting with primary care clinicians has already been recognized and prioritized.  We have been entrusted by our institution with the responsibility of coordinating mental health, and our faculty and residents are engaged in numerous projects, e.g., those which address psychiatric aspects of cardiac rehabilitation (in our Preventive Cardiology/Med-Sport operation), breast cancer (in our Cancer Center), geriatric depression (in our Geriatric Center), and substance abuse (in Family Practice).  These and other projects add new dimensions and fulfillment to the traditional rewards of psychiatry.  Because of psychiatry's changing nature, future-oriented applicants will wisely seek training in programs that are well-balanced.  While sometimes difficult to define, "well-balanced" programs must prioritize education; in this university, education holds highest priority.  Well-balanced programs must have broad, diverse, clinical delivery systems; we have them.  And, well-balanced programs must have a solid research base; this is an area in which Michigan excels.  At each of these levels - education, clinical, research - the University, the Medical Center and the Department are among the nation's leaders.  Our own special expertise has been in delineating molecular mechanisms that cause stress, linking neuroendocrine and neuropeptide dysregulation with clinical features, formulating new strategies for brain imaging, identifying predictors of adolescent suicide and developing new pharmacologic and psychotherapeutic treatments for mood, anxiety, eating, developmental, substance abuse and other types of disorders.  Our studies are varied, our investigators talented, and our facilities superb.  In this climate, residents at Michigan learn that "research" is not a mystical or frightening word but, rather, a fun part of a complete education and, simply, a tool for developing a new generation of clinicians.<P>

	Perhaps most importantly, the Department prioritizes people.  Residency education directors, departmental chairs and academicians do face frustrations; they also enjoy ample rewards.  Among them, the academic and personal development of residents and faculty rank highest.  This is an exciting time to study psychiatry, and the University of Michigan is an exciting place to do so.  <HR>
Continue on with the <A HREF="/web/UMpsych/brochure/intro.htm">introduction</A>.
<P>
