<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Introduction</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>Introduction</H1>
- Randolph Nesse, M.D., Professor and Associate Chair for Education and Academic Affairs<IMG ALIGN="Bottom" SRC="rnesse.gif"><P>

	An education program, if it works, changes those who participate, as you know only too well from your experience in medical school.  A psychiatry residency, if it does its job, even more fundamentally alters your view of human nature, and thus, your own life.  But psychiatry residency programs differ substantially in their basic approach to understanding people.  Are you finding it difficult to choose a program?  Good!  You recognize that you face a major decision.  <P>

	The temptation is to remedy uncertainty by trying to pick one point of view now and seeking a program that is based on that perspective.  Such premature closure is the enemy of wisdom.  You are not now in a good position to decide among the various perspectives in psychiatry.  Furthermore, psychiatry is changing rapidly.  <P>

	Yes, we now, finally, can reliably define mental disorders, we are beginning to find the brain mechanisms responsible for vulnerability to some disorders, and we can offer new treatments that seem like miracles to patients who have suffered for decades.  But we are just beginning to use this knowledge to understand what mental disorders are.  Can the human organism be designed so badly that 20 percent of women have an anxiety disorder and 14 percent have depression?  What are these emotions, and how are they regulated?  Why do people form attachments, and why do they so often go awry?  Why on earth do we have psychodynamic defenses that distort our view of our own inner lives, to say nothing of transferences that disrupt our relationships?  Are we really better off seeing the world accurately, or is distortion useful? Is it wise to use drugs to relieve ordinary bad feelings?  <P>

	While psychiatry is just beginning to acquire a fundamental understanding-comparable to what physiology provides for the rest of medicine - of how the mind works, the profession is able to define and treat a wide variety of mental disorders and even discover the factors that predispose individuals to certain disorders.  The answers are coming.  To prepare yourself, and perhaps to make your own contribution to this new knowledge, you need to acquire both solid clinical fundamentals and the tools you need to continue to learn.  <P>

	Some skills and knowledge are fundamental.  A psychiatrist must learn, first of all, to listen, and to understand what is beneath the surface.  Then, he or she must learn to observe and understand emotional reactions that make it difficult for others to relate to some patients, how to offer hope even in the midst of a realistic assessment, how to establish an alliance with the part of the patient that wants to change, and how to gently challenge the patient to do frightening things.  And, of course, he or she must learn neuroanatomy, neurophysiology, and psychopharmacology, and how to diagnose and treat patients with every disorder and all existing pharmacologic, behavioral and psychotherapeutic technologies.  These fundamentals provide the foundation for a lifetime of satisfying practice and further learning.  <P>

	Attention to such basic principles seems sometimes to be overshadowed by preoccupation with health care reform and the financing of medical care.  Some bureaucrats would like to pretend that our diagnoses are clear-cut, that our treatments can always be well-defined, that outcome can be readily measured.  They are quite right to demand accountability, and our new efforts to provide it will improve our profession.  But these forces have led some to imagine that psychiatry can be done from a cookbook, that general physicians can practice it just as well as psychiatrists, that treating psychiatric disorders is easy.  This is a delusion that will not last long.  <P>

	Psychiatry is not easy.  Providing the highest quality treatment requires years of experience even after completing a top-quality training program.  The resulting skill and knowledge will be recognized and valued.  The suffering of mental disorders is so severe and so common that people will always seek out clinicians who know as much as is   possible about a disorder, who can blend drug and behavioral and psychotherapeutic treatments, who have treated thousands of patients, and who are dedicated to providing comprehensive individualized treatment that cures as many as possible, and comforts the rest.  Caring for people who have depression, anxiety, schizophrenia, substance abuse and relationship problems is an ancient calling that is fast becoming far more effective and satisfying.  <P>

	If you want to learn how to help people with psychiatric disorders and you want to prepare yourself for a lifetime of continued learning, we would like to teach you.  
<HR>
