<HEAD>
<TITLE>A tradition of excellence</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>A tradition of excellence</H1>
<P>

The country's first professor of nervous and mental diseases - William Herdman - was appointed at the University of Michigan in 1888. The first university-affiliated psychiatric facility in the United States - the State Psychopathic Hospital at the University of Michigan - was opened in 1906, and Albert Barrett came to Michigan to become the director and the country's first full-time professor of psychiatry. From the very beginning, the emphasis was on training and research in a patient care setting.<P>

<H2>1930s</H2>

Raymond Waggoner, M.D., Sc.D., began a 33-year term as professor and chairman of psychiatry at the University of Michigan in 1937.  One of his first tasks after he became chairman was to urge the state to rewrite the laws governing the treatment of the mentally ill.  As a result, Public Act 85 was passed and in 1939, a new facility - the Neuropsychiatric Institute - replaced the Psychopathic Hospital. Admissions to the Institute increased, and yearly outpatient visits and consultations grew within the decade from 500 to more than 8,000.  Currently, there are 46,200 outpatient visits and 1,370 inpatient visits annually.  Dr. Waggoner still makes the trip from his Ann Arbor home to his office in the Riverview Building and remains active in community affairs.  <P>

<H2>1940s</H2>

After World War II and in response to the need for psychiatric treatment for veterans, the University of Michigan opened a special 50-bed inpatient unit, the Veterans Readjustment Center, which was the first facility of its kind. Here, the Department introduced intensive individual psychotherapy in an open-door, cooperative group setting allowing patients to maintain direct contact with family and community; this treatment approach became the prototype for similar programs throughout the United States. <P>

<H2>1950s</H2>

In 1955, the Mental Health Research Institute (MHRI) was formed to conduct basic research investigations into the causes and mechanisms of psychiatric disorders with a focus on brain-behavior relationships. It was one of the first institutes of its kind and quickly established a reputation for excellence.  <P>

<H2>1960s</H2>

The Department's residency program grew into one of the largest and best known in the country, with an increasing emphasis on child psychiatry. <P>

<H2>1970s</H2>

When Albert Silverman assumed the chair in 1970, he was committed to intensifying and refining patient care and academic programs. He recruited faculty active in psychopharmacology and psychoneuroendocrinology, balancing the Department's psychotherapeutic sophistication with the research sophistication of MHRI.  MHRI's creative researchers studied several neuropeptide systems, including endorphins and CRF, and plasticity, ensuring an aggressive basic science resource for creating new clinical knowledge.  Dr. Silverman also recruited in the area of neuropsychology, setting the stage for research, teaching and clinical services in this important component to the neuroscience area.  This interface with basic science set the stage for later work in PET and other neurologic inquiry.  <P>

<H2>1980s</H2>

In 1985, John Greden, M.D., became chair.  He has created an environment in which research, education, clinical excellence and collegial interaction are primary values.<P>

The Department steadily expanded its research activities, from basic studies of the brain mechanisms of stress and depression to positron emission tomography studies, treatment tools and new methods for providing behavior therapy. In 1987, the Department successfully competed for a national research center focusing on alcoholism and aging, and the University of Michigan Alcohol Research Center (UMARC) was established.    <P>

<H2>The 1990s and beyond</H2>

All of these developments have created unique strengths for the Department. In education and research, our diversity of sophisticated viewpoints offers a rich educational environment.  On a single patient care unit, there are often psychotherapists, family therapists and psychopharmacologists working together. Many faculty members transcend theoretical boundaries to offer an integrated perspective. Other areas of particular excellence include:<P>
<UL>
<LI>Psychobiological expertise - In both psychopharmacology and psychoneuroendocrinology the Department is recognized for its national leadership.<P>

<LI>Psychodynamic psychotherapy training - The Department emphasizes face-to-face interpretive work ranging from brief to long-term psychodynamically oriented intensive therapy in both adult and child/adolescent programs. <P>

<LI>Research and academic productivity - Clinical and basic psychiatric research at the University of Michigan is abundant and growing. <A HREF="mhri.htm">The Mental Health Research Institute</A> (MHRI), The <A HREF="substanc.htm#UMARC">University of Michigan Alcohol Research Center</A> (UMARC), inpatient research programs, the neuroscience program and the Positron Emission Tomography (PET) Research Center promote close collaboration between the basic sciences and clinical research. A specialized research track provides selected residents with training and supervised research experiences in a very diverse set of venues.<P>

<LI>Child psychiatry training - A large portion of the Department's staff and resources are committed to child and adolescent psychiatry. <P>

<LI>The Department has specialized expertise in several subspecialties including mood, anxiety and related disorders, schizophrenia, substance abuse, geropsychiatry, sleep disorders, consultation/liaison, mental health care organization, outcome studies and the application of computers in psychiatry.<P>
</UL>
<HR>
Go back to <A HREF="about.htm">About the Program</A>.<BR>
