</PRE>
<HR>
Return to the <A HREF="./">Table of Contents</A>
<P>
Return to the <A HREF="/web/UMpsych/">Psychiatry Home Page</A>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="PGY1">PGY I</A></H2><P>

	During the Categorical* First Year (PGY I), residents spend four months providing direct primary medical care, as required by the American Board of Psychiatry and Neurology.  Psychiatric residents take the same medical rotations as residents in the University of Michigan departments of Medicine, Pediatrics and Family Practice. We also offer residents the opportunity to select Family Medicine at one of our affiliated hospitals, Oakwood Hospital.   Residents also spend two months on Neurology, four months on Inpatient Psychiatry and one month on Emergency Psychiatry.  The Emergency Psychiatry experience allows residents to understand community mental health resources through a very active interaction with community mental health workers and programs.  One month of elective time may be arranged in almost any area of medicine that meets the special needs or interests of the resident. <P>

	The inpatient psychiatry experiences in the PGY-I year are spent at the Ann Arbor Veterans Administration Medical Center, a Dean's Committee teaching hospital near the medical campus.  All attending staff are faculty members of the University of Michigan Medical School. <P>
Return to <A HREF="#index">Rotation Schedule</A>
<HR>
 <H2><A NAME="PGY2">PGY II</A></H2><P>

	PGY II rotations are divided between eight months on the University Hospital adult psychiatry inpatient units and four months at either the Veterans Administration Medical Center or Chelsea Arbor Treatment Center, focusing on substance abuse.  Small case loads, intensive supervision and teaching, and many ongoing research projects create an academic atmosphere that facilitates both excellent patient care and education.  In addition to learning basic inpatient psychiatry, rotations on specialty units allow development of specific skills for the treatment of affective disorders, schizophrenia, personality disorders, substance abuse and eating disorders; residents also acquire technical skills in the administration of electroconvulsive therapy (ECT).  At the beginning of the year, a special series of seminars quickly provides a working knowledge of psychiatric diagnoses and basic principles of psychological and pharmacological treatment.<P>

	Early in the PGY II year, each resident begins a supervised, long-term intensive psychotherapy outpatient case which continues throughout the residency.  A special clinical seminar and individual supervision allow rapid development of psychotherapeutic skills.<P>

	The Departmental treatment philosophy emphasizes the importance of continuity of care.  Our Continuing Treatment Program makes it possible for residents to follow a wide variety of additional outpatients throughout the residency.<P>

	PGY II residents take night call approximately four times each month to provide coverage for the inpatient units and, with a community mental health worker, for the psychiatry emergency room. Back-up is provided by a senior resident or fellow, and a faculty member.  Each morning, there is a teaching and patient care coordinating meeting to discuss cases seen the night before.  <P>
Return to <A HREF="#index">Rotation Schedule</A>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="PGY3">PGY III</A></H2><P>

	The third year is devoted to learning adult outpatient psychiatry.  Treatment of ongoing PGY II cases is continued in the rotation to Outpatient Clinic.<P>

	Most new cases are seen first with a faculty supervisor.  Videotaped evaluations are reviewed during a seminar as part of this experience.  There are also opportunities for experience in group therapy, marital and family therapy, eating disorders, geriatrics, depressive disorders, community psychiatry, schizophrenia, behavioral medicine and other outpatient specialties. During part of each week, residents evaluate and treat children of all ages and with varied clinical problems. <P>
Return to <A HREF="#index">Rotation Schedule</A>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="PGY4">PGY IV</A></H2><P>

	Fourth-year residents spend six months with the Adult Consultation Liaison Psychiatry Program. The other half of the year is elective time which may be used to continue treatment of selected patients, perform administrative responsibilities, pursue special areas of interest or conduct research.<P>

	Upon completion of the general residency, fellowship opportunities exist within the Department for those graduates interested in additional specialized training.  The Department was one of the early leaders in the country in establishing subspecialty fellowship training.  Options include programs in affective disorders, child and adolescent psychiatry, consultation liaison psychiatry, anxiety disorders, sleep disorders, brain imaging, geriatrics, managed care, schizophrenia, substance abuse and eating disorders.<P>
Return to <A HREF="#index">Rotation Schedule</A>
<P>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="curriculum">Core curriculum</A></H2><P>

The core curriculum consists of a series of didactic seminars beginning in the PGY II year and continuing throughout the residency.  It is broad in scope, and major topics are presented in an advancing sequence throughout the residency.  More specialized subjects and electives are scheduled to coordinate with corresponding clinical rotations.  These comprehensive seminars cover a wide range of material during the three years including the following sequences:<P>

<PRE>
Descriptive Psychiatry and Psychopharmacology
Neuroscience			
Mood Disorders					
Personality Disorders				
Anxiety Disorders					
Geriatric Psychiatry				
Psychosomatics					  
Substance Related Problems
Ethics
Schizophrenia & Other Psychotic Disorders
Trauma
Electroconvulsice Therapy (ECT)

Forensic Psychiatry				
Community Psychiatry				
Cross Cultural Psychiatry				
Administrative Psychiatry
Managed Care in Psychiatry

Basic Concepts in Psychoanalytic Psychotherapy, Part I and II
Implications of Child Development Theory for Adult Psychotherapy
Psychopathology
Special Topics in Psychotherapy
Object Relations, Part I and II
Cognitive Therapy
Behavioral Therapy
Family Therapy
Group Therapy
Integration of Therapies
Treatment Selection

Practicalities
Ethology
Evolutionary Biology
Evelutionary Perspective on Psychiatry
Research Methodolgy
Issues of Gender & Sexuality
AIDS

Childhood Disorders
Development Psychology
Psychosis:
   Anxiety & Ric Disorders
   Disruptive Behavior Disorders
   Child Sexual Abuses
   Mental Retardation
Infant Development
Child Psychotherapy
Cognitive/Behavioral
   (Family, Group, Dynamic)
Psychopharmacology:
   Educational Assessment & Treatment
   Consultation/Liason


</PRE>
<P>

PGY I residents attend a separate series of didactic seminars and grand rounds coordinated with the Veterans Administration Medical Center inpatient psychiatry rotations.<P>

Department-wide major conferences, grand rounds or the invited speaker series occur  from 10:30 a.m. to noon every Wednesday.
