<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Consultation and General Psychiatry</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>Consultation and General Psychiatry Division</H1><P>
Director - Thomas Carli, M.D.<P>


<IMG SRC="/web/images/carli_.gif" ALIGN="left" HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5>


<P>
The size and diversity of the Consultation and General Psychiatry Division is one of its biggest strengths, notes Thomas Carli, M.D., Director of the Consultation and General Psychiatry Division.<P>

	"It is a major asset that allows us to have diverse clinics, treatment modalities and specialists," he says. "We are part of one of the top programs in the country in terms of resources and quality."<P>

	The clinics that serve the Medical Center and the community include the following:<P>
<UL>
<LI>Emergency Services and Urgent Care<P>

<LI>Consultation Liaison to the University of Medical Center, which offers programs in inpatient adult and child medicine and surgery, family practice, cancer, neurology, preventive cardiology, HIV, transplant, genetic predictive testing, rheumatology, primary care and other specialty services.<P>

<LI>Geropsychiatry<P>

<LI>Anxiety Disorders<P>

<LI>Mood Disorders<P>

<LI>Couples and Family Therapy<P>

<LI>Psychopharmacology<P>

<LI>Short-Term General Treatment<P>

<LI>Continuing Care<P>

<LI>Psychodynamic Psychotherapy Training Clinic<P>
</UL>
The Division sees "an ethnic and culturally diverse population with a full spectrum of problems - from serious mental illness to situational problems," says Dr. Carli. <P>

	"We treat everyone from graduate students who can't finish their Ph.D.'s, to couples in crisis, to seriously ill adults who have failed all past treatment," he says. "Because of the enormous breadth of our services, we're able to provide state-of-the-art treatment and diagnoses for a wide range of problems, and we do it in a time-efficient, cost-effective way."<P>

	The Division is the principle training site in residency for outpatient mental health services, so educational goals are of primary concern. Aims include providing training in biopsychosocial diagnosis and treatment, various psychotherapy modalities and the combination of these modalities with medications. <P>

	There is special emphasis, Dr. Carli notes, on treatment matching, shorter-term treatment and managed care.<P>

	"When residents complete their rotations with us, they leave solidly grounded in a number of areas, including psychobiology, psychodynamics, cognitive behavioral treatments and family systems," says Dr. Carli. The Director likes to make the distinction that the program offers both training - an apprenticeship, of sorts - and education, including didactic sessions and seminars. <P>

<H2><A NAME="CL">Consultation-Liaison For senior residents</A></H2><P>

	Current trends indicate that, in the future, psychiatrists will be working less in private practice settings and increasingly in collaboration with, and consulting to, primary care physicians in the care of these physicians' patients with primary and secondary psychiatric illnesses.<P>

	The Consultation-Liaison experience includes a six-month rotation during the PGY III or IV years with both inpatient and outpatient components.   Residents learn the special skills of consulting with other physicians regarding the diagnosis and treatment of an array of psychiatric problems in medical and surgical patients at the University of Michigan Medical Center.  The framework is one of comprehensive medicine, with attention to the biological, intra-psychic and social factors that interact to produce symptoms and influence recovery.  Supervision includes bedside rounds three times each week.  This format allows psychiatry residents and faculty members the invaluable opportunity of observing each other interacting with patients.<P>

	The didactic teaching program includes, <A HREF="/web/UMpsych/announce/seminar.htm"> Seminars in Consultation Psychiatry</A>,  a seminar covering basic topics encountered in consultation work, presented by program faculty at the beginning of each rotation. For the remainder of the rotation, faculty and residents participate together in a weekly consultation/psychosomatic medicine journal club.<P>

	In addition, the psychosomatic and behavioral medicine core curriculum seminar is presented annually by program faculty, combining theoretical perspectives and basic science with treatment modalities such as hypnosis and biofeedback.<P>

	Consultation-Liaison faculty are involved in research pertaining to neuropsychiatry and psychoneuroendocrinology, such as cutting edge clinical research on the effects of steroids on brain structure and function.   Residents are encouraged to participate in these and other clinical studies at the interface of medicine and psychiatry.  <P>

<H2><A NAME="LGT">Psychodynamic Psychotherapy Training Clinic</A></H2><P>

	Psychodynamic psychotherapy in the training program is a specific treatment modality. This clinic offers residents a range of experiences in the realm of psychological interventions.<P>

	The core experience is open-ended treatment that is introspective in approach and interpretive in strategy, aiming at producing major shifts in personality organization. Therapy is conducted two or three times a week and is supervised weekly.  Each resident learns to provide individual, insight-oriented psychodynamic psychotherapy, and through either experience or observation, is exposed to conjoint therapy, group therapy and non-interpretive psychotherapies.  The program covers a three-year period.  The didactic component is offered as part of the existing core curriculum with the addition of a continuous case seminar led by the clinic director. <P>

	This form of psychological intervention and the learning process inherent in using it are essential to clinical development.  For those interested in psychotherapy the training provides a sound basis for continued learning; for the generalist, it is an opportunity to learn, experientially, about the inner life of patients, the process of healing and the role of the therapist as a healing agent.<P>

	The clinic is part of the collaborative agreement between the Department of Psychiatry and the Michigan Psychoanalytic Institute.  Supervisors are trained analysts who are adjunct faculty in the Department.<P>
<HR>
Continue on to learn more about the <A HREF="gero.htm">Geropsychiatry Division</A>.
