<HEAD>
<TITLE>Mood and Anxiety Disorders</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>Mood, Anxiety and Related Disorders Division</H1>
Director - Oliver G. Cameron, M.D., Ph.D.<P>
		Oliver G. Cameron, M.D., Ph.D.,  doesn't hesitate when asked why he chose to focus on the study of mood, anxiety and related disorders:  the sheer number of cases in the general population is the overriding reason.<P>

		"These disorders cover at least two-thirds of all serious psychiatric disorders," says Dr. Cameron. "These areas are very important from a public health and epidemiologic point of view."<P>

		The Division's faculty members evaluate and treat adults on an inpatient and outpatient basis with anxiety and affective disorders, including chronic depression, manic disorders,  panic and generalized anxiety, and obsessive/compulsive disorders. The Division is closely linked with the Mental Health Research Institute, the Veterans Administration Medical Center and the Anxiety and Depression Program within the Child and Adolescent Service.<P>

		The Department of Psychiatry is in the process of combining the mood and anxiety programs into one division, a logical step, says Dr. Cameron. "In the past, people compartmentalized patients, but psychiatric research has demonstrated that if you have one of these disorders, you often have another. Combining these is a strong acknowledgment that such problems go together and mean benefits in all ways - research, education and patient care. It's a move that makes a lot of sense."<P>

		Research is a crucial component of the program, says Dr. Cameron. "It's very easy and highly encouraged for residents to participate in research. Ongoing projects are all around them. Research is being conducted on the people they are taking care of." <P>

		Dr. Cameron notes that much has already been learned in this area of study. "Depression has been highly researched for 25 years and anxiety for 15 years. A lot is known so there are very provocative leads."  The extensive study has led to extremely successful management of both disorders.  If left untreated, these illnesses can lead to the inability to work, handle family situations or manage financial issues.  In depression, suicide is always a concern. <P>

		"The real problem is serious dysfunction in all realms of one's life," he says. "I get a great deal of satisfaction and enjoyment out of helping people turn things around."<P>
<HR>
