<HEAD>
<TITLE>Neuropsychology Division</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>Neuropsychology Division</H1><P>
Director - Stanley Berent, Ph.D.<P>
	Stanley Berent, Ph.D., Director of the Neuropsychology Division, and his colleagues hope to add years to the lives of Alzheimer's patients. Positron emission tomography and psychometrics are utilized to detect subtle changes in cognition and the brain - years before such changes are diagnosable clinically - that indicate dementia is imminent.<P>

	"It is important to find the disease as early as possible, because some of the new medicines only work when dementia is in its first stages," says Dr. Berent. "This work might redefine how we diagnose the disease."<P>

	Such ground-breaking research certainly isn't found everywhere, but it occurs quite regularly in the Neuropsychology Division. Studies focus on aging and dementia and various neurologic illnesses and how these disorders interplay with other psychiatric illnesses. <P>

	Research, though, is only one aspect of the program.  Neuropsychologists and a variety of students, residents, graduate students and post-doctoral fellows manage 3,000 inpatients and outpatients each year. The staff sees children and adults and spends much of the time diagnosing whether problems are neurological or psychological, says Dr. Berent. They diagnose dementia, degenerative motor disorders, learning disabilities, hyperactivity and a host of other concerns. They also are investigating the effects of environmental toxins on cognition and other behaviors.<P>

	Experts provide short-term and family counseling and make referrals for further diagnosis and treatment. Neuropsychologists work closely with most departments within the University of Michigan, including Nuclear Medicine, Internal Medicine, Surgery, Occupational Health and Psychology. <P>

	The University Hospital and the Department of Psychiatry support an active postdoctoral training program in Psychology.  There are currently about a dozen fellows enrolled in this program, pursuing research and clinical training in neuropsychology, behavioral medicine and other areas of specialization.  These trainees and their faculty sponsors interact with residents and fellows in Psychiatry and present an important multidisciplinary component to the training program.<P>
<HR>
