<HEAD>
<TITLE>Schizophrenia Division</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>Schizophrenia Division</H1><P>
Director - Rajiv Tandon, M.D.<P>
	The Schizophrenia Division is unique, perhaps, because it is both a local community service and a nationally recognized clinical research program. Rajiv Tandon, M.D., Director of the Division, views schizophrenia as a "brain disease that causes enormous personal suffering" and the activities of the program reflect this viewpoint: while research focuses on elucidating the nature of brain abnormalities (structural, functional, chemical) in the disorder, clinical efforts are devoted to providing state-of-the-art treatments and developing newer, more effective treatments that improve the quality of life of patients afflicted with schizophrenia.  <P>

	The Division's faculty members, along with other staff, evaluate and treat adults with schizophrenia and other psychotic disorders on an 18-bed inpatient unit in the University of Michigan Hospital and in several outpatient settings. This includes the University-based outpatient clinic which principally provides expert consultations to other psychiatrists in the state and several community-based schizophrenia clinics, where more than 500 patients with various psychotic disorders receive treatment.  The Division has earned a reputation as an excellent community effort, in part because the Division's residents - under faculty supervision - work in local community mental health clinics, gaining valuable experience in community psychiatry and the treatment of the chronically mentally ill. In addition to individual awards of excellence, the Division has been recognized as a model program by the State Mental Health Association and the Alliance for the Mentally Ill. <P>

	Nationally, the Division is recognized as a center of research excellence. Research is extensive, and it examines every aspect of the nature of brain abnormalities in schizophrenia: structurally, using magnetic resonance imaging; functionally, using positron emission tomography (PET), electrophysiology and neuropsychology; and chemically, using PET, investigational medications, treatment and infusion studies.  While generating considerable empirical data, the Division emphasizes developing and testing theoretical constructs and hypotheses about the nature of schizophrenia. "Our field needs well-conceived models about the nature of schizophrenia that can explain much of what is known about the illness; research should focus on evaluating testable predictions of these models.  The meaning of data is at least as important as the addition of data," says Dr. Tandon.     <P>

	What draws residents is the true blending of research, clinical work and teaching that occur here. "We really believe these three missions are closely tied together," says Dr. Tandon. "Quality clinical care, cutting-edge meaningful research, and effective teaching are interdependent processes that drive one another.  We encourage residents to think critically and invite them to challenge our thinking."  Residents are also strongly encouraged to participate in research, and there are several opportunities for such research.  
<HR>
Continue on to the <A HREF="substanc.htm">Substance Abuse Division</A>.
