<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Substance Abuse Division</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>Substance Abuse Division</H1><P>
Director - Robert Zucker, Ph.D.<P>
	Substance abuse, and alcohol abuse/dependence, in particular, are tied to the fabric of everyday life and are, consequently, the most common of psychiatric disorders, notes Robert A. Zucker, Ph.D.,  Director of the Substance Abuse Division.  One in every four men and one in every nine women will, at some point in their lives, have an alcohol/drug abuse/dependence diagnosis.  The psychiatric problems are an intriguing puzzle, says Dr. Zucker, given comorbidity and substantial variations across different portions of the age span.  <P>

	The University of Michigan's Substance Abuse Division addresses these issues with a broad menu of activities that seeks to integrate clinical training with the generation of new knowledge by way of research.  Clinical training occurs both at the Chelsea Arbor Treatment Center and at the <A HREF="vamc.htm">Veterans Administration Medical Center program</A>.  <A NAME="Chelsea">Chelsea Arbor</A> is a joint venture of Chelsea Community Hospital and the University of Michigan Medical Center.  It operates under the direction of Kirk J. Brower, M.D., Executive Director and Associate Director for Clinical Activities within the Substance Abuse Division.  Chelsea Arbor offers outpatient, intensive outpatient, and residential treatment at the Kresge House in Chelsea; outpatient and intensive outpatient treatment programs also exist at an Ann Arbor site, and acute care treatment for detoxification occurs at Chelsea Community Hospital.  <P>

	If residents are interested in substance abuse research, the University of Michigan offers an exceptionally rich research environment, notes Dr. Zucker.  The institution has one of the nation's most active substance abuse agendas involving several projects within the Department and numerous additional studies in other areas of the university.  Faculty are closely linked to the University of Michigan Alcohol Research Center, which has as its primary focus the study of alcohol problems as related to aging.  Areas of research include:  Neuroimaging studies; testing of brief intervention programs in primary care sites; a study of the pharmacotherapy of alcoholism; and a high-risk etiologic study following one of the youngest at risk populations.<P>

	Residents may become increasingly involved in these research endeavors as the residency proceeds.  For those interested in pursuing a career in academic medicine, a nationally funded training grant currently allows research fellow appointments after the residency ends.  
<P>
<H2><A NAME="UMARC">University of Michigan Alcohol Research Center</A> (UMARC)</H2>

	In 1987, under a funding initiative of the National Institute of Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism (NIAAA), grant support was secured to establish the University of Michigan Alcohol Research Center (UMARC).  The Center's research theme was alcohol and aging, with a special focus on brain changes and clinical implications of chronic alcoholism on the aged and aging.  Over the years, since its inception, UMARC has expanded its developmental scope and research mission to include a number of other thematically connected research projects committed to understanding the etiology, course, clinical manifestations and health care consequences of chronic alcoholism.  These include the University of Michigan-Michigan State University (UM-MSU) Longitudinal Study on Alcoholism Etiology, as well as a series of studies on the consequences and costs of chronic alcoholic disorder.  UMARC's programs assess consequences of alcohol-aging interactions, focusing on alterations of brain metabolism, brain receptor binding, brain blood flow, cognition, sleep, and driving performance.  In addition, current clinical intervention studies include a study of screening and brief intervention for alcohol problems among older adults in primary care, and a study of serotonergic dysregulation in older alcoholics, combined with a pharmacologic trial.<P>

	UMARC serves as both a regional and national resource for intellectual exchange and training in alcohol, aging, neurosciences, developmental issues in  substance use disorders, and clinical intervention.  Five independent extramurally-funded projects have resulted from UMARC support.  In addition, the Center operates a NIAAA funded post-doctoral Clinical Research Training Grant for the training of post-residency psychiatrists and post-doctoral psychologists.<P>

	The Center also has a commitment to educate physicians and to mentor and train research scientists;  UMARC's research operations, as well as activities carried out in allied substance abuse treatment facilities, (see the description of <A HREF="vamc.htm">VAMC</A> activities),  form the basis for carrying out these commitments.	
<HR>
Continue on to the <A HREF="vamc.htm">Veterans Administraion Division</A>.
<P>
