<TITLE>Veterans Administration Division</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>Veterans Administration Division</H1><P>
Director - Alan Mellow, M.D., Ph.D.<P>
		The Ann Arbor Veterans Administration Medical Center (VAMC) is a Dean's Committee facility fully affiliated with the University of Michigan Medical School.  It is a 260-bed general medical and surgical hospital located near the U-M Medical Center campus.  All VAMC attending staff are faculty members of the U-M Medical School, and the VA services are fully integrated with the home departments of the U-M Medical Center.<P>

		The VA Psychiatry Service, led by Alan M. Mellow, M.D., Ph.D., has three overall goals:  to provide the highest quality psychiatric care possible to eligible veterans in the area;  to provide excellent educational experiences in psychiatry for residents, medical students, fellows and other trainees;  and to conduct first-rate basic and clinical psychiatric research relevant to the VA's patient population.  Clinical research is conducted with patients in both inpatient and outpatient settings.  The Psychobiology Laboratory has an active laboratory research program.<P>

		The inpatient psychiatry service treats patients who suffer from a variety of disorders including schizophrenia and other psychoses, mood disorders, dementia, post  traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), personality disorders and substance abuse.  In addition, there is a specialized inpatient team for geriatric patients, as well as an active electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) program.  There are two general psychiatry units - one with 16 beds, the other with 18 beds - and a 24-bed Substance Abuse Treatment Unit.  The service has active clinical and preclinical research in dementia, PTSD, schizophrenia and substance abuse.<P>

		Residents spend four months on one of the general psychiatry units during their first year in the program.  "We are the psychiatry training site for first-year residents - their first contact as physicians in psychiatry," says Dr. Mellow.  "We provide close supervision and are very available for beginning house staff."<P>

		Residents have primary responsibility for the care of six to nine patients at any given time and generally provide care for approximately 35 patients during their rotation.  They are assisted by third-year medical students in their primary care duties.  They also may participate in an inpatient geriatric psychiatry team.<P>

		Residents are supervised by both the attending physician in the unit and an off-unit staff physician.  The VAMC chief resident provides on-unit consultations and training in case formulation and treatment planning.  Training in pharmacotherapy,  individual short-term and supportive therapies, ECT and group psychotherapy is emphasized.  There is an ongoing didactic program for first year residents with seminars on the psychiatric interview, emergency psychiatry and the phenomenology and treatment of major psychiatric disorders.  A weekly grand rounds is held with all the staff and residents participating.  <P>

		In the PGY-II year, some residents have a substance abuse rotation with inpatient and outpatient components.  Other residents receive their substance abuse training at the <A HREF="substanc.htm#Chelsea">Chelsea Arbor Treatment Center</A>.  The emphasis is on management of mild to moderate detoxification, relapse prevention, substance abuse consultation on medical/surgical patients, dual diagnosis patients and patients with prior traumatic experiences.  Supervision in pharmacotherapy as well as group and individual therapy training is provided.  A weekly seminar complements the clinical experience.<P>

	In the PGY-IV year, residents return to the VAMC for part of their consultation/liaison psychiatry experience.  The rotation includes consultation in a nursing home as well as on busy medical/surgical units.  The team includes a psychologist, a psychology intern and a medical student, and the resident plays a supervisory role on the team.  Elective rotations are available on the ECT Service, Geropsychiatry Service and in the Outpatient Mental Health Clinic.	
<HR>
