<HEAD>
<TITLE>The University of Michigan</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>The University of Michigan</H1><P>

	The University of Michigan includes 17 schools and colleges, a full-time staff of approximately 17,000, a total enrollment of more than 50,900 and research volume in excess of $325 million.  Private gifts to the University during 1992-93 totaled more than $85 million.<P>

	The University's research and cultural resources are extensive.  The library system includes the Harlan Hatcher Graduate Library, the Undergraduate Library and 19 divisional libraries.  Other autonomous libraries on campus include the Law Library, the William L. Clements Library of Americana, Michigan Historical Collections/Bentley Historical Library, Kresge Business Administration Library and the Gerald R. Ford Presidential Library located on North Campus.  The Clements Library's collection of rare books makes it one of the most important centers of early American research in the country.  The building itself is an architectural gem, designed by the noted Albert Kahn.  The total University holdings number more than 6 million volumes.<P>

	University research facilities include the Ford Nuclear Reactor, the Dental Research Institute, the Electron Microbeam Analysis Laboratory, the Positron Emission Tomography Center, the Mental Health Research Institute, the Neuroscience Laboratories, the Middle English Dictionary Project, the Institute of Science and Technology, the Statistics Research Laboratory and the Radio Astronomy Antenna located northwest of Ann Arbor, and a telescope located at Kitt Peak, Arizona.<P>

	The University of Michigan intercollegiate athletic program has men's teams in football, basketball, baseball, track and field, swimming, hockey, wrestling, golf, cross country, gymnastics and tennis.  University of Michigan women compete in intercollegiate basketball, field hockey, swimming and diving, tennis, gymnastics, track, softball, golf, cross country and volleyball.  A member of the Big Ten Conference, the University of Michigan has an outstanding intercollegiate athletic record, including more football championships than any other Big Ten school.  The University also supports an extensive intramural and recreational sports program for men and women students, faculty and administrative staff.  Approximately 225 acres of land are devoted to athletics.  Among the facilities are the Michigan Stadium, (the nation's largest collegiate football stadium), Crisler Arena, Yost Ice Arena, the indoor track and tennis building and four indoor recreational sports facilities.  Staff members and employees are eligible for the University's intramural athletics program, which offers everything from team play in a variety of divisions to the use of squash, tennis, paddle ball and handball courts.  The University of Michigan has two championship-level golf courses open to staff and employees.<P>

	Each year, the University's Musical Society calendar includes more than 40 performances and include symphonic orchestras, renowned vocalists and instrumentalists, chamber ensembles, dance companies, jazz bands, theater and opera companies, and choral presentations, including the annual holiday performances of Handel's "Messiah".  Hill Auditorium has seen most of the century's great individual musical artists, orchestras and dance troupes perform on its stage.  Under the auspices of the University Musical Society, artists from literally all over the world-such as Leontyne Price, Luciano Pavarotti, James Galway, Isaac Stern and Leonard Bernstein-are continually brought to Ann Arbor.  The Society, which is located on the first floor of Burton Tower, also sponsors dance and musical events in the Power Center for the Performing Arts and in the auditorium of the Rackham Building.  Each year the Musical Society brings world-renowned artists and orchestras to the campus.  The Power Center, along with the Lydia Mendelssohn Theater in the Michigan League, hosts plays and musicals.  Hill Auditorium also annually presents the four-day May Festival.<P>

	Only five minutes from the University Hospital is the Ruthven Exhibit Museum which houses the University planetarium, as well as fine paleontology, zoology and anthropology collections.  The visual arts are evident in a number of small galleries across the campus and in the University's Museum of Art, a spacious, cool and contemplative place that uses natural light to present the works of Frankenthaler and Rauschenberg, among others.  Some excellent nineteenth century landscapes and portraits are also part of the permanent collection.  For those interested in classical periods, the Kelsey Museum, devoted to ancient and medieval archeology,  displays a large collection of artifacts from Egypt and North Africa.  The Arboretum bordering the Medical Center is a valued place to escape for a brief respite on a busy day.  The Matthaei Botanical Garden, to the east of the city, has a lush indoor garden and extensive outdoor walking trails.
<HR>
