<HEAD>
<TITLE>Ann Arbor</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>Ann Arbor</H1>

	Ann Arbor is an attractive town of more than 100,000 people located on the banks of the Huron River in southeastern Michigan. The appreciation of Ann Arbor's attractiveness does not stem from local loyalty alone: in a number of surveys conducted by magazines and outside firms during the past several years, Ann Arbor has consistently been named as one of the nation's 10 best places to live.<P>

	Probably no city of its size elsewhere in the United States and, perhaps, the world, can offer the range of diversions available in Ann Arbor. Some of Ann Arbor's attractions are sponsored by the University of Michigan, such as the Botanical Gardens, the Arboretum, Medieval Festival and many cultural events. Others are unrelated to the University, like the Farmer's Market and the Ya'soo Greek Festival. Still others are joint ventures, such as the Summer Arts Festival. Ann Arbor is a regular stop on the touring route of topflight artists, musicians, theater companies and lecturers.<P>

	The largest community in Washtenaw County, as well as the county seat, Ann Arbor is about 40 miles west of Detroit and covers an area of slightly more than 23 square miles.<P>

	Almost from its founding in 1823, Ann Arbor has been the home of the University of Michigan; it has evolved into an internationally known center of academic, research and cultural excellence. <P>

<H2>Living</H2><P>

Families are attracted by the city's highly regarded public school system and its various recreational facilities including numerous parks spread across 2,000 acres, biking paths and walking trails, swimming pools, ice rinks, softball facilities, and golf courses. <P>

Housing accommodations span the range from the University's dormitories, apartments and married student housing to gracious homes in the wooded hills along the Huron. There are several attractive subdivisions within the city and nearby, and a wide variety of rental residences is available. Ann Arbor was among the first communities to adopt and apply a fair housing ordinance.<P>

Ann Arborites are extremely conscious and proud of their history and have supported a movement to restore the downtown area and the Old West Side. Office buildings have been sandblasted, cleaned and painted and many older homes renovated and decorated. When the city decided it needed a new downtown firehouse, the original red brick one - long a landmark - became a children's museum. The old train depot is now a restaurant, furnished with the original waiting room benches, baggage cart and other memorabilia.<P>

<H2>Restaurants and coffee houses</H2><P>

There is probably nothing more inviting in downtown Ann Arbor than the delicious scents of the city's array of tantalizing restaurants. From the fine dining of Moveable Feast to the casual camaraderie of Casey's Tavern, there truly is a choice for every diner. <P>

Along with the hundreds of eateries and restaurants, there are scores of coffee houses featuring every type of gourmet coffee and other brewed beverages, not to mention a host of delectable baked goods to enjoy over a good book and a steaming cup of java.<P>

<H2>Cultural Events</H2><P>

In addition to the presentations sponsored by the University Musical Society, there are plenty of free and low-cost events available to residents and visitors.  The University's School of Music sponsors hundreds of concerts and recitals each year, at no cost to the audience.  Musicians may audition for the Ann Arbor Symphony and theatrically inclined individuals can pick from a wide range of local groups, including the Gilbert and Sullivan Society and the Ann Arbor Civic Theater.  Theater lovers who do not share the urge to get up on stage can attend the performances of the University Players, Ensemble Theatre Company and community organizations including the Purple Rose Theatre in nearby Chelsea.<P>

Of special interest to serious movie-goers is the Ann Arbor Film Festival.  For six days each spring, the Festival screens hundreds of "experimental" films, produced by independent artists in the United States and abroad.  It is the oldest and largest event of its type in the world.<P>

 Ann Arbor also has, through the University of Michigan Office of Major Events, rocked with the sounds of Bruce Springsteen and Fleetwood Mac, and cooled down with Herbie Hancock and Ella Fitzgerald.<P>

The Ann Arbor Art Fair (actually three fairs at once), held each July, brings crafts people from all over North America to the city's streets.  Booths filled with pottery, paintings and other works are set up on South and East University, Maynard and Main Streets.  The Fair has become a festival in recent years, complete with mime shows, rock bands and strolling sidewalk musicians.  It's one of the things that makes summer life in Ann Arbor a genuine pleasure. <P>

<H2>Day to day life</H2><P>

This really is no more than a brief introduction to Ann Arbor. Most of what newcomers learn to love about the town is not "event oriented," but is related simply to living here. Summer mornings at the Farmer's Market and Kerrytown, quiet walks in the Saginaw Forest, the excitement of football Saturdays, poking through dusty tomes in the city's many excellent bookshops - these are reasons why Ann Arbor is such a fine place in which to live.<P>

<H2>Ann Arbor tidbits</H2><P>

Ann Arborites are considered unusually affluent, with one of the highest average household incomes in the nation, ($66,228, putting Ann Arbor in 11th place in Places Rated Almanac.)<P>

Ann Arbor was tied for second place in the book, The 50 Best Places to Live and Retire in the U.S.<P>

Ann Arborites are more educated than people in most other cities; 94 percent have high school diplomas and two-thirds have four or more years of college, compared with one in five nationally. <P>

