<H1>Evolutionary Biology Series</H1><P>
<B>Evolutionary Theory and the Behavioral Sciences:</B> Colloqium sponsored by <BR>
The University fo Michigan Institute for Social Research and <BR>The Evolution and Human Behavior Program
<HR>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>The ISR Evolution and Human Adaptation Program will sponsor a series of
lectures and seminars in the months ahead.  The first will be a
mini-symposium on December 13 from 2:30-5:00 in Room 6050 ISR on "Desires
Designed for the Stone Age and the Diseases of Civilization: What
Strategies Can Protect Us?" If you would like to receive information about
this and other upcoming lectures on evolution and human behavior, please
send a note to nesse@umich.edu.  If you have a specific interest in work in
this area and would also like information about specialized seminars and
workgroups, please indicate that as well
<P>
<LI><B>Location:</B>            
ISR Evolution and Human Adaptation Program
<LI>December 13, 1996
<LI>Room 6050 ISR

<LI><B>Dated:November 27, 1995</B><P>
</UL>



2:30-3:00	Coffee, tea, conversation, and your choice of Stone-Age or
Electronic-Age snacks
<P>
3:00-3:15	Randolph Nesse, M.D., Professor, Department of Psychiatry;
Research Associate, ISR: Introduction and the problem of depression
<P>
3:15-3:35	Boyd Eaton, M.D., Clinical Associate Professor or Radiology;
Adjunct Associate Professor of Anthropology, Emory University: Medical
implications of old genes and new ways of life: Nutrition, exercise, and
reproduction.
<P>
3:35-3:45	Discussion
<P>
3:45-4:00	Beverly Strassmann, Ph.D., Assistant Professor, Department of
Anthropology, UM: Total lifetime menses in the absence of contraception-
The Effects on Disease
<P>
4:00-4:10	Discussion<P>
4:10-4:25	James Neel, Ph.D., M.D., Professor Emeritus, Departments of Human
Genetics and Internal Medicine, UM: Getting the most out of some very old
gene
<P>
4:25-4:30	Discussion
<P>
4:30-4:45	Alan Weder, M.D., Professor, Department of Internal Medicine, UM:
Hypertension and the modern environment
<P>
4:45-5:00	Discussion
<P>

Randolph M. Nesse, M.D.   The University of Michigan<P>
5057 I.S.R.,   P.O. Box 1248,  Ann Arbor, MI  48106 <P> 
(313) 647-7553   Fax: 647-7340  nesse@umich.edu 

