<BODY>

Reprinted from the American Journal Of Psychiatry.
153:7, pp. 861-869.<BR>
&copy;Copyright 1996 American Psychiatric Association<BR>
Reprinted by permission.

<P><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<P><B>Title: The Internet and The Future of Psychiatry</B></P>

<P>Authors: <A HREF="/web/UMpsych/staff/mhuang/">Milton P. Huang, MD</A> and <A HREF="/web/UMpsych/staff/nalessi/">Norman E. Alessi, MD</A></P>

<P>Dr. Huang is the fellow in the psychiatric informatics program.
</P>

<P>Dr. Alessi is the Chief Information Officer and Director of the
Division of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry.</P>

<P>Location: University of Michigan, Department of Psychiatry :
Address reprints to: Dr. Huang, 1500 E. Medical Center Drive, Box
0390, Ann Arbor MI, 48109-0390</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>Abstract:</B></P>

<I><P>The Internet is a rapidly growing communications resource that is
having a profound impact on areas such as business and government. It
is beginning to have an impact on medicine, and we anticipate it will
soon have significant effect on the field of Psychiatry.
Understanding the Internet and its implications is a complex task.
Objective: This article describes the components of the Internet and
how these work together to establish communication. Method: This
information is derived from review of relevant literature and direct
experience with using the Internet. Results: This description of
Internet structure provides an understanding of the potential impact
the Internet will have upon our field, especially in the areas of
education, clinical care, research, and administration. Conclusions:
The growth of the Internet and related information technologies is
inevitable with diverse technical and social implications. As
psychiatrists, we need to have a conceptual framework that will allow
us to continue and expand upon our professional mission in the
changing environment these technologies will create.</P></I>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>With the approach of the twenty first century, we are now witness
to major changes in technology and the impact these changes are
having upon our culture and work. Of these changes, one of the most
significant is that occurring in information technology, brought
about by advances in computers and networking. We are now able to
communicate faster, to more places and in more ways than ever before.
These potentials, however, bring with them unanticipated difficulties
as the speed and dispersion of information increase. Physicians are
now faced with an overwhelming set of new information demands and
information sources. Computerized patient records, third-party payer
databases, and artificial intelligence based diagnostic instruments
are just a small selection of possible examples. Any individual
facing such a deluge will fail in their attempt to navigate this
future without a framework for incorporating and organizing these
informational challenges.</P>

<P>The Internet is one particular example of such an information
challenge. This network of computers serves as a tool for instantly
communicating complex information between millions of people all over
the world. Its impact is reflected in its frequent discussion in the
popular press (1) as well as recent articles in medical journals such
as JAMA (2), The Journal of Nuclear Medicine (3), The Journal of the
American Academy of Dermatology (4), and Academic Medicine (5). It is
being used to distribute information about city traffic conditions,
stock market status, news, and government legislation. Over the last
year, over 20,000 businesses started marketing products through the
Internet (6) accounting for $50-200 million in commerce. Transactions
are expected to rise to $2.5 billion by 1998 (7). The Internet is
becoming a part of everyday life for everyone, and this presence is
extending into medicine as well. Radiologists are using the Internet
for providing interactive teaching experiences as well as CME credits
(8,9,10,11). Researchers are establishing shared databases of
information (12,13,14,15,16). Some clinicians are examining and
billing patients using video conferencing technology routed through
the Internet (17).</P>

<P>Such applications are now being extended into the field of
Psychiatry. The American Psychiatric Association is currently
investing $1.2 million to update its own capabilities (18). As these
networking technologies begin to play a role in our practice, it is
essential for all psychiatrists to have a conceptual framework for
understanding the many aspects of the Internet. This paper provides
such a framework, using a four layered model of Internet based
communication. We also explore some anticipated future applications
of the Internet, and end with a description of some of the challenges
that the use of this technology will create.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>HISTORY OF THE INTERNET</B></P>

<P>The Internet is a worldwide network of connected computers. Its
history is one of rapid, continuing growth (19,20,21). Started by the
US Department of Defense as a set of four computers hooked together
in 1969, the network grew to over one hundred in the decade after
that, and to over one thousand in the five years from 1980 to 1985.
Subsequent support from the National Science Foundation built an
academic communication backbone of higher and higher transmission
speeds. In the current stage of growth, independent commercial forces
have become the most rapidly expanding portion of the Internet (6).
The Internet now has over four million host computers with
approximately 20 to 30 million users. It is an international
phenomenon with connections in 90 different countries stretching from
Antarctica to Iceland to Zimbabwe (20, 22).</P>

<P>Although the above history of rapid growth describes the
connection of more and more computers, the Internet is more than just
a physical structure. An essential part of creating a network is
establishing common standards or protocols about how communication is
to take place. There is diversity in the types of computers, in the
types of wires, and in the types of languages that computers use. By
developing the Internet Protocols starting in the early 70's, Vinton
Cerf and Robert Kahn, created a set of communication standards which
permit worldwide connections despite such variability (20, 23).
Internet communication is defined by adherence to these protocols.
</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>INTERNET PROTOCOLS</B></P>

<P>In order to communicate from one point to another, literally
dozens of protocols come into play. Sending a message from a computer
at home requires protocols for converting a screen of typed text into
a digital form. Another protocol converts it into a stream of
information that a modem can handle. A modem protocol converts the
stream into a standardized audio signal that can pass on the
telephone line. The existence of protocol standards enables people on
the other end of the line to decode the telephone signal and the
digital stream so that they can convert it into signals that work on
their network and computers, recreating the original message. Even if
the receiving machine is a workstation buried in a University
network, it can interpret the original communication by taking
advantage of the standardized protocols.</P>

<P>Every step in this path of message translation is necessary and
each has multiple choices. To simplify understanding the Internet,
several models exist which divide the large number of protocols into
groups that are related to each other in layers. Each layer generally
represents a separate step in translation of the original message.
The most universal such model is the Open System Interconnection
(OSI) Reference Model, developed by the International Organization
for Standardization (ISO) in 1978 (24). This model is more complex
than most users need to understand network function. We have designed
a simpler four layer model for psychiatrists which goes beyond the
OSI model by incorporating some of the "protocols" that human beings
use in their communication. (see figure 1).</P>

<P>---------------------------------------------------------------------
</P>

<P><B>figure 1</B></P>



<P><IMG SRC="4Alayer.gif"
WIDTH=389 HEIGHT=235 X-SAS-UseImageWidth X-SAS-UseImageHeight
ALIGN=bottom></P>

<P>OSI model compared to four layer model</P>

<P>---------------------------------------------------------------------
</P>

<P>In our model, the lowest layer is the physical layer which is the
physical wires and wiring standards that form a connection. The next
higher layer is the transmission layer which includes all protocols
on how to pass information from one point on the network to another.
The layer above that is the form layer which specifies what medium
and organization the actual transmitted information should use. The
final layer is the human interaction layer, where the protocols
represent the interpersonal expectations that people implicitly form
when communicating with each other.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>The Physical Layer</P>

<P>Physically, the structure of the Internet is that of a network of
networks. The simplest network is the Local Area Network or LAN (25).
This refers to any set of computers and printers in one location that
are directly connected together by wires, fiber optic cables, or
other circuits. Several small LANs can be connected together through
telephone lines or other long distance telecommunication links to
form larger Wide Area Networks or WANs. These larger networks in turn
are connected together through network "backbones" to form the larger
Internet. Thus, every computer in the Internet is physically
connected to every other computer though wires, fiber optics,
microwave relays, modems, and other hardware, eventually stretching
around the world (23).</P>

<P>Physical layer protocols specify standards for how these wires can
be connected together. For example, ethernet protocols standardize
the types of cables, their length, and the number of connections they
can make when used in creating ethernet networks. Modem protocols
standardize the transmission speeds and compression algorithms used
in modem connections. All physical layer protocols serve to
standardize the types of possible physical connections between
computers.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>The Transmission Layer</P>

<P>Once the physical characteristics of the network are determined,
transmission protocols will specify how electronic messages are sent
over the physical network. For example, all connections on a network
need to be able to identify specific computer locations. This is done
with Internet Protocol (IP) where each Internet computer has a unique
IP address. Another protocol, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP),
creates a fixed format for getting messages from one IP address to
another (23, 26). This protocol specifies a method that takes all
information for transmission and divides it into self contained
packets which are encoded with their destinations. The protocol sends
the packets over the network and arranges for them to be recombined
at the destination, checking for packets that are lost along the way.
Thus, in sending information from computer A to computer B through
the Internet, any message will be divided into packets that each know
where computer B is located and can take any path through the
physical network to reach it. No specific line between A and B has to
be reserved, as in the case of a telephone call. This system was
designed by the Department of Defense in its early network
experiments in order to make communications fail-safe in case
portions of the network were interrupted (20, 21, 26). It also has
the advantage of making more efficient use of communications lines as
packets from several different people can be sent simultaneously on
the same line instead of reserving the line for information from only
two communicators.</P>

<P>Transmission layer protocols allow different physical networks to
intercommunicate by standardizing how signals are transmitted over
the physical connection. Use of TCP/IP, enables communication with
any other computer that also uses TCP/IP.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>The Form Layer</P>

<P>On top of the Transmission layer is the Form layer, where the
protocols define the form which the transmitted data should take.
Such definitions include many different aspects of how one sees and
explores data. One such aspect is the medium used to display the data
(such as text, sound, or video). Another aspect is the organization
of data access (such as paging through an alphabetical list or typing
in a keyword to be searched). Form protocols might even specify
transmission in a fashion to make communication seem more immediate
(like a phone) or delayed (like a letter). Commonly used Form
protocols of the Internet include Electronic Mail (e-mail), File
Transfer Protocol (FTP), Usenet news, Telnet, Gopher, Internet Relay
Chat (IRC), Wide Area Information Servers (WAIS), and Hypertext
Transfer Protocol (HTTP) (Table 1).</P>

<P>---------------------------------------------------------------------
</P>

<P><B>Table 1</B></P>

<P><HR><TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH="100%">
   <TR>
      <TD>
         <P><B>Name</B>
      </TD><TD>
         <P><B>Description</B>
      </TD><TD>
         <P><B>Examples</B>
      </TD></TR>
   <TR>
      <TD>
         <P>Electronic Mail (e-mail)
      </TD><TD>
         <P>This protocol provides an electronic mailing address for
         each user. Each user can then send a typed text message to
         any other user whose address they know. The software that
         implements this protocol often allows users to easily send
         multiple copies of their letters or create replies to
         letters which include a copy of the original message.
      </TD><TD>
         <P>author's address:</P>
         
         <P>&lt;mhuang@umich.edu&gt;</P>
         
         <P>InterPsych's psychopharmacology discussion group:
         &lt;psycho-pharm@netcom.com&gt;</P>
         
