      </TD></TR>
   <TR>
      <TD>
         <P>Internet Relay Chat (IRC)
      </TD><TD>
         <P>This protocol defines "channels", specifying a topic of
         conversation for the channel. Clients may obtain a list of
         topics of conversation that are ongoing, and join those of
         interest. All clients connected to a particular channel will
         type messages onto their screens. These messages are
         immediately sent to everyone else on the channel, so others
         can respond in real time.
      </TD><TD>
         <P>InterPsych's "Staff Lounge"</P>
         
         <P>channel #interpsyc
      </TD></TR>
   <TR>
      <TD>
         <P>Wide Area Information Servers (WAIS)
      </TD><TD>
         <P>This protocol uses a client/server model, where the
         client computer connects to the server and allows the user
         to submit an inquiry in plain english ("Tell me about the
         use of Risperidone in Schizophrenia.") The server takes the
         inquiry and searches specific databases for relevant
         articles, ranking its results in the order of relevance, and
         sending the list back to the client.
      </TD><TD>
         <P>Directory of Servers
      </TD></TR>
   <TR>
      <TD>
         <P>World Wide Web (WWW, W3, the Web)
      </TD><TD>
         <P>This protocol uses a server/client model where a server
         document containing words and graphics is displayed on the
         client's screen. These documents can contain hypertext
         links. A link specifies other documents on the same or other
         computer that the client or browser will immediately jump to
         if the client wants further information about the linked
         text or pictures.
      </TD><TD>
         <P>Psychiatry Star: &lt;http://www.psych.med.umich.edu&gt;
         </P>
         
         <P>Psycoloquy:
         &lt;http://www.princeton.edu/~harnad/psyc.html&gt;</P>
         
         <P>The Genome Project's Database:
         &lt;http://gdbwww.gdb.org/&gt;</P>
         
         <P>American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry:
         &lt;http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/aacap/&gt;</P>
         
         <P>The University of Iowa's Virtual Hospital:
         &lt;http://indy.radiology.uiowa.edu/VirtualHospital.html&gt;
      
      </TD></TR>
</TABLE></P>

<P>Form protocols commonly used on the Internet</P>

<P>---------------------------------------------------------------------
</P>

<P>As long as two individuals agree to use a particular protocol,
they will be able to communicate. In order to better explain these
protocols, we describe the use of three particular protocols in
greater depth: e-mail, Internet Relay Chat, and HyperText Transfer
Protocol, which is the protocol used by the World Wide Web (WWW). It
is important to recognize that these protocols only make
specifications about how data from the Transmission layer is
interpreted.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>E-MAIL</P>

<P>The e-mail protocol defines an electronic mailbox with an
electronic address for each user (27). It also specifies a standard
for sending and receiving text messages (electronic mail) where one
computer (the "mailserver") receives and stores the mail until a user
checks their mailbox there. Any computer that follows these standards
can send e-mail over the Internet. In fact, e-mail is so popular that
many non-Internet computers adhere to this protocol as well, allowing
e-mail to reach a total of 146 different countries.</P>

<P>Different software applications which implement the e-mail
protocol will each provide a different interface, some being more
graphically oriented and others providing special mailing functions.
Some programs make it simple to copy a note and send it to several
others (carbon copy) or to directly reply to an incoming message
without looking up the address of the sender. More sophisticated
options include automatic answering of mail or the ability to
"enclose" other computer files with the text message, including audio
and video clips.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>INTERNET RELAY CHAT (IRC)</P>

<P>Internet Relay Chat (IRC) is a text-based Form layer protocol
which enables users to communicate immediately, rather than with the
delay of e-mail. This protocol defines communication "channels."
Several IRC users connect to a computer "server" that links them to
the same channel. Whenever any connected individual types something
on their keyboard, the server will enclose it in an Internet packet
and send (serve) duplicates of the typed message to all other users
connected to the channel so that it immediately appears on their
computer screens. The idea is similar to a telephone "party line" but
is implemented using Internet protocols (28, 29).</P>

<P>As for e-mail, specific implementations of the IRC protocol might
organize messages differently on the computer screen or include
special commands for importing information from other documents.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>THE WORLD WIDE WEB (WWW)</P>

<P>One of the protocols which is most rapidly growing in popularity
is the HyperText Transfer Protocol (HTTP) used by the World Wide Web
(WWW) (30, 31,32). This protocol sets up "server" computers which
distribute documents containing text and graphics, as well as audio
and video files. This distribution occurs when a "client" computer
makes an information request of the server. The World Wide Web
project, started in 1991 by the European Laboratory for Particle
Physics (CERN: Conseil Europeen pour la Recherche Nucleaire),
designed a simple access to information through this protocol by
using it in conjunction with a document standard called Hypertext
Markup Language (HTML). This standard allows the definition of
"hyperlinks" within a document. A person using web software sees
documents on their computer screen containing words and pictures.
"Hyperlinked" words or pictures are highlighted and are activated
with a mouse click. If this article were in hypertext, clicking on
the highlighted word hypertext would initiate a request from a server
for another document describing more about hypertext. The downloading
process is invisible to the user, although the information might be
retrieved from a computer anywhere in the world. The subsequently
displayed document in turn could have further hyperlinks to other
documents, creating a global network of information.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>Form layer protocols define particular ways for presenting data
passed through physical and transmission layers of a network. Choice
of a particular form will allow communication with other Internet
computers which agree to implement the same form protocol. There are
many Form layer protocols besides those described in Table 1. Some
specify ways for transmission of "live" video information, others
specify ways to organize information for database searches. No
universal standards exist and new protocols are created every day.
</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>The Human Interaction Layer</P>

<P>The previous three layers are sufficient to describe the technical
components of Internet function relevant to forming communication.
Nonetheless, there is an important additional layer of human
interaction that is built upon these previous layers when the
Internet is used for communication between people. Our "protocols"
for communication between people are derived from centuries of
experience with verbal communication. In a conversation, we are
accustomed to speaking to another person where they immediately hear
our words, and we can monitor their nonverbal responses. Technology
affects these expectations. The advent of the technology of writing
created "written conversation" which lacks the immediacy and
monitoring aspects of its verbal precursor. Readers of an author need
certain levels of trust in the expectation that written exposition
will accurately reflect the other person's views (33). In a similar
fashion, correspondence through the Internet does not conform to our
usual expectations of verbal or written correspondence. The most
difficult task of someone learning about the Internet is not mastery
of the technical layers of communication expectations, but
acclimatizing oneself to the shift in expectations that are generated
by a new format for communicating.</P>

<P>There are many shifts in expectations that people must face in
using the Internet. One of the first is the speed of communication.
Messages sent through the Internet can travel around the world almost
instantly. In fact, e-mail users refer to traditional mail as
"snail-mail." In using this designation, they set the communication
experience apart, revealing a perception of its difference from the
usual experience. This difference increases as the speed of
communication brings about increases the speed at which information
spreads. More familiar media for communication do not allow
information to move immediately from one person to several thousand
people with a simple keystroke. Because it is easy for people to
circulate information quickly to a large audience, it also becomes
more difficult to maintain the same expectations of privacy. People
using the Internet need to adjust to the expectation that their
communications will be distributed to many areas that are not obvious
from the context of the immediate communication.</P>

<P>Related to the expectation of privacy in communication is the
expectation of impermanence. Verbal communication and even written
communication before the advent of easy to use copying machines were
often expected to be impermanent. They only lasted as long as the
memory of the audience or the piece of paper which they were
inscribed upon. Since Internet communications all travel through
multiple layers of software and hardware, it is easy to monitor or
even digitally record communications. This ability to record and
document all communications creates an altered expectation about
communications through the Internet. Internet users often keep in
mind that their employers, government, and legal agencies maybe
interested in examining their communications and that use of the
Internet permits this. Various legal precedents already attest to the
perception that such groups have rights to monitor these
communications because they are different from their non-electronic
counterparts (34, 35, 36).</P>

<P>The increased speed and dispersion of communications also
increases the volume of information that the individual is exposed
to. Traditional verbal and written communications often limit people
to more familiar realms for obtaining information, so that they
always return to the same journals or colleagues available in a
particular physical location. Access to a worldwide network exposes
individuals to a large set of electronic publications and
intellectual colleagues that one could not expect with traditional
communication (37). The Internet user must not only adjust to
expecting increases in information and information sources, but also
form strategies for determining the value of information so that they
can appropriately focus their energy.</P>

<P>A final element that is pervasive in affecting people using
information technologies is the continuous expectation of change.
Newer, faster computer and networking hardware appear every month.
New software and communications protocols emerge to take advantage of
these changes. Information providers change their information to take
advantage of the new technology, so that the information that each
user of the Internet sees will change as high speed links appear or
protocols like those of the World Wide Web replace older ones like
gopher. In this environment, Internet users need to change their
expectations around the communication of information. Unlike familiar
paper publications, information in electronic form will continue to
shift both in content and in the technology required to access it.
This expectation of fluidity, like expectations around the speed,
permanence, and volume of communication, is another factor in
everyday communications that can no longer be taken for granted in
the context of the Internet.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>FUTURE TRENDS</B></P>

<P>The future of the Internet will be driven by the impact which it
has on people and their desire to apply its potential for
distributing information. In the areas of education, clinical care,
research, and administration, we see many forces that will have
significant consequences in building the future of psychiatry.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>Education</B></P>

<P>Education in psychiatry will change as the Internet improves
communication and provides information access to patients,
psychiatric trainees, and continuing education for physicians (38,
39). Internet use will continue to expand, and the general public
will use it as a resource to find out information about psychiatric
illnesses. To meet such information demands, Internet based
information resources will develop from academic and government
institutions with an educational mission. As the Internet begins to
increase the public's expectation of information and demand for
psychiatric information, commercial providers will also enter this
arena. Managed care organizations are already investigating means for
reducing cost through computer based medical education (40), and such
forces will further encourage the development of networked
information resources.</P>

<P>In addition to serving patients, educational materials will
develop for training psychiatrists and continuing education. Sites on
the WWW already exist which teach radiological diagnosis (9,10,11) or
provide teaching cases where the trainee asks for information on
exam, past, medical, family, and social history, and then must come
up with a differential diagnosis (41). CME credits are available for
some of these training programs, and their presence on the Internet
makes them available to anyone in any country or rural location as
long as they have a computer connection. As organizations seek to
monitor and create standards of training, licensing, and care, they
will use the Internet to gather and distribute information about the
education of psychiatric practitioners.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>Clinical Care</B></P>

<P>Just as educational information will have greater dissemination
through the Internet, so will clinical information and information
about clinical treatment. Electronic patient records have been
pursued as a means for improving the continuity and efficiency of
patient care (42). The presence of the Internet will encourage the
use of communications networks for transmitting that information.
Much of this is likely to be driven by third party payers or
treatment review organizations which will want to receive copies of
patient information from clinical sites (43, 44). Treatment providers
in emergency and rural settings will also want more broadly
accessible patient information, so it can be made available in any
treatment location (45). The idea of a specifically located treatment
provider will change and may even reach into the home. Patients who
become accustomed to accessible educational information will also
expect easy access to treatment and consultation from physicians.
They will expect to be able to reach mental health providers through
their electronic information gateways, and these interfaces will
likely evolve from current text-based inquiries to more sophisticated
video-based consultations. These types of psychiatric interviews are
already being conducted in at least eleven different states at the
current time (17).</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>Research</B></P>

<P>As the Internet becomes more involved in information transmission
in education and clinical care, health services research will benefit
greatly. The transmission of clinical information for treatment is a
short step from the transmission of clinical information into
databases. Psychiatric information is already gathered by clinician
networks such as the APA clinician network (APA Practice Guidelines
Steering Committee, Office of Research American Psychiatric
Association: Development of a Psychiatric Practice Research Network:
Overview of the Purpose and a Proposed Approach. Unpublished Report.
June 1993.), but the use of the Internet can allow more uniform
access on a global scale. Tracking practice patterns will help us
understand more about which treatments are effective and which are
not.</P>

<P>As the Internet begins to provide psychiatrists with improved
opportunites for research with psychiatric colleagues, it will also
expand our access to the knowledge and research of neurologists,
internists, psychologists, and other specialists. This improved
information exchange will extend the boundaries of our research and
make our learning more accessible to other specialists. Projects like
the Human Brain Project will bring together more of the data
necessary to form an integrated model of brain function incorporating
development, genetics, behavior, brain physiology, demographic and
social information (46, 47, 48). The future of research will be
"collaboratories" (collaborative laboratories) where coworkers of
multiple specialties are connected electronically instead of joined
in a physical location (49). The "research center without walls" is
cost effective in its efficient use of national and worldwide
resources. (50)</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>Administration</B></P>

<P>The growth in information exchange that the Internet is creating
will also create changes in organizational structures. All
organizations have a representation which they present to others
which provides identity and definition. Corporations, institutions,
and governments all use these representations as a point of
communications with others. With the Internet, these representations
are becoming electronic. Currently, the most rapid way to obtain
information about Presidential press releases is through the Internet
(51). More organizations will assume electronic representations in
order to more efficiently communicate with the government and the
public. Special interest groups are using the Internet to communicate
to both the government and their supporters.</P>

<P>As institutions become more electronic and less "physical," they
will also become more decentralized. Physical locations will mean
less as people organize themselves according to electronic
representations of institutions and employ distanced communications.
Departments of Psychiatry or psychiatric treatment groups will be
defined by their communications and desire to be aligned rather than
by where they concretely exist. Examples of electronically based
organizations already exist and will become more prevalent with
advances in technology (52).</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>FUTURE CHALLENGES</B></P>

<P>The rapidly moving future described above brings with it several
specific challenges which are directly derived from the freedom and
ease of information exchange which the Internet delivers. We divide
these problems into three major areas: the need for organization, the
need for standards, and the need for security and privacy. These
problems represent a general challenge for both individuals and
organizations as the Internet alters our future communication.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>The Need for Organization</B></P>

<P>The highly varied protocol structure of the Internet creates
opportunities for disorganization. Information travels thorough
particular paths which may not intersect. What is known on the e-mail
network does not necessarily travel to the gopher or WWW networks,
and vice versa. What an administrator expects about permanence of
e-mail communication might not coincide with the expectation of a
staff clinician. Furthermore, the continuing growth of technology
creates constant change as new techniques are applied to each layer
of protocols. Changes in wiring on the physical layer or changes in a
video application protocol in the form layer will reverberate through
all layers, requiring adaptation. The Internet's complexity and
continually shifting nature will isolate users and information
providers who are not knowledgeable about such intricacies.</P>

<P>This constantly changing environment represents a challenge to all
individuals and organizations using the Internet. Time and resources
need to be allocated to studying each layer of communication.
Individuals should have basic familiarity with computer hardware of
the physical layer, Internet connectivity of the transmission layer,
software applications of the form layer, and the potential
difficulties with adapting communication expectations in the human
interaction layer (53). For large organizations, this task becomes
more complex as they attempt to create experts at each level of
communication who can master the various changes in their area of
Internet study (54). These experts must be able to communicate well
with each other, as any change that affects one of them will spread
to affect them all.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>The Need for Standards</P>

<P>The difficulties reflected in the need for organization of the
Internet are compounded by a the need for content standards. Although
protocols provide standards in creating the framework for
communication, they do not make specifications as to content of that
communication. The ease of communications that the Internet provides
means that anyone can put out information of any sort. In many cases,
there is no verification of validity, no process of review or quality
control. Paper journals, on the other hand, have built long standing
reputations for the type of information they contain and the quality
with which that information is organized and presented. A policy
statement by the editors of the New England Journal of Medicine
limits electronic circulation of manuscripts and describes their
concerns about the maintenance of familiar standards (55). Some
electronic journals are now peer reviewed (56, 57), but the main body
of reviewers and editors of psychiatric journals publish solely in
the paper realm. The sheer volume and speed of electronic publication
will call for different review process for much electronic
information (58).</P>

<P>This difficulty in establishing and judging value represents a
challenge to individuals and organizations using the Internet.
Individuals will need to exercise discrimination in judging their
Internet communications. The fact an electronic journal or letter
"feels" like a paper one does not automatically lend validity to its
contents. Conversely, organizations that serve as information
providers must allocate effort to translate paper techniques of
validation and critique from paper to the electronic realm. They will
need to monitor their electronic works to maintain quality and
direction without falling prey to the trap of publishing electronic
words simply because it is easy to do so.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>The Need for Security</B></P>

<P>A third challenge of the Internet is to address the need for
security and privacy that the free exchange of information places at
risk (59, 60). In psychiatry, this becomes an extremely important
issue as we must protect the confidentiality of patient information.
Breaches of security can occur at all levels of communication. At the
physical and transmission layers, the information packets that are
sent through the net are susceptible to interception at different
points in their journey. Some form protocols have features that do
not match with human expectations of human interaction
communications. The person who only looks upon IRC as a telephone
party line will not anticipate that others will record a chat session
although this capability is easily available to all conference
members. Someone mailing a private electronic letter, may not expect
its contents to be excerpted and forwarded to others. Such
occurrences become more common as the Internet makes information
transfer easier and consequently less private.</P>

<P>The challenge which the need for security poses will require
individuals and organizations to learn and prepare for such potential
breaches of privacy. At the physical, transmission and form layers,
such problems are being addressed with the use of encryption and the
creation of "firewalls" in the network. The human layer, however, is
the hardest to regulate. "Hackers" who attempt to break security
systems always do so by approaching the network through people,
duping them into giving out their passwords. People will always be
the most likely contributor to a security risk, and the small
mistakes of an accidental breach of confidentiality will be
compounded as the Internet makes global communication something done
easily from any desktop. Internet users will need to understand all
the different ways in which they can compromise private information,
and organizations that provide Internet access will need to make sure
their employees are aware of these possibilities (61).</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><B>CONCLUSION</B></P>

<P>The Internet represents more than a physical network or set of
protocols. It represents a communications phenomena where more and
more people will have the ability to transmit more and more
information quickly and easily on a global scale. This capability is
affecting us at a societal level as people begin to expect and demand
instant information. In psychiatry, we will be faced with calls from
researchers who want clinical data; educators who want clinical
experience; third party payers, government regulators, and patients
who want documentation of clinical expertise. We will be expected to
be able to utilize information management tools like the Internet to
answer these demands. Although we may refuse to answer all the
demands put to us, we will not be able to avoid the fact that this
movement will continue to sweep the rest of society along.</P>

<P>With such forces as a background, we need to formulate a cogent
understanding of the Internet's function so that we can establish a
direction and goal for moderating change. Whether that goal is to
limit breaches of confidentiality, improve patient communications, or
contact a worldwide audience, change will only occur if all the
different levels of the Internet communication model are addressed.
Implementation of physical wires or communications software will fail
without organizing expectations for communication of people. Studying
how information flows through an Internet network also requires
studying how information flows among the people who wish to send it.
</P>

<P>As psychiatrists, we will be required to negotiate between the
informational demands that will be required of all medical
practitioners and the central goals that drive us in our profession.
As a profession, we should be aware of and encourage the study of how
information is used in psychiatry. We must continue to educate
ourselves so that we can remain effective organizers and
communicators of information and in this way best serve our
professional mission.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

