<HR>
<H1>Riding the Third Wave:<BR>
Psychiatry in the Information Era</H1>
<P>
The world of psychiatry is changing rapidly. Few would argue that we have entered into a new era. Many practicing psychiatrists would likely call it the managed care era, since it is changing how we practice. I would argue, however, that the era of managed care is not the one we have entered, nor the one we should be worried about. This era is the information era.
<P>
	Obviously, we have entered into a new health care era paradigm. But the real question that we should ask ourselves is why. Some would say it's politics: The politics of the era are demanding that people become more cost-conscious and attempt to deal with care in a more economical manner.
 But why is this happening now? It is because of information technologya new availability of data bases, networks and computers; a new ability to collect information, analyze information and apply it to new models.
	<P>
Whether in medicine or manufacturing, these new abilities enable people to communicate, measure, calculate and project information. Information about whether something is good or bad, efficient or inefficient, should be used or eliminated.
<P>	Information is the foundation and basis of what constitutes the new era. It is changing the very basis of how we judge and value things. An interesting review of this can be found in Heidi and Alvin Toffler's book, Creating a New Civilization, in which they talk about the impact of the "Third Wave," or in particular, the impact of our moving from an agrarian to an industrial to an information society.
<P>
<B>Information Society</B>
<BR>
	The information society in which we live will change everything that we believe and think of as being our current reality. Why? Because it reduces jobs to quantifiable and qualitatively analyzable entities that can be broken down into simple tasks. This shifts away from the model requiring a highly skilled laborer such as a psychiatrist. Instead, these simple tasks are distributed to many people who have only minimal skills or training.
	<P>As we move into this new era, we have to be aware that there are many people who have great expertise in implementing this process. Furthermore, these experts have no reason to believe that psychiatry needs to exist. There may be 40.000 people who believe the contrary, such as the members of the American Psychiatric Association, but we should remember that it was only recently that AT&T laid off 40,000 workers-approximataely 8.5% of its workforce.
<P>
	We need to prepare the existing body of psychiatrists, as well as better prepare those who are entering residency programs.
<P>
In examining the world at large, I have become more appreciative of the development of monumental corporations that dwarf our entire speciality in numbers, as well as international conglomerates with resources that can move nations.
<BR>Many such powerful entities are operating with assumptions different from our own as they move into the health care industry and use information technology to achieve their goals. We have to be be aware of such forces that might work for  or 
against us.  We have to develop a strategy around information technology, so that 
in this new era we will not become victims, but victors.
<BR>We need to prepare the existing body of psychiatrists, as well as better prepare those who are entering existing residency programs.
<P>
<B>A Strategy for the Future</B>
<BR>
	The strategy I would propose has four components: the formation of a society for psychiatric informatics; the development of a standardized curriculum involving psychiatric informatics at every year of training during residency; the development of specialized psychiatric information fellowships,and more topics concerning computer and information technology applications at national meetings.
<P>
<B>Formation of a Society</B>
<BR>
	Medical informatics is an area highly regarded in many areas of medicine, particularly pathology, radiology and internal medicine. These groups actively participate in national informatics societies, and have built a large enough interest among their members to create specialized informatics societies. 
<P>In order to promote
and share interest and experience among psychiatrists is this area, it was critical 
to form such an organization in psychiatry .  As noted in this column several times before, there is such an organization.: The Psychiatric Society for Informatics.  Those
interested can contact: 
Marvin Miller, M.D.  <BR>
1315 W 10th St., Indianapolis, IN  46202
<P>
Development of a Curriculum
<BR>
	It is of utmost importance that psychiatric informatics be taught at every level of training. This should be phased in over each year of residency and cover issues of information management (such as library skills, data base searches, etc.), electronic data bases for patient information, information technology within one's practice and understanding information technology in any practice in which one enters. Using such an approach over a number of years will enable the psychiatrist to build a body or fund of knowledge and develop expertise in regard to the recognition of technology essential when entering into a job.
<P>
<B>Informatics Fellowships</B>
<BR>
	As in other areas of medicine, specialization is important for development of a field.
This is why we now have specialization programs in neuropsychiatry, substance abuse, geriatrics, and so on. It will become increasingly important to form a cadre of psychiatrists with recognized expertise in informatics and information technology, and whose expertise  is supported not as an avocation but as  a major component of a vocation. Such recognition will undoubtedly further the development of fellowships in psychiatric informatics over the next 10 years.
<P>
<B>Presence at National Meetings</B>
<BR>
	The easy availability of informatio tec nology courses for psychiatrists is of utmost importance. The American Psychiatric Association and other groups need to more of their meeting time to this area of expertise. It would be folly to beli person could learn enough to keep these issues while only attending; for one hour a year.
<P>
Information technologies are developing at such tremendous rates and providing such a tremendous advantage that most industries invest up to 11 percent of their funds in information technology. I would ask all psychiatrists how much time they are spending on information technology and if they really recognize the significance of this era.
<P>
	Numerous books indicate the significance of information technology in business and the impact it will have on industry. Two examples are: Paradigm Shift, the New Promise of Information Technology by Don Tapscott, McGraw-Hill, 1993, and Business Re-engineering with Information Technology by John J. Donovan, Prentice Hall, 1994. 
<P>
Psychiatrists who wish to compete will have to constantly retrain themselves; this was true of biological psychiatry in the 1990s and certainly will be true of this new paradigm of the 21 st century.
<P>
The reality is that we have a choice, and ifwe wish to be winners in this new world, we must be willing to change our own lives, creating a new place in the information era.
<P.
Dr. Alessi is chief information officerforthe department of psychiatry atthe Universityof Michiganand director of the child and adolescent psychiatry division.

Dr. Huang is the first psychiatric informatics fellow of the University of Michigan and is responsible for WWW development of UM's Psychiatry Star.
<P>
