<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Child and Adolescent Psychiatry</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>Child and Adolescent Psychiatry Division</H1><P>

	An emotional commitment toward working for children may be what draws individuals to the field of child and adolescent psychiatry.  One must consider a broad range of developmental parameters, learn to communicate differently and be much more intuitive in order to succeed.<P>

	Faculty within the Division have succeeded in mastering these skills and are particularly well known for their work in psychopharmacology, mood disorders, autism and suicidal behavior.  Research projects include the study of the neurobiological mechanisms of mood disorders in child and adolescents; the pharmacotherapy of aggression; the study of developmental disorders; suicidal behavior as it relates to long-term functioning; and computer applications in psychiatry.<P>

	The Division is comprised of the 26-bed inpatient unit at C.S. Mott Children's Hospital, where children from age 18 months to 18 years are treated for acts of aggression and psychiatric disorders that cannot be managed on an outpatient or less-restricted basis.  Patients -about 400 per year- stay 12 days, on average, and are seen for developmental disabilities such as autism, mood affective disturbances and psychotic disturbances.<P>

	The outpatient program is for children from age one to 18 years who have behavioral, emotional or cognitive disturbances such as attention deficit disorder, hyperactivity, mood disorders or disruptive behavior disorders.  The faculty and staff provide a full range of diagnostic tools, offering psychological, school, occupational and therapy assessments.<P>

	Therapy options are equally broad, with individual and group, cognitive-behavioral, family therapies and pharmacotherapy available.  The Division manages 12,000 visits annually, making it one of the top 10 in the United States.<P>

	The training program is one of the largest as well, with 12 child fellows and a number of research fellows each year.<P>
<HR>
Continue on to learn about the <A HREF="consult.htm">Consultation and General Psychiatry Division</A>.
<P>
