<DOCNO>WT24-B26-250</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA094-001014-B042-46</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.psych.med.umich.edu:80/web/CD/Statement.htm 141.214.71.83 19970121063226 text/html 7579
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: WebSTAR/1.2.4 ID/39
Message-ID: <af09da74.151813@141.214.71.83>
Date: Tuesday, 21-Jan-97 06:29:08 GMT
Last-Modified: Friday, 18-Oct-96 20:46:57 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 7334
</DOCHDR>
<!--This file created 10/18/96 4:53 PM by Claris Home Page version 1.0-->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Statement</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 1.0">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=66 BOTTOM=480 LEFT=8 RIGHT=634>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#08023C" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#CCCA16">

<P><HR></P>

<P><IMG SRC="../images/Normtimes.JPG" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=200
X-SAS-UseImageWidth X-SAS-UseImageHeight ALIGN=bottom></P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5><A HREF="Faculty.htm">Faculty</A></FONT><FONT SIZE=5>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=5><A HREF="Education.htm">Education
Statement</A></FONT><FONT SIZE=5>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=5><A HREF="Publications.htm">Publications</A></FONT><FONT SIZE=5>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=5><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A></FONT></B></P>

<P>For over four decades, the Child and Adolescent Psychiatric
Hospital of the University of Michigan has established standards for
clinical care, research and education that have defined the scope and
position of child and adolescent psychiatry. The University of
Michigan had the first free standing child and adolescent psychiatric
hospital in the nation. This was the first facility in the world to
recognize the unique needs of adolescent patients resulting in the
formation of an adolescent inpatient unit by Willard Hendrickson, now
a Professor Emeritus at the University.</P>

<P>Internationally recognized leaders in child and adolescent
psychiatry including Dr. Stuart Finch, Dr. Humberto Nagera, Dr. Luke
Tsai, and Dr. Norm Alessi have guided the Child and Adolescent
Psychiatric Hospital through four decades of change and maturation,
training many of the most illustrious names in the field. The first
textbook in child and adolescent psychiatry was written and edited by
CAPH faculty, Stuart Finch, John McDermott and Saul Harrison. In the
era of psychodynamic psychiatry, the Division was revered as one of
the premier training sites for residents in child and adolescent
psychiatry. During the 1970's and 80's, as academic interests shifted
to emphasize studies of psychopathology, the Child and Adolescent
Psychiatric Hospital was on the forefront of this research, utilizing
and developing structured interviews for adolescents with psychiatric
disabilities, and further describing and understanding disturbances
of depression and aggression in youth.</P>

<P>Over the last several years, the faculty of the CAPH have made
substantial contributions to the identification of comorbid
disturbances in children with developmental disabilities and
depression. Most recently, a number of faculty members are
investigating the genetic basis of obsessive compulsive disturbances,
depression with aggressive disruptive behavior disturbances, the use
of ECT in adolescents with mood disturbances, and the complex
phenomena of developmental psychopathology in children and
adolescents with mood disturbances.</P>

<P>The future domains in which the resources of the Child and
Adolescent Psychiatric Hospital will focus are:</P>

<P>1. Applications of information technology</P>

<P>2. Psychopharmacology</P>

<P>3. Developmental psychopathology</P>

<P>4. Neurobiology and molecular genetics</P>

<P>5. Treatment outcomes and optimal service delivery</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>Applied Information technology:</P>

<P>Under the guidance of Dr. Norman Alessi, the faculty and staff of
the Child and Adolescent Psychiatric Hospital are exploring
information technologies that will improve the diagnosis, treatment
and continuity of care of children with mental health disturbances.
In this area, we are investigating ways to automate the collection of
information, facilitate the collection of outcome data, develop
multimedia applications, and implement telemedicine in child and
adolescent psychiatry. Dr. Alessi has created an Informatics
Fellowship in the Department of Psychiatry where two fellows are
developing data base structures, information collection strategies,
and standards for information technology that will be applied
nationally.</P>

<P>Psychopharmacology:</P>

<P>The development of strategies for the investigation of
psychopharmacological agents in child and adolescent psychiatry is of
utmost importance. Without a question, the use of medications will
become increasingly important to the evolution of psychiatry. The
field must identify and develop more focal medications, investigating
their utility for particular types of child and adolescent
psychopathology. Dr. Neera Ghaziuddin is currently in the process of
investigating serotonergic mechanisms of selective serotonergic
uptake inhibiting antidepressants. Further protocols will be
developed around specific drugs and disorders, such as Obsessive
Compulsive Disorder (OCD), Child Depression, Attention Deficit,
Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD), Psychosis, and possibly, children with
Developmental Disabilities. In addition to traditional research
designs, the Division is exploring new paradigms for clinical
investigations to examine the effectiveness of alternative
pharmacologic strategies in the setting of routine clinical practice.
</P>

<P>Developmental Psychopathology:</P>

<P>Without a question, little is known about the course and outcome
of many psychiatric disturbances in children and adolescents.
Information about these developmental pathways is essential to
prevention and early intervention efforts. Unfortunately, earlier
models, such as that by Anna Freud, conceptualized psychotherapies as
on a continuum with normality rather than as a disruption in the
normal pathways of development. Work such as Dr. King's examines the
course of psychopathology and its impact on numerous domains of
development. It will be of utmost importance as we proceed to
understand the implications of these disturbances throughout the life
span.</P>

<P>Neurobiology and molecular genetics:</P>

<P>One of the most promising areas of medical research today is the
investigation of genetic factors in common diseases. Numerous studies
have shown that most of the mood, anxiety, and tic disorders are
familial; that is, these problems run in families. Gregory Hanna is
conducting a family study of childhood obsessive-compulsive disorder
(OCD) to identify the mode of transmission and the susceptibility
genes in this illness. Information about the genes involved in OCD
will allow us to make improvements in the detection and treatment of
OCD and related disorders.</P>

<P>Treatment Outcome Studies:</P>

<P>In addition to studies focused specifically on the effectiveness
of psychopharmacologic agents in child and adolescent psychiatry, the
Child and Adolescent Psychiatric Hospital is developing an integrated
clinical and research program to study optimal treatments and
combinations of treatments for mood and anxiety disorders. Drs.
Alessi, Ghaziuddin, Hanna, Kalter, King and Weidmer-Mikhail are
bringing together their collective skills in this area to design
treatment components and implementation strategies. These efforts are
expected to positively impact the standards of clinical practice for
these disorders in our rapidly changing health services delivery
system.</P>

<P>As it has in the past, CAPH will continue to provide leadership
through its strong training programs, research and scholarship into
the next millennium.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P><HR></P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
</BODY>
</HTML>
