<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Education</TITLE>
   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 1.0">
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=90 BOTTOM=480 LEFT=12 RIGHT=542>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#070140" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#BDC524">

<P><HR><IMG SRC="../images/Jimtimes.JPG" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=200
X-SAS-UseImageWidth X-SAS-UseImageHeight ALIGN=bottom></P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5><A HREF="Statement.htm">Division
Statement</A></FONT><FONT SIZE=5>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=5><A HREF="Faculty.htm">Faculty</A></FONT><FONT SIZE=5>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=5><A HREF="Publications.htm">Publications</A></FONT><FONT SIZE=5>
</FONT><FONT SIZE=5><A HREF="index.htm">Home</A></FONT><FONT SIZE=5>
</FONT></B></P>

<P><B>&nbsp;</B></P>

<P><B>RESIDENCY IN CHILD AND ADOLESCENT PSYCHIATRY</B></P>

<P>The Division of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry at the University
of Michigan Medical Center has long been recognized as one of the
nation's foremost programs for training leaders in the field. Its
rigorous yet flexible course of training produces clinicians with
outstanding skills in diagnostic assessment, traditional
psychotherapies, empirically-based psychotherapies, somatic
treatment, and consultation. The division also enthusiastically
supports residents interested in academic careers, research, and
medical education, through faculty actively engaged in diverse
research and scholarly activities. Two current child psychiatry
residents are enrolled in a research training track that merges
research and clinical training.</P>

<P>Who Should Consider Training in Child/Adolescent Psychiatry?</P>

<P>Child psychiatry training is valuable not only for physicians who
have decided upon a career working with children, but also for
psychiatrists who demand a fuller appreciation of behavior and
psychopathology from longitudinal and developmental perspectives.
Many important psychiatric disorders, including behavior disorders
and pervasive developmental disorders, mental retardation, learning
disabilities, and Tourette's syndrome, to mention only a few, begin,
by definition, in youth. Other disorders commonly viewed as the
domain of adult psychiatry, including schizophrenia and
manic-depressive disorder, typically crystallize in adolescence or
early adulthood, with early signs sometimes evident in infancy.
Psychosocial adversity in early life reverberates through the
lifespan, and most theories of personality development and disorder
emphasize early developmental influences and predispositions.</P>

<P>For these reasons, child psychiatrists frequently offer unique
perspectives on psychopathology across the life cycle. Furthermore,
as psychiatry seeks a niche as a primary care specialty, the capacity
to treat whole families spanning several generations of
psychopathology will become increasingly valuable.</P>

<P>In practice, many adult psychiatrists treat adolescents. Those
with certificates of training or board certification in
child/adolescent psychiatry have a wider range of employment options,
and salaried child psychiatrists frequently earn a premium. Child
psychiatry remains among the few shortage specialties in medicine.
</P>

<P>Application for Combined Adult and Child/Adolescent Training</P>

<P>An applicant may seek admission to the child and adolescent
training program as part of the application for general psychiatry
residency training simply by indicating on the application form that
she wishes to be considered for both programs. This application
should be returned to Dr. Riba, Director of Residency Training (box
0704).</P>

<P>The combined adult and child programs require five years of
training, though most residents become eligible for board
certification in general psychiatry after their fourth year.
Residents applying for both programs will be interviewed by members
of the adult and child/adolescent psychiatry faculty.</P>

<P>The Department recognizes that occasionally physicians conclude
that they are better suited to careers in general psychiatry; in such
cases residents may withdraw from the child program and complete
general psychiatry training after the fourth year, provided they have
fulfilled all requirements of the adult program. Admission to the
child residency training program is, of course, contingent on the
availability of funded positions and continued accreditation of the
program; participants in the combined programs receive first priority
in assigning available positions.</P>

<P>It is probably wise for applicants to secure commitments for
advanced training as early as possible, since changing financial
incentives may reduce the number of training places available
nationally by the turn of the century. An early decision to enter
child psychiatry training also streamlines planning and ensures that
all requirements for board certification are completed within five
years.</P>

<P>Application for Child/Adolescent Training Only</P>

<P>General psychiatry residents anticipating successful completion of
the PGY-3 or PGY-4 years may apply for child and adolescent training
at, respectively, the PGY-4 or PGY-5 level. These applications should
be returned to Dr. Dillon, Director of Training in Child/Adolescent
Psychiatry (box 0390). The "match" has recently been introduced to
child psychiatry; the applicant should contact Dr. Dillon's office to
ascertain whether spaces in the University of Michigan program will
be offered within or outside the match.</P>

<P>The Residency Program in Child/Adolescent Psychiatry</P>

<P>For those who have decided to pursue child and adolescent
psychiatry training, the University of Michigan program is an
outstanding choice. The program here is demanding but educationally
geared.</P>

<P>Didactics</P>

<P>For the past two years we have employed a unique and innovative
approach to didactic training. During July and August, first year
child residents apportion about 50% of their training time to
didactics, including 3-4 hours of lecture daily. Other clinical
responsibilities are reduced to ensure that this time is actually
available. It is thus possible to rapidly and thoroughly cover the
rudiments of child psychiatry before clinical commitments seriously
compete with scholarly good intentions.</P>

<P>Intensive didactics in state-of-the-art, empirically-based
psychotherapies are currently offered in September and October, and
are followed by an 18 month long continuing case conference. In
addition to this sequence, a psychoanalyst provides 2.5 hours per
week of instruction and case seminars in the first year (1.5 hours
per week in the second year) devoted exclusively to principles of
psychodynamic interviewing, treatment, and development. Classes from
November through June are modeled after graduate seminars in which
topics of special interest receive close scrutiny.</P>

<P>For the second year of child residency, intensive didactics in
principles of consultation and psychosomatics, educational issues,
and forensic psychiatry are presented in July. The continuing case
conference and seminars on special topics continue throughout the
year.</P>

<P>Clinical</P>

<P>The clinical curriculum in the first year includes traditional
inpatient training on a combined child/adolescent unit of about 15
beds, as well as continuing care, intensive outpatient treatment, and
child neurology postings. The second clinical year is
outpatient-based, including rotations in pediatric consultation,
school consulation (using the local schools), preschool day care, and
developmental disorders. Forensic cases, ranging from custody to
homicide, are supervised by a board certified forensic child
psychiatrist and by an attorney/psychologist.</P>

<P>Supervision is supplied by full-time medical faculty, full-time
non-medical faculty, and courtesy medical faculty. Residents
generally have 3-4 supervisors at any given time.</P>

<P>Breaking with the traditional practice of assigning a supervisor
to each resident and conducting therapy according to the supervisors'
particular attainments and inclinations, the psychotherapy teaching
program presents a menu of required treatments that residents conduct
over the two year sequence with supervisors who specialize in
providing the treatments being learned. Psychotherapy supervision is
thus assigned according to the needs of the case, rather than by a
random process of matching faculty and resident names. Treatment
techniques considered fundamental for the broadly trained child
psychiatrist include applied behavioral analysis, parent management
training, structured group therapies, family therapies, structured
individual psychotherapies for depression and anxiety
(cognitive-behavioral therapy or interpersonal psychotherapy),
therapies involving exposure and classical conditioning, and
traditional dynamic psychotherapy.</P>

<P>DIVISIONS</P>

<P>Child and Adolescent Psychiatry Division</P>

<P>The Division of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry includes ten full
time child psychiatrists as well as numerous non-medical faculty and
community (part-time) medical faculty. Many have been drawn to the
profession both by an emotional commitment to help children and by
the challenge of mastering the broad range of skills required for
successful practice. Most of the faculty are engaged in research or
other scholarly enterprises, and many are well known nationally and
internationally for their work in fields such as autism, computer
applications in psychiatry, suicide, affective disorders, and child
custody.</P>

<P>The Division has an inpatient unit of approximately 15 beds with
several hundred admissions annually and an average length of stay of
about one week. The inpatient units treat a broad spectrum of
psychopathology including behavior disorders, affective disorders,
eating disorders, psychoses, adjustment reactions, personality
disorders, and aggression and self-injurious behavior associated with
autism and mental retardation.</P>

<P>The outpatient program treats patients from infancy to about age
eighteen. Its 12,000 visits annually ranks it among the 10 largest
outpatient child psychiatry clinics in the United States. It offers a
complete range of psychosocial and somatic treatments.</P>

<P>Both inpatient and outpatient facilities are currently housed in a
Maternal and Child Health Center that also is the home of the
divisions of pediatrics and obstetrics-gynecology. Links with the
outstanding facilities and faculty of these departments are an
important benefit of training at the Child and Adolescent Psychiatric
Hospital.</P>

<P><HR></P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
