<HEAD>
<TITLE>Course Overview</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H2>Course Overview</H2>
By Norman Alessi 
<P>

The first lecture covered the why, what, who, and our hopes for this lecture series.<P>

<B>Why</B>:  Information technology is driving the managed care era.  The application of techniques which have been or which currently evolving in a business setting, are now being applied to the medical setting.  Therefore, it is absolutely critical that we, as a medical center, come to understand what the implications of these might be, will be, and what their effects will be on the delivery of care.<P>

Numerous other major university medical centers in the United States have major informatics departments.  Columbia University, Stanford, Indiana University, University of North Carolina, Duke, to list some of the leaders.  It is our thought that informatics is a field which is of significance to our medical center and much as other major medical centers have such initiatives, we feel that it is important that we as an outstanding biomedical research hospital have a similar thrust.<P>

In order to support the development of informatics fellowships in the UMMC and the University of Michigan Medical School, it is important that we have organized lectures concerning informatics.  Currently, to our knowledge there are only two departments which have informatics fellowships, the Department of Psychiatry and the Department of Pathology.  The lecture series will support the development of such fellowships for all departments.<P>

<B>What</B>:  There currently exists a listing of our informatics lecture series topics on the World Wide Web.  This can be obtained from http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/UMpsych/infmatic/
lecture/.  The course has the following major titles, following an introduction to the series: 

<UL>
<LI>Information Sources
<LI>Clinical Information Systems
<LI>Expert Systems, Decision Making, Economics of Care
<LI>Networking
<LI>Databases
<LI>Ethical, Legal, and Security Issues
<LI>Human Factors Knowledge Representation, Multimedia, Virtual Reality
</UL><P>

<B>Who</B>:  These presentations are given by those individuals who we believe are the leaders within our medical center in the areas of informatics and applied information technology. <P> 

<B>Hopes</B>:  We hope that this series provides a nidus for those interested in information technology to start looking at this topic and determine its best approach here.<P>


<HR>
Return to the <A HREF="./">Lecture Series</A> table

