<H2>Michael McGill </H2>
<P>
Michael McGill joined the University of Michigan in February 1992 as
Director of Network Systems.  He was responsible for the voice, data and
video networks at the University.  He also played a significant role in the
evolution of the electronic information resources on campus.
<UL><P>
  
<LI>In February1994, he was appointed Chief Information Officer for University of MichiganMedical Center and is responsible for information technology for the
medical campus and University of Michigan Hospitals.<P>

<LI>Prior to the University of Michigan, Dr. McGill served as Vice President of
Industry Marketing Systems, for Ameritech Information Systems for two
years.<P>

<LI>From 1983-1990, he was Vice president of OCLC (Online Computer Library
Center, Inc.)<P>

<LI>Mike was Program Director for Information Science for the National Science
Foundation from 1981-1983.<P>

<LI>From 1980-1981 he was Senior Computer and Information Science Advisor,
Office of Toxic Substances, US. Environmental Protection Agency.<P>

<LI>From 1974-1980 Mike held the position of Associate Professor and Assistant
Dean for Research and the Ph.D. Program, School of Information Studies and
Associate Professor of the School of Computer and Information Science,
Syracuse University.<P>

<LI>In 1979 he was a Visiting Associate Professor, Department of Computer
Science, Cornell University.<P>

<LI>From 1972-1974, Mike was Assistant Professor of Computer Science, State
University of New York at Oswego.<P>
</UL>

Mike received a BA in Communications from Michigan State University, and an
MA in Communications and a Ph.D. in Computer and Information Science from
Syracuse University.<P>

<B>Publications include:</B>
<UL>
<LI>Introduction to Modern Information Retrieval, McGraw-Hill Computer Science
Series, 1983. (With Gerard Salton)<BR>

<LI>"Campus Strategies for Libraries and Electronic Information", Chapter in
EDUCOM Strategies Series on Information Technology, 1989 (with Drew Racine)<BR>

<LI>"The Evolving National Information Network: Background and Challenges,"
Report of the Technology Assessment Advisory Committee to the Commission on
Preservation and Access, July 1993 (with D. Van Houweling).<BR>
</UL>
McGill is a Fellow of the American Society for the Advancement of Science.

       






