<HEAD>
<TITLE>Edward Goldman</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>

<HR>
<H2>Edward Goldman MS</H2>

Edward Goldman:

Edward Goldman has been Medical Center Attorney, University of Michigan 
since 1978.  He is also Adjunct Professor at the University of Michigan 
Medical School and the University of Michigan School of Public Health.  
Mr. Goldman enjoys a diverse career combining the practice of law, 
teaching and writing, labor arbitration and community service.
<P>
As a complement to his extensive health law experience, Mr. Goldman has 
been a labor arbitrator for the Expedited Arbitration Panels for the 
Michigan Steel, Auto and Can Industries, and the Ohio Steel Industry for 
twenty years. 
<P> In addition, he worked in the City Attorney's Office of 
Ann Arbor for four years, taught at the University of Michigan Law 
School for four years and was a partner in a private civil and trial 
practice for three years.
<P>
Mr. Goldman has written on a number of topics in the health care field. 
<P> 
His writing has covered such important areas as refusing treatment, 
informed consent for breast cancer therapy, consenting to blood 
transfusion, Jehovah Witnesses, medico-legal issues in pulmonary 
medicine, and the law of emergency care in neonatal emergencies.  
<P>He has 
also published in the areas of wrongful birth, fetal versus maternal 
rights, medical education, and non-custodial parents' rights in their 
children's health care.
<P>

A graduate of both the University of Michigan and its law school, Mr. 
Goldman is a former president of the Michigan Society of Hospital 
Attorneys.  
<P>In 1980, the society recognized his contributions by giving 
him its "First Annual Award for Outstanding Contributions to Health Law 
Literature."
<P>
Mr. Goldman has served on Michigan State Bar Committees on Medical-Legal 
Issues and Rights of the Mentally Disabled.  Since 1978 he has been a 
lecturer for a variety of University of Michigan Continuing Medical 
Education programs.  He also serves on the editorial board of the 
Journal of Critical Care.
<P>

In 1993 Mr. Goldman was a member of the White House legal audit task 
force on health care reform.  This position gave him the opportunity to 
work on the Clinton health reform plan.




