<HEAD>
<TITLE>Sean Auton</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>

<HR><P><H3>Sean Auton </H3><P> 


Sean Auton is an honors graduate of the University of Michigan and a 1995 
graduate of its law school. 
<P>
 He worked at the Medical Center since 
1991 as a computer network consultant and systems programmer before 
joining the Medical Center Attorneys' Office.  
<P>
Prior to joining the 
Attorney's office, his work included designing, testing, and implementing 
high speed networks, programming end-user applications and network 
monitoring software, relational database programming, design and
implementation, and integration of department and University accounting 
systems.
<P>
Mr. Auton interned at the American Association for the Advancement of 
Science in 1994, and while there published several articles including 
pieces on actions taken against scientists and mathematicians by the House 
Committee on Un-American Activities, legal analysis of human rights 
violations perpetrated against members of the scientific community, and 
helping to draft the American Medical Association position statement on 
the participation of physicians in Death Penalty cases. 
<P>
 In addition, Mr. 
Auton also sat on a joint panel with the National Institute of Health 
examing patient privacy and ethics of the National Healthcare Reform 
initiative. 
<P>
While at the University of Michigan Law School, Mr. Auton's work included 
an analysis of patent rights under the Uruguay Round of the GATT 
agreement, the licensing of technology to foreign nations, as well as 
constitutional analysis of citizen' privacy rights.  




