<TITLE>Virtual Reality</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="EEEEEE">
<B> <IMG hspace=3 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H2>Virtual Reality</H2>

<P>
Dr.-Ing. Klaus-Peter Beier
Director, University of Michigan Virtual Reality Laboratory
Associate Professor & Research Scientist
<P>
The enabling technologies of immersive virtual reality allow for
head-referenced viewing of virtual worlds that are computer generated. The
combination of depth perception through stereo viewing, look-around and
walk-around capability, and realistic interactions of humans with a full
scale representation of virtual objects provides an unrivaled tool for the
communication of information, the visualization of processes, and the
creative expression of ideas.
<P>
The talk will give a short introduction into the existing technologies of
virtual reality, will outline benefits and problems, and will present
several examples from the engineering area.
<P> The concept of a new course Eng
477 "PRINCIPLES OF VIRTUAL REALITY" will be outlined.
<P> This course is being
developed around the new facilities of the Media Union and will be offered
to all schools and colleges in fall 1996.
<HR>

<DD> Klaus-Peter Beier
<DD>Virtual Reality Laboratory  
<DD> Phone:  (313) 764-4296
<DD> Fax:    (313) 936-8820
<DD>e-mail: beier@umich.edu
<DD> University of Michigan         
<DD>  2600 Draper, 225 NA&ME Bldg.    
<DD>Ann Arbor, MI 48109-2145




<HR>
