<center><H2>HEALTH CARE REFORM 1996 STYLE</H2>
<B>Legislative Update 104-17</B></center><P>

<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/legalert.htm">Current Alert</A> |<A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/terms.htm"> Glossary</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/contact.htm">Contact Legislators </A>| <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/archive.htm">Archives</A>| legal issues |  <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/fax.htm">send back</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/index.htm">Index</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/survey.htm"> Survey </A><BR clear=all><HR noshade>



<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>




		104th Second Session of Congress<p>


			104 - 17<p>


								February 27, 1996<p>


<p>


<b>	HEALTH CARE REFORM 1996 STYLE</b><p>


<p>


<b><u>S.1028 -- Minimum Reform</u></b><p>


In July 1995, Senator Nancy Kassebaum (R-KS), retiring chair of the Senate Labor and Human
Resources Committee, introduced a bill, S.1028, requiring insurance companies to provide
portability of coverage and to stop denying coverage for pre-existing conditions.  The bill moved
quickly out of committee in August and into legislative oblivion while insurers added up the cost
of these changes.  As the presidential election moves closer, the Senate leadership has decided to
put health care system reform back on the front burner, with floor action possible by mid-April. <p>


<p>


	If signed into law, S. 1028 would provide the following:<p>


- Group health plans would not be able to impose more than a 12-month exclusion for people with
pre-existing medical conditions, defined as a condition "for which medical advice, diagnosis, care,
or treatment was recommended or received within the 6-month period ending on the day before
the effective date of the coverage."<p>


- Workers who kept up coverage could not be excluded for health reasons or subjected to a new
waiting period when they switched jobs or group policies.  If a person did lose coverage, the
18-months of COBRA coverage would also be accessible.  COBRA is part of a former budget
agreement that allows workers to quit a job but continue to have health insurance coverage if they
pay the premium.<p>


- After three years of group and COBRA coverage, workers could not be excluded because of
health or medical history.<p>


- Children are added to the group health plan when they are born or adopted.<p>


<p>


The bill has broad bi-partison support.  Currently there are 44 co-sponsors - 21 Republicans and
23 Democrats.  They are: Senators Kassebaum (R-KS), Kennedy (D-MA), Frist (R-TN), Dodd
(D-CT), Jeffords (R-VT), Mikulski (D-MD), Gregg (R-NH), Wellstone (D-MN), Gorton
(R-WA), Pell (D-RI), Hatch (R-UT), Simon (D-IL), Chafee (R-RI), Lieberman (D-CT), Cohen
(R-ME), Simpson (R-WY), Rockefeller (D-WV), Kerry (D-NE), Inouye (D-HI), Glenn (D-OH),
Dorgan (D-ND), Snowe (R-ME), Bennett (R-UT), Hatfield (R-OR), Abraham (R-MI), McCain
(R-AZ), Ford (D-KY), Stevens (R-AK), McConnell (R-KY), Graham (D-FL), DeWine (R-OH),
Mosley-Braun (D-IL), Daschle(D-SD), Warner (R-VA), Pressler (R-SD), Hollings (D-SC),
Cochran (R-MS), Pryor (D-AR), Kerry (D-MA), Leahy (D-VT), Kohl (D-WI), Lugar (R-IN),
Robb (D-VA), and Boxer (D-CA).<p>


<u><b>The Status:</b></u><p>


The bill cleared the Labor and Human Resources Committee on August 2, 1995, by a unanimous
16-to-0 vote.  The Senate has agreed to vote on the bill some time between mid-April, and early
May.  It is unclear whether Senator Kassebaum will accept any floor amendments to the bill. 
Many think that any floor amendments to the bill will jeopardize its passage.  An amendment from
Senator Jeffords (VT) that would prevent health plans from imposing lifetime benefit caps, and an
amendment from Senators Wellstone (MN) and Domenici (NM) on mental health parity are both
possible, if amendments are accepted.   <p>


<p>


<u><b>The Problem:</b></u><p>


The largest opposition to the bill comes from insurers who largely sell individual policies.  The
Health Insurance Association of America believes the bill will increase premiums on individual
health insurances from 10 to 30 percent.  But, a study released by the American Academy of
Actuaries said that the bill will have "minimum impact" on individual premiums, causing rates to
rise 3 to 5 percent over three or more years.   Also, there are  a number of  business groups who
oppose certain parts of the legislation, including any potential amendments on lifetime caps and
mental health parity.<p>


<p>


<u><b>What can I do?</b></u><p>


It is imperative that you write/fax, call, or e-mail your senators about your support for S.1028, the
Health Insurance Reform Act, and any amendment concerning mental health parity, and the
elimination of lifetime caps.  If your senators are not a co-sponsor of the bill, please urge them to
become one.<p>


<b>Call:</b>  You can reach your senators' Washington offices by calling the Capitol Operator at
(202)224-3121.  When you call, be sure to mention that you are a constituent and a child and
adolescent psychiatrist.<p>


<b>E-mail:</b>  The e-mail address for on-line congressional offices can be accessed through the
document center's web site: gopher://una.hh.lib.umich.edu/o/socsci/poliscilaw/uslegi/conemail.<p>


<b>Write/Fax:</b> Write or fax a letter or postcard to your senators' Washington office.  Addresses are
included below. To find out if your senators' have a public fax number you may call the
Academy's Department of Government Affairs at 800-333-7636. <p>


The Honorable, U.S. Senate, Washington, DC 20510<p>


<p>


<u><b>What do I say?</b></u><p>


Following are some talking points you may want to mention during your call or include in your
letter:<p>


 	There are currently over 40 million Americans without health insurance.<p>


 	About 21 million Americans lack health coverage because of pre-existing conditions.<p>


 	Over 80 million Americans have preexisting conditions that could make it difficult for them to
maintain health coverage when changing jobs.<p>


 	Currently, children and adolescents with mental illnesses are denied coverage for up to six months
if their parent changes jobs.<p>


 	Today there is increased progress in terms of diagnosis and treatment for children and adolescents
with mental illnesses.<p>


<p>


If you have any questions, please call the Academy's Department of Government Affairs at
800-333-7636.<p>


<p>



</body>
