<title>NGA Medicaid Proposal: not good for children and adolescents</title>
<meta name="Author" content="mc">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>

<BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000 link="#CC0000" alink="#FF3300">
<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/">Up</A> | <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/aacap/<HR>

<IMG SRC= "/web/aacap/logogov.gif"width=200 height=110 align=left border=1> <BR>


<center><H2>NGA Medicaid Proposal: not good for children and adolescents</H2>
<B>Legislative Update 104-16</B></center><P>

<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/legalert.htm">Current Alert</A> |<A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/terms.htm"> Glossary</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/contact.htm">Contact Legislators </A>| <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/archive.htm">Archives</A>| legal issues |  <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/fax.htm">send back</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/index.htm">Index</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/survey.htm"> Survey </A><BR clear=all><HR noshade>



<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>





<CENTER><B><A NAME="	104th_2nd_">	104th 2nd </A>Session of Congress
									February 22, 1996</B><p>



<u><b>The issue:</b></u><p>


After the President vetoed the Congressional proposal to restructure Medicaid, there was little
hope that a budget agreement would be reached.  On February 6th, at a National Governors
Association meeting, the governors agreed on their own separate Medicaid reform.  The plan 
attempts to reduce Federal and State budget deficits at the expense of low income consumers who
lack other means to obtain needed health care.  <p>


The NGA proposal will jeopardize many children and adolescents who receive Medicaid services. 
It will: <p>


	<p>


- Eliminate the current federal definition of disability. The governors' proposal would allow states
to choose whether or not to cover people with different disabilities.  The state funds available
would inevitably determine coverage and services. This will result in children and adolescents with
mental illness losing coverage in one state while a neighboring state's definition would include
them.<p>


- Reduce the current requirement that Medicaid eligible children be provided services to age 12. 
EPSDT coverage is now given to children through age 21.   This proposal will cut benefits to
children with physical and emotional disorders over the age of 12, who need the vital Medicaid
screening and services to treat their illnesses.<p>


- Implement a Medicaid block grant.  The NGA proposal, through "block granting," would give
states more authority over the Medicaid program.  According to the plan, each state will have a
maximum federal allocation that will be available only if the state puts up a matching percentage,
but states would be permitted to reduce their matching funds to 40%, down from 50%.  This
would reduce Medicaid spending over 7 years, and decrease the amount and adequacy of
Medicaid-funded services to children and adolescents with mental illnesses.<p>

<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>
<p>


<p>


<u><b>The threat:</b></u><p>


This proposal is a very real threat. This week, the House and Senate are holding hearings on the
governors' proposal, which is being drafted into legislative language by Committee staff. 
Although the President and Congressional Republicans were praising the governors for their
work, neither side has fully endorsed the proposal. If the proposal passes Congress, and, even
though the President does not agree with certain components of the bill (ie: the definition of
disability being left up to the states), we must remember that he is a former governor, and chair of
the National Governors Association. <p>


<p>
<IMG vspace=6 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

<u><b>What can I do?</b></u><p>


It is imperative that you write/fax, call, or e-mail your concerns about the NGA's proposal to your
governor, Congressional representative, and senators'.<p>


<b>Call:</b>  You can reach your representative's and senators' Washington offices by calling the Capitol
Operator at (202)224-3121.  When you call, be sure to mention that you are a constituent and a
child and adolescent psychiatrist with concerns about the NGA's Medicaid proposal.  <p>


<b>E-mail:  </b>The e-mail address for on-line congressional offices can be accessed through the
document center's web site: gopher://una.hh.lib.umich.edu/o/socsci/poliscilaw/uslegi/conemail.<p>


<b>Write/Fax: </b>We have included a sample letter below and addresses for the leadership.  <p>


 <p>


<p>


To write:<p>


Your governor: The Honorable ____________, State Capitol, Capitol City, State, Zip<p>


Your congressperson: The Honorable ____________, U.S. House of Representatives,
Washington, DC 20515            <p>


Your senators: The Honorable ______________, U.S. Senate, Washington, DC 20510<p>


<p>


<i>Dear Representative/Senator            :<p>


<p>


	I am a child and adolescent psychiatrist with very strong concerns about the Medicaid
restructuring plan recommended by the National Governors Association on February 6. While I
recognize that changes must be made to the Medicaid program to make it more efficient, I
believe that the governors' proposal for restructuring Medicaid would have an extremely
negative impact on the lives of children and adolescents with mental illnesses.  <p>


	Medicaid is a critical source of funding for children and adolescents with mental and physical
disabilities.  Of the five million Medicaid beneficiaries with disabilities, 14% are children under
the age of 21 -- about 800,000 children.  During your negotiations, I strongly urge you to
consider the following recommendations: <p>


 	maintain the current federal definition of disability,<p>


 	maintain the current requirement that Medicaid-eligible children be provided EPSDT services
through age 21, and<p>


 	maintain the individual Federal entitlement to Medicaid.<p>


<p>


	I strongly urge you to focus on reforms that improve the program for Medicaid beneficiaries and
protect consumers against the proposals that accommodate the states' desire for fewer federal
requirements.  Please do not agree to a proposal that would roll back hard fought, justified
gains in health care for children and adolescents.<p>


<p>


Sincerely,<p>


<p>


<p>


(Your name)</i><p>


<p>


<p>


If you have any questions, please call the Office of Government Affairs at 800-333-7636.<p>






</body>



