<title>MIXED BAG FOR FDA REFORM</title>
<meta name="Author" content="mc">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>

<BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000 link="#CC0000" alink="#FF3300">
<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/">Up</A> | <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/aacap/<HR>

<IMG SRC= "/web/aacap/logogov.gif"width=200 height=110 align=left border=1> <BR>


<center><H2>MIXED BAG FOR FDA REFORM</H2>
<B>Legislative Update 104-15</B></center><P>

<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/legalert.htm">Current Alert</A> |<A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/terms.htm"> Glossary</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/contact.htm">Contact Legislators </A>| <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/archive.htm">Archives</A>| legal issues |  <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/fax.htm">send back</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/index.htm">Index</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/survey.htm"> Survey </A><BR clear=all><HR noshade>



<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>
Department of Government Affairs Legislative Update 104-15<p>


<p>


February 13, 1996, 104th 2nd Session of Congress                 <p>


<p>


Mary Crosby, Dir. Gov't Affairs, Dep. Ex. Dir, Kristin Kroeger, Ass't Dir. Gov't Affairs, Jennifer
Dexter, Legislative/Research Specialist<p>


This session, the House and Senate will focus on reform measures that could severely curtail the
Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) power.  There is a sense that the FDA has been given too
broad a mandate by Congress, resulting in the agency becoming a slow-moving bureaucracy. 
Backed by pharmaceutical and medical device manufacturers, several members of Congress are
now sponsoring or drafting bills that would redefine the FDA's role and lessen the oversight of
those two industries by the FDA.<p>


<u><b>SENATE PROPOSAL</b></u><p>


The Senate FDA reform proposal (S. 1477, "The FDA Performance and Accountability Act") was
introduced by Senator Kassebaum (R-KS).  Provisions in the bill include the following:<p>


 - It requires the FDA to comply with the existing statutory deadline of 180 days for new drug
approval, currently there is no enforcement of this time limit, and FDA approval times average
19.2 months (576 days).   In the new bill, if the review process of a new drug is not completed in
180 days, the FDA would be required to contract with outside experts for outside review, or if the
drug has already been through the United Kingdom or European Union review process
successfully, the drug is approved by default.<p>


	- It allows manufacturers to market products for "off label" use.  Currently, manufacturers can
provide information on request, and physicians can prescribe for "off label" use, but manufacturers
cannot distribute information on such uses.<p>


- It allows drugs to be approved for "off label" use if it has been used in practice for five years and
has been proven "clinically sound."  Since many psychotropic medications are prescribed
"off-label" for children, the medications used routinely for children could be approved by default.<p>


	- It eases the requirements for clinical trials on animals by requiring only one "scientifically sound"
study.  Now, the FDA interprets the law as requiring two such studies except in cases where the
results are unequivocable or the study is sufficiently large.  Some patient advocates oppose this
provision as endangering patients and taking away the FDA's flexibility in requesting data. <p>


Senator Kassebaum expects to hold hearings on the bill in late February.   <p>


<p>


<p>


<u><b>POTENTIAL HOUSE PROPOSALS</b></u><p>


No FDA reform bill has been introduced on the House side yet.  However, it is predicted that any
House proposal will remove more of the FDA safeguards than the Kassebaum bill.  Some of the
more controversial ideas include:<p>


	- a proposal to allow applicants to submit drug trial summaries instead of all of the primary data. 
The FDA claims that the complete data is crucial to the approval process.<p>


- a proposal that would allow non-governmental agencies to review applications and then make
suggestions to the FDA.<p>


If Congress fails to pass a comprehensive FDA reform bill in this session, the provisions in the
existing bills may be rewritten into smaller, more specific bills.<p>


<u><b>FDA RESPONSE</b></u><p>


The FDA is attempting to circumvent the reform by taking administrative measures to decrease
approval times.  FDA representatives point to the 42 percent decrease in approval times since
1987 as proof of their good faith effort to internally address this issue.  But critics point to the
fact that approval times are still much longer than the mandated 180 days.  FDA Commissioner,
David Kessler, has expressed his belief that any shortfalls within the agency can be fixed from
within.<p>


<u><b>ACADEMY ACTION</b></u><p>


The Academy will follow events in this debate closely, and keep the membership informed of any
action needed.  If you have any comments, or would like a copy of the bill please call the
Department of Government Affairs at (202) 966-7300.
</body>

