<head>
<title>IDEA UP FOR CRITICAL
REAUTHORIZATION IN 1996</title>
<meta name="Author" content="mc">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head><BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000 link="#CC0000" alink="#FF3300">
<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/">Up</A> | <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/aacap/<HR>

<IMG SRC= "/web/aacap/logogov.gif"width=200 height=110 align=left border=1> <BR>


<center><H2>IDEA up for Critical
Reauthorization in 1996</H2>
Legislative Update 104-14</center><P>

<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/legalert.htm">Current Alert</A> |<A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/terms.htm"> Glossary</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/contact.htm">Contact Legislators </A>| <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/archive.htm">Archives</A>| legal issues |  <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/fax.htm">send back</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/index.htm">Index</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/survey.htm"> Survey </A><BR clear=all><HR noshade>



<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>


Mary Crosby, Dir. Gov't Affairs, Dep. Ex. Dir.<p>


Kristin Kroeger, Ass't Dir. Gov't Affairs<p>


<center><H3>104th 2nd Session of Congress<p>


						February 13, 1996<p>


Status of the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA)</H3></CENTER><p>


The Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA), P.L. 94-142, guarantees children with
disabilities a free and appropriate public education.  The federal government enacted this law in
1974, because some school systems were failing to meet the educational needs of children with
disabilities.  This law has allowed millions of children, with physical and mental disabilities to be
educated in regular classrooms.<p>


IDEA is up for reauthorization in 1996, and while Congress is expected to reauthorize this vital
law, it will be changed. There is some apprehension that the proposed bill and the amendments
that will be introduced will discriminate against children with serious emotional disorders. The
Academy is concerned about diminishing the guarantee to educate children with serious emotional
disorders.  The concern grows out of the linking of serious emotional disturbances with violent
behavior.<p>


The Senate Subcommittee on Disability, chaired by Bill Frist (R-TN) and the House
Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Youth, and Families, chaired by Randy Cunningham
(R-51-CA) are the authorizing bodies in each house.  The Senate plans to introduce its bill in late
February, and do subcommittee amendments in late March.  The House has not announced its
schedule. <p>


<b><u>Potential Problem</b>:</u><p>


The point of IDEA is to protect all children with disabilities from discrimination in receiving an
education; however, children with serious emotional disorders who are disruptive are singled out
in the current Senate bill.  The issue of violence in schools could result in discrimination against
these children.  The Senate language could deny a free and appropriate public education to any
child seen as "seriously disruptive." The current law provides for the child to remain ("stay-put")
in school until an agreement with the parents/guardians is worked out.  Temporary, alternate
placement can be used if a weapon is brought to school. Under the Senate bill, the "stay-put" rule
is not preserved, and the child is removed from the current placement into an alternative
placement, which may or may not be suitable for the child.<p>


<p>


The Academy supports the existing law, and opposes any amendment that would discriminate
against children with serious emotional disorders, who could become a magnet for attention and
removal.  Reauthorization in 1996 is critical because next year's Congress may have fewer IDEA
supporters, but reauthorization must not come with a threat to children with serious emotional
disorders. IDEA must keep the features that make it work for children with disabilities, their
parents, and their schools.<p>


<u><b>What Should I Do?</b></u><p>


Visit, Call, or Write/Fax/E-mail your representative and senators. <p>


<b>Visit:</b>  Congress will be in recess from February 9-26.  This is a great time to visit your
representative and senators in their home district.  Or you may choose to attend one of the many
town hall meetings they are holding,  To find out when your representative and senators are
available or the schedule of his/her town meetings, please contact their district office listed in your
telephone book.<p>


<b>Call:</b>  You can reach your representative and senators Washington offices by calling the Capitol
Operator at (202)224-3121.  When you call be sure to mention that you are a constituent and a
child and adolescent psychiatrist with concerns about the reauthorization of the Individuals with
Disabilities Education Act because...(See "what should I say").<p>


<b>Write/Fax:  </b>	The Honorable (full name), U.S. House of Representatives, Washington DC 20515		The Honorable (full name), U.S. Senate, Washington, D.C. 20510<p>


<b>E-mail</b>:  The e-mail address for on-line congressional offices can be accessed through the
document centers wed site: gopher://una.hh.lib.umich.edu/o/socsci/poliscilaw/uslegi/conemail.<p>


<u><b>What Do I Say?</b></u><p>


Discipline and the supposed "cost" of educating children with disabilities are why some groups are
trying to weaken IDEA.  We want to get the message to Congress that IDEA is a good law, it
works, and that we want to reauthorize it, not weaken it.  It is essential that you call or write your
congressional representatives immediately and express your (1) support for the law and, (2)
concern that its protections will be weakened.  The following are some key points to make when
writing your senators and representatives:<p>


<i><b> 	Don't use disciplinary measures as an excuse to improperly exclude or expel children with
disabilities:</b></i> IDEA already contains adequate prosecutions for all children.  Inappropriate
segregation or expulsion solves nothing; it just increases lifelong costs to society.  Children with
serious emotional disorders should be receiving treatment.  Providers and parents should have a
part in decisions to move these children.<p>


 	<i><b>Don't dismantle IDEA just to reduce costs:</b></i> Everyone is concerned about reducing waste and
increasing efficiency.  But do not randomly, carelessly, or haphazardly alter the law in the name of
reducing costs.  It is critical to provide adequately for the educational needs of children with
disabilities within their local public schools. <p>


<i><b> 	Education is the best investment anyone can make in the life of a child with a disability:</b></i> By
receiving a good education, children with serious emotional disturbances will be best prepared to
fully participate in and be an asset to society.  Effective education and related services save
money by reducing lifelong dependency.  This is the best investment to make, which will be
recouped many times over.<p>

<HR>



<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/">Up</A> | <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/aacap/
