<TITLE>legal 13</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000 link="#CC0000" alink="#FF3300">
<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/">Up</A> | <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/aacap/<HR>

<IMG SRC= "/web/aacap/logogov.gif"width=200 height=110 align=left border=1> <BR>


<center><H2>Why is NIH relieved? What about SAMHSA?</H2>
Legislative Update 104-13</center><P>

<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/legalert.htm">Current Alert</A> |<A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/terms.htm"> Glossary</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/contact.htm">Contact Legislators </A>| <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/archive.htm">Archives</A>| legal issues |  <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/fax.htm">send back</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/index.htm">Index</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/survey.htm"> Survey </A><BR clear=all><HR noshade>



<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>


<center>Why is NIH relieved? What about SAMHSA?<p>


</center>
	Before adjourning the first session of the 104th Congress, legislators acted on two important
issues, approving funds for the National Institutes of Health and eliminating funds for the
Department of Defense program for training psychologists to prescribe psychotropic
medications.  The Academy lobbied for both actions.  Academy members and the AACAP
Department of Government Affairs worked during 1995 to increase NIH funding while Congress
appeared determined to cut all programs.  At the same time, a grassroots campaign in key
Congressional districts was organized to assist the APA in its efforts to end the DoD program.<p>


 <p>


	Balanced budget talks between President Clinton and the Congress are at a stalemate.  Both sides
have retreated to their corners in hopes that their differences will be resolved by the November
election.  Their constant disagreement over many appropriations bills in the last two months, has
managed to shut down the federal government twice and establish short-term continuing
resolutions which fund agencies at either the House or the FY '95 appropriation, which ever is
lowest.  Those programs slated to be cut received only 75% of their FY '95 levels.<p>


<p>


$$NIH, NIMH$$	Funding for the National Institutes of Health (NIH) and, consequently,	the National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH) was stalled in the budget negotiation gridlock
until January, when negotiators attached appropriations to pending legislation, which then
funded NIH through the end of the fiscal year.  It is particularly satisfying that NIH received a
5.7 percent increase over the fiscal year 1995 amount, for a total of $11.9 billion for all
institutes.  NIMH is scheduled to receive a 4.8 percent jump over last year's funding.<p>


<p>


SAMHSA,  et al.	Unfortunately, this new approach of "targeting appropriations" did not have as		great of an effect on other Labor, HHS, and Education programs.   On January 26, Congress
passed another continuing resolution which would fund all  other programs under the Labor,
HHS, Education bill  until March 15 at FY "95 levels or the House-or Senate-passed levels,
whichever is lowest.  These programs include SAMHSA, CMHS, and all disability education
programs.<p>


 <p>


	Medicaid &amp; Medicare -- too many unresolved differences = Deadlock	With the budget negotiations stalled, proposals to reform Medicaid, Medicare, and the welfare
reform system are left without a vehicle for passage.  Since Medicare, Medicaid and welfare
reforms decreased federal financing for treating low-income children and adolescents with
serious emotional disorders, and for subsidizing graduate medical education, this gridlock is
favorable for many of the Academy's areas of concern.<p>


	The deadlock in this debate continues to be on fundamental differences - both in funding levels
and policy.  Senator Majority Leader Robert Dole (R-KS) said January 23 the chance of
resolving these differences are "pretty unlikely....We are just coming from different directions."<p>


<p>


	Under the House-Senate passed budget reconciliation bill, the Medicaid program would be
transformed into a block grant program, with states given the opportunity to determine eligibility
and services.  Savings for this new plan are estimated at $163 billion, down from the $170
billion that was originally proposed.  On an optimistic note, Sen. Chafee's amendment, which
required coverage for low-income pregnant women and children, aged 12 and under, was
retained in conference.  Unfortunately, his mandate for states to cover children and adults with
disabilities was dropped from the conference report and never reinstated.<p>


<p>


	Conferees dropped an amendment sponsored by Senator Kent Conrad (D-ND), requiring
non-discriminary coverage of treatment for mental illness.  But, Senator Pete Domenici (R-NM)
successfully included report language that would require state Medigrant plans to "assure the
quality of services, including such services provided to individuals with chronic mental and
physical illnesses."  The report language reads, "States will provide . . . quality assurance
programs for individuals with chronic mental illness.  For this purpose, chronic mental illness
shall be defined through diagnosis, disability, and duration, and shall include disorders with
psychotic symptoms, such as schizophrenia, schizo-affective disorder, manic depression, and
autism, as well as severe forms of other mental disorders, such as major depression, panic
disorder, and obsessive compulsive disorder."  <p>


<p>


	The Clinton Administration strongly opposes block granting Medicaid.  The Administration
would prefer to have a "capped entitlement" approach to reforming Medicaid.  But there is
serious doubt that the administration will be able to overturn Congressional support for a block
grant.  <p>


<p>


	The Senate-House Conference agreement on Medicare dropped Academy supported positions on
point-of-service, antitrust and medical liability reform.  The conference agreement establishes a
Graduate Medical Education and Teaching Hospital Trust Fund provision with five accounts
totaling $13.5  billion over 7 years.  The reconciliation bill would have decreased both direct and
indirect financial support for teaching hospitals and resident physicians. <p>


<p>


SSI, A Bad Year	 On December 20, the conference committee reported out the Personal Responsibility and Work
Opportunity Act of 1995 (also known as the welfare reform bill,  H.R. 4).  This bill, 	caught in the budget gridlock, includes the children's SSI program.  The Academy has urged 	reasonable modifications of this cash benefit support for families with children who are disabled,
but the final committee bill eliminates the individualized functional assessment (IFA), and
denies cash and health benefits to families who do not meet new criteria.  The bill creates a
"two-tier" system of eligibility for children to receive their cash benefit.  Once the child is
determined to meet the definition of disability, the amount of cash benefit will be determined by
the following criteria: For a child under 6--such individual has a medical impairment that
severely limits the individual's ability to function in a manner appropriate to individuals of the
same age and who without special personal assistance would require specialized care outside the
individual's home; or<p>


For a child age 6 or over-- such individual requires personal care assistance with: (a) at least two
activities of daily living; (b) continual 24-hour supervision or monitoring to avoid causing injury
or harm to self or others, or the administration of medical treatment; and who without such
assistance would require full-time or part-time specialized care outside the individual's home."  <p>


<p>


	Children with disabilities who meet these criteria will receive 100% of the benefit amount
provided by law.  While the disabled children who do not meet these criteria will only receive
75% of the benefit amount provided by current law.  The conference report also adopted the
Senate language requiring a "grandfather" provision which modifies the effective date for these
changes for January 1997.  The Academy opposed this two-tiered system.<p>


<p>


	On January 9, President Clinton vetoed the welfare reform bill, (H.R. 4), saying it "does little to
move people from welfare to work."  If negotiations over the budget-reconciliation bill collapse,
it would take an intense Congressional effort to produce a freestanding welfare reform bill that is
acceptable to the president or that can override a veto.<p>


Psychologists Prescribing 	In another important decision, U.S. House and Senate conferees last month	agreed to end  the $4 million per year Psychopharmacology Demonstration 		Program (PDP), an experimental program that would train psychologists to prescribe medication. 
The PDP program was eliminated as part of the Republican commitment to abolish wasteful
spending.  The conference report, filed in December, directs the Secretary of the Department of
Defense to "terminate the demonstration program for training military psychologists in the
prescription of psychotropic medications . . . The Secretary may not enroll any new participants"
in the PDP.   Adoption of this language is a major success for all of the individuals and
organizations that have worked to end this DoD program since its inception in 1989.<p>


<p>


V-Chip, Such a Deal!	As part of the stalled Telecommunication Reform Bill, the "v-chip" legislation 	would require television sets with screens of at least 12 inches to include special  		devices called "v-chips," which would allow parents to screen out materials they did not wish their
children to view.  The cable and broadcast industry would have one year to develop ratings for
sex and violence that would be electronically sent to television sets.<p>


<p>


For weeks, the House and Senate were at odds on language in the bill that would establish
criminal penalties for people who make material deemed "indecent" available to minors on-line. 
Just recently, an agreement was made that would included this language and the "v-chip"
language.  The bill passed in Febrary and is expected to be signed by the President , (PL 94-142,
have been completed by both the House and Senate subcommittees that oversee this legislation. 
The House bill was drafted by the majority staff of the Economic and Educational Opportunities
Committee, while the Senate bill represents a more bipartisan approach from the Subcommittee
on Disability Policy.<p>


<p>


	This year, "discipline" is the main focus of the reauthorization.  The House bill does not reflect
any significant changes to the current discipline language.  But, the Senate bill has significant 
changes to the discipline language which could deny "free and appropriate education" to any child
seen as "seriously disruptive" or "who is involved with dangerous weapons or drugs, or engages
in, or is substantially likely to engage in serious bodily injury."  With this language as it reads,  the
"stay-put" provision will not be applied if a child falls in either of these two categories.  As a
result,  the child will be kept in the alternative educational placement.   <p>


<p>


	As of this writing, legislative schedules have not been set, but both House and Senate staff
anticipate action early in the year and have promised that once the bill is reviewed and revised
(marked-up) by the committees, it will move quickly through the committees and to the floor.<p>


+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<p>


<p>


What can you do?<p>


Members of Congress or the Administration appreciate hearing from people who support specific
actions/positions they have taken.  You can encourage more support by thanking the following
folks:   <p>


1)Write, fax, or e-mail President Clinton, House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt, Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle
expressing your sincere appreciation for the increase in NIMH funding.  Be sure to explain what
this funding increase means to your continuing research.<p>


<p>


2)Write to President Clinton thanking him for supporting children and their families when he 
highlighted the importance of the V-chip legislation and a rating system for television programing
in his State of the Union Address.  <p>


If you have any questions, or need additional information, please contact the Academy's
Department of Government Affairs at (800) 333-7636.<p>


The WWW Internet address is http://www.med.umich.edu/aacap.  The e-mail addresses for
on-line Congressional offices can be accessed through the Documents Center's web site:
http://www.lib.umich. edu/libhome/Documents.center/federal.html.<p>


<p>


Coming Issues:	IDEA Reauthorization<p>


<address></i>		Health Care Reform 1996<i>
</body>

