<center><H2> Medicare Reform and Graduate Medical Education</H2>
<B>Legislative Update 104-10</B></center><P>

<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/legalert.htm">Current Alert</A> |<A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/terms.htm"> Glossary</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/contact.htm">Contact Legislators </A>| <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/archive.htm">Archives</A>| legal issues |  <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/fax.htm">send back</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/index.htm">Index</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/survey.htm"> Survey </A><BR clear=all><HR noshade>



<IMG vspace=4 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>

<H2><B>September 12, 1995 Legislative Alert No	104-10</B> </H2>


<BR>
Mary Crosby, Deputy Executive Director<BR>
Kristin Kroeger, Assistant Director<BR><P>
<HR>
Subject(s) : Medicare Reform and Graduate Medical Education.

<HR>
<CENTER><H2>MEDICARE REFORM<BR>
AND<BR>GRADUATE MEDICAL EDUCATION
</H2>
</CENTER>
<P> 


The Leadership in the House and Senate decided that $270 million will be saved during the next seven years of the Medicare program. Graduate Medical Education funding has always been an easy source for savings because it did not affect patients'benefits, the payment schedule, or the copayments and deductibles.  It did influence the amount of direct and indirect payments that are made to teaching hospitals.<P>

Child and adolescent psychiatry training experienced the results of  Congressional actions that cut funding for the seventh year of specialty training, then the sixth year, and now the biggest threat: The elimination of funding support except for a single specialty.  This possibility has already caused the training program leaders for child and adolescent psychiatry to come together to contemplate strategies for preserving training programs.  

Background	<BR>
Currently, between $5 billion and $6 billion in Medicare funds are funneled into Graduate Medicare Education. This spending is 7.1 percent of Medicare's total annual expenses and 29 percent of the overall cost of graduate medical training. <P>

The funding is high, but it can be defended as protecting the best system of health care in the world. But the world is changing and the way medical training is supported is changing with it. The strategy right now is to make plans for change before the decisions are taken out of your hands.<P>

Message:  <font size=4><B> Medicare GME funding must be the object of reform not the object of continual cuts without new direction or support.</B></font size=4><P>

Medicare GME payments are currently made to teaching hospitals and facilities in two forms: 
<UL>
<LI>as direct medical expense payments, which subsidize the actual cost of resident physicians and the slots they hold at teaching facilities; and 
<LI>indirect medical expense payments, which cover non-salary expenditures incurred by hospitals as a result of the care provided by these residents.
</UL>

Direct (resident) payments are being addressed in a proposals being circulated by Rep. Nancy Johnson (R-CT), Ben Cardin (D-MD) and a few other groups.  Rep. Johnson developed the reform at the behest of House Ways and Means Health Subcommittee Chair William Thomas.  The reform provisions could very well be included in the upcoming budget reconciliation act.<P>

<H3>The key areas in the plans are</H3>:

<UL>
<LI>	Limit the number of physician resident slots to 110 percent (1.1 positions for every U.S. medical graduate) -- a 30 percent reduction in available positions supported by DME subsidies.  Currently, GME payments support 1.4 residency slots for every U.S. medical school graduate at a median salary of  $36,000.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Rep. Johnson would combine a nationwide moratorium on the number of resident slots with an institution-by-institution position cap to enforce this limit. The AMA approved policy consistent with this step in June, but without the numbers. The point is to reduce the &quot;over supply&quot; of physicians in the workforce and to move toward the $270 billion savings goal.   The moratorium on Medicare funded positions would begin after July 1, 1995.  The number would then be reduced per program by 5 percent in 1996 and 1997. 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Hospitals would not be allowed to eliminate internal medicine, family practice, or pediatrics residency slots.  Subsidies for non-citizen medical training would be terminated by 1998 and physician over-specialization would be discouraged by only allowing GME student support to the first accreditation level.  Medicare now pays one-half the cost of training beyond this point to specialty certifications.  Students seeking a geriatrics specialty would be exempt from this stipulation and still receive full funding.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>also, this measure attempts to even out payments for &quot;high-cost&quot; programs.  It would also separate direct and indirect GME costs from calculation of per capita costs in "Medicare Choice" plans (the voucher program outlined in House GOP Medicare reform proposals) and distribute these funds directly to hospitals and facilities incurring medical education costs. 
</UL>
<UL>
<LI>The proposal also targets subsidies to teaching hospitals with the highest uncompensated care case loads and severity of illness factors while also reducing, over three years, payments for non-salary costs.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Finally, it would call for the establishment of a commission to explore a broad-based all-payer financing mechanism.  The measure does not, however, set up an all-payer fund to make a specific recommendation in this direction. 
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Rep. Cardin, who plans to introduce his plan later this session has concerns about the Johnson proposal because the bottom line is that her proposal takes away nearly 50 percent of public GME support without creating an alternative source for funding.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>No proposal has yet to emerge in the Senate.  The House will act first (this week) on Medicare spending proposals and the reaction to Johnson's proposal could influence the Senate's proposal.   
</UL><P>

<H3><B>Other Proposals:</B></H3><P>

<UL>
<LI>Some of  the proposals suggest stopping the resident subsidy after three years of training -- the amount of study required to gain initial medical board eligibility.    This would be a means to reduce the over-supply of physicians in the workforce and create an incentive to physicians to focus on internal and general medicine -- shifting attention away from specializations.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Another idea is to restrict or phase out support for foreign medical students.  Currently, there are 40 percent more residency slots available than there are graduates from American medical schools.   The argument in favor of impeding non-citizen access to these positions is connected to the bottomline--the system simply does not have the resources to underwrite training for students coming from abroad.   Moreover, as slots are reduced and competition becomes stiffer, support for foreign medical students is a corner that can be cut.  But this concept has triggered near panic from inner city and rural places.<BR>
The second tier of this position is that the job market will correct the problems associated with filling the positions if adjustments, such as those noted are made to bring more general practitioners into the medical community.
</UL>



<UL>
<LI>Indirect GME support:  On a different track, the debate regarding the indirect GME costs is shaped around efforts to reduce and change the way these funds are distributed.  Currently,  IME allocations are based on a target payment of 7.7 percent for every 10 percent increment of teaching intensity--a variable measured by the ratio of hospital residents to beds.  
</UL>

Many argue that this approach actually encourages hospitals to maintain resident positions--even in the midst of downsizing.  Johnson's proposal would ratchet down the target to 4.5 percent of 1998 and charge Medicare's Prospective Payment Advisory Commission (ProPAC) with crafting an alternative formula within the next year.  Though the 4.5 percent rate matches a ProPAC recommendation, their suggestion did not factor in the impact of Medicare's funds.  

<UL>
<LI>As a result, if such decreases were enacted, GME would be taking a double hit.  Combining proposed DME and IME adjustments results in an aggregate funding decrease of more than 50 percent.  THIS IS DISPROPORTIONATE WHEN COMPARED TO THE RELATIVE SIZE OF GME SPENDING WITHIN THE MEDICARE PROGRAM.
</UL>

<H3><B>How to make up for the shortfall, however it comes:</B>
</H3>
<UL>
<LI>the Council on Graduate Medical Education suggested the creation of a transition program that could ease some of the pressure -- especially for facilities that are extremely reliant on foreign medical students.  
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>the creation of an all-payer funding mechanism to provide a dedicated GME funding source by taxing payers within the health care system.  Rep. Cardin's legislation would create such a fund by taxing payers on a premium basis.  Rep. Johnson may call for the establishment of a commission to study this idea and other related issues but not recommending implementation of an all-payer fund.
</UL>
<UL>
<LI>Regardless of what Congress decides to do about Medicare, Medicare HMOs will grow rapidly in coming years.  That means big changes ahead in the way the program pays for health care services and products and assesses their quality.  The Academy's managed care efforts have always been designed to support managed treatment that allows child and adolescent psychiatrists to be the decision makers for the treatment plan -- treatment guidelines, outcomes projects, the newsletter for benefits managers and managed care directors (managed care report), interactions with managed care medical directors, etc. are part of that effort.  
</UL><P>

The Academy has responded positively to recommendations by psychiatry training leadership to sanction one certificate for both general and child and adolescent psychiatry.  The Academy has always defended GME support for specialties with a shortage of practitioners, which applies to child and adolescent psychiatry.  
<HR>

<B>How to contact legislators and let us know about your action</B><P>

Legislators, Senators, should be contacted by both teachers and residents.  Let them know how these changes would influence your program.Sorry, we don't have sample letter for this legislative alert<P>

If you have any questions, or need additional information, please contact the Academy's Department of Government Affairs at (800) 333-7636


Whether you are calling or writing Washington or the field office, let them know you are a constituent.  





