<HR><IMG SRC= "/web/aacap/logogov.gif"width=200 height=110 align=left border=1> <BR>

 <center><H2><B>August 1, 1995 Legislative Alert No	</B> </H2></center>


<A HREF="/web/aacap/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/legalert.htm">Current Alert</A> |<A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/terms.htm"> Glossary</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/contact.htm">Contact Legislators </A>| <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/archive.htm">Archives</A>| legal issues |  <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/fax.htm">send back</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/index.htm">Index</A> | <A HREF="/web/aacap/govafair/survey.htm"> Survey </A><BR clear=all><HR noshade>

<IMG vspace=2 SRC= "/web/images/dot_clear.gif"> <BR>
<H3>AACAP DEPARTMENT OF GOVERNMENT AFFAIRS</H3>



<H3><B>August 1, 1995 Legislative Alert No	</B> </H3>


<BR>
Mary Crosby, Deputy Executive Director<BR>
Kristin Kroeger, Assistant Director<BR><P>


<HR>
Subjects :
<B><OL>
<LI>FEDERAL SUPPORT FOR RESEARCH.
<LI>CHILDREN'S MENTAL HEALTH SERVICES.
<LI>MEDICARE GRADUATE MEDICAL EDUCATION FUNDING.
</OL></B>
<HR>
<CENTER><H2>DEEP FUNDING CUTS A REALITY?</H2>
<H3>STATUS CHECK AFTER THE SECOND 100 DAYS<BR>
WHAT COMES AFTER THE AUGUST RECESS?</H3>
</CENTER>
<b>DIRE PREDICTIONS  MAY COME TRUE</b>:<P> 

The full House Appropriations Committee confirmed slashing cuts in Labor, HHS, Education program funds approvedby the Subcommittee on July 12.  <u>Overall, 176 programs were terminated by the House Committee, cutting the three agencies budgets by $9.3 billion.</u> <P>


 Many programs that serve children and adolescents with mental illnesses are affected. 
<UL><LI> The Substance Abuse Mental Health Services Administration's (SAMHSA) demonstration program funding will drop from $506 million to $145 million in FY 1996, essentially ending several Center for Mental Health Services' programs, such as the Child and Adolescent Service System Program (CASSP), and programs serving people with AIDS and those who are homeless.  
<LI>Dept. of Ed. special education programs will lose $263.2 million, with termination notices given to programs for early childhood education, parent training, and personnel development.
</UL><P>

  Final action by the full House is expected before the recess.
<p>
<b>IS THERE ANY GOOD NEWS? </b>:<P>

<UL>
<LI>The Committee maintained the Center for Mental Health Services' Children's Mental Health Services Program funding ($60 million), and the  Mental Health Block Grant at $275.4 million. 
<LI>They increased the National Institutes of Health appropriations by 5.7%, with the National Institute of Mental Health approved for a 4.8% increase.  The Committee's report included supportive language for the Use, Need, Outcomes and Costs for Child and Adolescent Populations (UNOCCAP) study, and for childhood mental illnesses.
</UL>
<p>
<b>WHAT HAPPENS NEXT? </b><P>

Congress is preparing for the August recess (8/7 - 9/5) by considering legislation at a furious pace.
<UL>
<LI>Laws that are expiring <b>(IDEA/P.L.94-142, SAMHSA, Ryan White Act)</b> are lined up for reauthorization, and ALL of the <b>appropriations bills </b>(13) must be approved before October 1.  
<LI><b>Welfare reform </b>measures approved by the House are pending in the Senate, with <b>SSI </b>for thousands of children with mental illnesses threatened.
<LI><b>Medicare and Medicaid </b>revisions are scheduled for September announcements, but early leaks confirm plans for deep cuts in funding and extensive use of  block grants.  
<LI>Special issues such as <b>television and media violence, gun control,  health care reform and managed care </b>also demand attention as they pass through committee and floor consideration.
</UL>
<p>
<b><H2>Contacts with Congress needed</H2></b>

The Academy has communicated with the House and the Senate
on each of these issues, but contacts from constituents reinforce the requests for support or opposition. <P>

 <b>This is a special communication to all Academy members to reach out to members of Congress during this critical break in the first session of the 104th Congress.</b><P>

This has truly been a revolutionary seven months for Congress, both in the quantity of legislation and the scope of the policy changes generated by the House and pending in the Senate. <b>  It is still too early to make final assessments of this Congress, but there are questions that can be raised by child and adolescent psychiatrists about the direction of the proposals.</b><p> <p>
<b>What you can do:		Contact your legislators during the recess.</b>
<p>
Three issues that need immediate attention because they are particularly
important to the profession and to the children and adolescents with mental
illnesses and their families are
<OL>
<LI>federal support for research;
<LI>federal and federal/state programs to provide children's mental illness services;
<LI>federal support for medical education.
</OL>

  On each of these issues, keep the messages short, but let them know you are a child and adolescent psychiatrist and a constituent. </b><p>
<p>
<b>1.  FEDERAL SUPPORT FOR RESEARCH. </b><P>

 Message:  There is a clear role for the federal government to support research into the causes and treatment of mental illnesses.  The advances that have been made during the 1991 - 1995 Five-Year <u>National Plan for Research on Child and Adolescent Mental Disorders</u> should not be jeopardized.  The 4.8% increase recommended for NIMH funding is not excessive.  It will barely sustain ongoing research with little room for new studies and projects.
<p>
<b>2.  CHILDREN'S MENTAL HEALTH SERVICES. </b><P>

 Message:  The recommendation to maintain the funding for the Center for Mental Health Services' Children's Mental Health Services Program at the $60 million is appreciated, but the consolidating of almost all  other mental health and substance abuse programs into one demonstration lump and then cutting the funds from $531 million to $144 million is disastrous.  Do not terminate the state grants for the Child and Adolescent Service System Program (CASSP) or the grants to serve people with mental illnesses and AIDS or who are homeless.
<p>
<b>3.  MEDICARE GRADUATE MEDICAL EDUCATION FUNDING. </b><P>

 Message:  Plans to drastically reduce graduate medical education expenditures should be reconsidered.  Do not sacrifice medical students and penalize teaching hospitals in order to cut the $270 billion from Medicare as called for in the budget resolution.   Child and adolescent psychiatry is a shortage specialty, and by terminating funds for the fourth and fifth years of Medicare support, Congress will endanger the specialty that treats children and adolescents with the most serious mental illnesses.</b>
<p>
<b>How to deliver the messages: <P>

 Visiting, writing, calling, FAXING, or E-MAIL.
</b>
<p>
In addition to the regular forms of contact, such as writing and calling your
Congressional representatives, the recess offers you an opportunity to visit
the state and district offices, attend a townmeeting, arrange a breakfast or
lunch meeting, join with a consumer group (NAMI, NMHA, Fed. of Families)
representative to set up a visit, or<b> if you have a computer and modem, use
it to e-mail or fax your message to Congress. </b><p>
<HR>




