<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Psychiatry and the World Wide Web</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#EEFFFF">
<B><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>Psychiatry Navigates the Web</H1>
<I>by <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/UMpsych/staff/mhuang/">Milton P. Huang</A>, MD and <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/UMpsych/staff/nalessi/">Norman Alessi</A>, MD</I><BR>
&#169; 1995 Psychiatric Times.  Reprinted with permission. All rights reserved.<BR><P>
<DD>Whenever the Internet is discussed on televised newscasts, the images shown are invariably taken from the World Wide Web (the Web or WWW on the page, W3 in speech), one of the newest technologies created for cruising the infosphere. The Web was started up in 1989 and 1990 by Tim Berners Lee and others at CERN, the European Particle Physics Laboratory in Geneva, Switzerland, as a way to organize information for the researchers; and it has since become responsible for the majority of Internet traffic.
<P>
<DD>The Web's popularity stems from its ability to provide an easy-to-use, graphical interface for obtaining information. Its flexibility allows for the transfer of sounds, video and animation, as well as access' to documents stored in non-Web formats.
<P>
<DD>Tens of thousands of organizations now have electronic representations on the Web and the number is growing daily. Examples include the White House, the Internal Revenue Service, the National Institutes of Health, the Louvre, Fisher Scientific, Metro Goldwyn Mayer, Paramount Studios, the Rolling Stones and many more. A person 
<A HREF="http://www.whitehouse.gov/">visiting the White House</A>, for example, is greeted by a photo of the White House and access to an audio greeting from President Clinton. One can travel from this page of information to other pages including photographic tours of tile White House, lists of the president's speeches, White House news and press releases, or go on to other pages about organizations in the executive branch.
<P>
<DD>The Web is tied together by the concept of hyperlinks. When you open up a Web document, you will usually see an electronic page of text and pictures. As you read through the document, particular words or images of interest will be <A HREF="link.htm">highlighted</A>, indicating a hyperlink. Clicking your mouse on the highlighted object takes you to another document with further information about that item. (Try it!) These subsequent documents may have further hyperlinks to even more documents, thus building a complex network of information that extends among millions of computers throughout the world.
<P>
<DD>The Web provides information using a client-server model. Users run software called a "Web browser" on their "client" computer. The client connects to the Internet and demands information from a serving computer. The user can specify which server to query by giving the browser an electronic address or Uniform Resource Locator (URL). The highlighted hyperlinks in every document also contain URLs, thereby enabling the client computer to request the relevant document when the user clicks on a link.
<P>
<H2>Psychiatry on the Web</H2>

<DD>Although the Web contains information on a seemingly endless list of topics, relatively little is available on psychiatry.  This deficiency perhaps is due to a corresponding lack of involvement on the part of psychiatrists in information
technology. Nonetheless, as the Web has expanded, so too has the extent of psychiatric material available on it. In October 1994, two departments of psychiatry had home pages on the Web. By March 1995, six or seven had home pages. Now, there are more than a dozen such departments represented, e.g., the <A HREF="http://cpmcnet.columbia.edu/dept/pi/">New York Psychiatric Institute</A>, the <A HREF="http://www.pitt.edu/~wplib/">University of Pittsburgh</A>, <A HREF="http://neuroscience.ucdavis.edu/psychiatry/">UC Davis</A>, the <A HREF="http://unixg.ubc.ca:780/~psychiat/ubcp_home.html">University of British Columbia</A>, the <A HREF="http://w3socpsy.med.rug.nl/">University of Groningen</A>, <A HREF="http://www.iop.bpmf.ac.uk/">London University</A>, and the <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/UMpsych/">University of Michigan</A>. These home pages range in content, containing basic program descriptions, lists of faculty and research, and even campus maps or calendars of events.
<P>
<DD>Various psychiatric organizations and societies also have been joining the Web in increasing nurnbers, including the <A HREF="http://www.nimh.nih.gov/">National Institute of Mental Health</A>, the <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/aacap/">American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry</A> (AACAP) and recently, the American Psychiatric Association (APA). Besides descriptions of the organizations, these Web sites are also providing educational information and other resources.
<P>
<DD>The AACAP has made its patient-education series of pamphlets, "<A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/aacap/factsFam/">Facts for Families</A>," available on the Web. These cover more than 50 topics, ranging from childhood depression to sexual abuse. This information is very popular, and the number of files requested has been growing at a rate of 40 percent each month. <IMG ALIGN="RIGHT" SRC="acapchrt.gif" ALT="chart"> The requests have come from more than  forty six countries, including Estonia, South Africa, Singapore, and New Zealand.  Plans are in the works to translate these pamphlets into several different languages.
<P>
<DD>Beyond pamphlets, we are now beginning to see the growth of  electronic journals.  Since December 1994, <A HREF="http://www.cityscape.co.uk/users/ad88/psych.htm"><I>Psychiatry On-Line</I></A> has been a freely available electronic journal, edited by Benjamin Green, M.D., a consultant in psychological medicine at Halton Hospital, Cheshire, UK.  Green has collected a list of visitors to this Web site, which now numbers over 5000.  Articles have covered topics ranging from dialectical behaviour therapy to drugs of abuse and addiction. All articles are archived so that anyone on the Web can access them at any time.  Perhaps even more famous than this journal is <A HREF="http://www.princeton.edu/~harnad/psyc.html"><I>Psycoloquy</I></A>, a refereed electronic journal about psychology, cognitive science, neuroscience and behavioral science, linguistics and philosophy with an estimated readership of 40,000.  This journal parallels editor Sevan Harnad's (Ph.D.) paper journal, <I>Behavior and Brain Science</I> both in subject matter and editorial practice.  The main difference is that <I>Psycoloquy</I> is distributed via e-mail and available on a WWW archive. 
<P>
<H2>Getting on the Web</H2>
<DD>Readers who are interested in getting on the Web need three things: a wired connection to the Internet, Internet connectivity software, and browser software.  Computers networked through a university or hospital already meet the first criteria.  Home-based computers that work through a modem will need a connection through an Internet provider.  Although those details are not covered in this article, it is important to note that some providers supply only e-mail or telnet connections to the Internet.  In order to use the WWW, a Point to Point Protocol (PPP) or Serial Line Internet Protocol (SLIP) type of connection is necessary.  As the Web grows in popularity, more providers, including commercial service providers like CompuServe or Prodigy, are enabling WWW-capable connections.
<P>
<DD>Internet connectivity software is often packaged with computer systems.  Windows-based computers use WinSock whereas Macintosh computers use MacTCP.  This software enables the connection between the Internet and the Web browser program.  Many Web browsers are available, the most common being <A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/SDG/Software/Mosaic/Docs/help-about.html">Mosaic</A> and <A HREF="http://home.netscape.com/">Netscape</A>.  Any browser can explore the Web, but documents may look slightly different depending on the particular browser you use.  Browser software can be obtained from books on the Internet, Internet providers, or even directly downloaded from the Internet.  For details of using a browser, see the accompanying <A HREF="#sidebar">sidebar</A>.
<P>
<H2>Difficulties with the Web</H2>
<DD>Although the Web is an exciting new resource, there are difficulties that become apparent with use.  One basic problem is that of organization.  No central organization and no definitive index to the Web exists.  Anyone with access to the Web can add information to it, and while this fact adds much diversity, it also makes navigation difficult as the quantity of information becomes overwhelming.
<P>
<DD>This basic problem generates another.  The Web is a dynamic, constantly changing place.  New documents appear and replace old ones.  Updates occur on a daily basis, and some pages get major overhauls; they are moved to new machines or modified to take advantage of newer Web technology such as security standards.  Browsers and Web standards keep changing, so that different Web browsers have different special features and display documents differently.  All of these types of changes mean that Web documents can be quickly outdated if they are not maintained.  Individuals who maintain Web sites ("webmasters") need to keep up with the technology as well as keep an eye on the constantly changing WWW information network.  They can thus serve as human synthesizers and filters of information, simplifying the task of Web navigation for the people who visit their Web sites.
<P>
<H2>The Future</H2>
<DD>Despite the above drawbacks, the Web is still the easiest way to access enormous amounts of information from the Internet.  As more psychiatrists contribute, we can shape it into a more useful information tool.  Several areas of application could be pursued.  The most obvious is educational.  As already mentioned, the Web contains informational pamphlets directed to patients.  This resource could also be applied to teaching residents and physicians.  The "<A HREF="http://indy.radiology.uiowa.edu/VirtualHospital.html">Virtual Hospital</A>" from the University of Iowa teaches radiology though multimedia textbooks that contain radiographs that are displayed on the viewer's computer screen.  Physicians can even earn CME credits online.
<P>
<DD>Opportunities exist for providing psychiatric teaching to medical students, primary practitioners, and others who need this information.  Besides supplying information through electronic journals, psychiatrists could design educational programs with accompanying video to teach the subtleties of the mental status examination. Clips of clinical interactions could be used to hone the assessment skill of trainees and physicians who otherwise would not have access to such psychiatric teaching.
<P>
<DD>Beyond disseminating psychiatric information, the WWW could help generate that information as well.  As a communications tool, the Web can tie together workers in the field and various research centers to facilitate the health services research process.  For example, pediatric cardiologists from eleven institutions contribute data to the <A HREF="http://www.med.umich.edu/pdc">Midwest Pediatric Pacemaker Registry</A> which summarizes that information on the Web, describing the current standards and approaches used in pacemaker treatment.  Electronic polling of Web-connected clinicians could help identify aspects of the current practice of psychiatry and disseminate that information to any location within reach of a modem.  We could construct databases to provide rapid feedback about drug efficacy or side effects.
<P>
<DD>Because of the many potential uses of the World Wide Web, psychiatrists should consider informing themselves about this resource so that we can take advantage of that potential in all applicable areas, whether service, research, or education.
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="sidebar">Sidebar - Traversing the Web</A></H2>

<DD>Once you have an Internet connection and a Web browser running, you need to enter a Web page address or Uniform Resource Locator (URL).  As an example, the URL for the University of Michigan Department of Psychiatry's homesite, Psychiatry Star, is:
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu">http://www.psych.med.umich.edu</A></CENTER>
<P>
This URL has two basic parts.  The first part specifies the type of communication.  "http" stands for HyperText Transfer Protocol which is the language of Web hyperlinks.  "www.psych.med.umich.edu" is this name of the serving computer, located in the "psych" network in the medical school network in the University of Michigan network.  Once this address is entered into a browser program, the Psychiatry Star homepage is downloaded from the UM server and you will see the page below.<A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/"><IMG ALIGN="Left" SRC="psystar.gif" ALT="image of PsychStar page" HSPACE=5 VSPACE=5></A>  As you read down the page, you see highlighted links to other pages maintained at this Web site, including an electronic brochure on the <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/UMpsych/">UM Psychiatry Department</A>, the homepage of the <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/aacap/">AACAP</A>, a page on <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/intpsych/">InterPsych</A>, and more.  The article you are now reading is also available there, in a hypertext format to demostrate the use of hyperlinks.  You are now visiting the article directly, having entered the URL: 
<P>
http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/psytimes/psychwww.htm
<P>
<DD>Although this is an excellent starting place for examining the Web, the art of Web "surfing" involves familiarity with two important categories of Websites: prebuilt subject indices and "robot" search engines.  Many such options are summarized in a simple format at 
CUSI (configurable unified search index):	<A HREF="http://www.eecs.nwu.edu/susi/cusi.html">http://www.eecs.nwu.edu/susi/cusi.html</A>
<P>
<DD>Subject indices are hierarchically organized listing of different topic areas, good for those interested in finding out what is available on a broad topic.
<P>
<B>Subject indices:</B><BR>
<PRE><TABLE ID="1" BORDER>
<TR><TD>Yahoo:	<TD><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/">http://www.yahoo.com/</A>

<TR><TD>EINet Galaxy:	<TD><A HREF="http://www.einet.net/">http://www.einet.net/</A>

<TR><TD>The Global Network Navigator Whole Internet Catalog:	<TD><A HREF="http://www.gnn.com/wic/newrescat.toc.html">http://www.gnn.com/wic/newrescat.toc.html</A>

<TR><TD>WWW Virtual Library:	<TD><A HREF="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/DataSources/bySubject/Overview.html">http://www.w3.org/hypertext/DataSources/bySubject/Overview.html</A>
</TABLE></PRE><P>
<DD>Search engines compile a database of Web addresses, allowing the user to type in a string of words to search for.  This is a good method for rapidly finding information on a very specific topic.
<P>
<B>Search engines include:</B><BR>
<PRE><TABLE ID="2" BORDER>

<TR><TD>Lycos:	<TD><A HREF="http://lycos.cs.cmu.edu/">http://lycos.cs.cmu.edu/</A>

<TR><TD>The World Wide Web Worm:	<TD><A HREF="http://www.cs.colorado.edu/home/mcbryan/WWWW.html">http://www.cs.colorado.edu/home/mcbryan/WWWW.html</A>

<TR><TD>WebCrawler:	<TD><A HREF="http://webcrawler.com/WebCrawler/WebQuery.html">http://webcrawler.com/WebCrawler/WebQuery.html</A>

<TR><TD>ALIWEB:	<TD><A HREF="http://www.cs.indiana.edu/aliweb/form.html">http://www.cs.indiana.edu/aliweb/form.html</A>
</TABLE></PRE><P>
<DD>Recognize that although the database of a robot like Lycos contains references to over four million web documents, that may be only half of the total number of documents on the Web.
<P>
<HR>
