<HEAD>
<TITLE>Psychiatry and the World Wide Web</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#EEFFFF">
<B><A HREF="/">Home</A> | <A HREF="./">Up</A> | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>
<H1>U of Michigan On-Line with 1st Psychiatric Informatics Fellowship</H1>
<I>by <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/UMpsych/staff/nalessi/">Norman Alessi</A>, MD and <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/UMpsych/staff/mhuang/">Milton P. Huang</A>, MD</I><BR>
&#169; 1995 Psychiatric Times.  Reprinted with permission. All rights reserved.
<P>
<DD>In 1994 we started the first <A HREF="/web/UMpsych/infmatic/index.htm">psychiatric informatics fellowship</A> at the <A HREF="http://www.umich.edu/">University of Michigan</A>. The primary goals are to provide an opportunity to study the impact of information technologies on psychiatry, as well as the potential application of these technologies in clinical care, education and research. The following article discusses the need for informatics psychiatry, the justification for such a fellowship and the areas that we have chosen to develop in our psychiatric informatics fellowship. 
<P>
<DD>Information technologies are among the most prominent forces shaping our world today. Computers, telecommunication, interactive video and CD-ROM, mobile communication and the Internet are just a few technologies changing the cultures in which we live and practice.
<P>
<DD>To date, psychiatry has not demonstrated an understanding of the significance of these technologies. Certainly, all would recognize the computer's utility in an office practice for billing or in a managed care environment, where there is an increased need to develop &quot;practitioner profiles&quot; to remain competitive. But what about computers' impact on education, research and clinical care?
<P>
<DD>Other areas of medicine, including radiology, pathology and internal medicine, have maintained interest in information technologies and have developed a wide range of applications. Psychiatry's psychoanalytic and biological traditions have not needed to recognize the potential that growing information technologies provide. Neither bound by procedures nor basing its development on technical innovation, psychiatry has been insulated from these trends and may suffer from a self-selection of physicians who do not feel comfortable with these technologies. We are isolated within a world becoming increasingly more reliant on technology and isolated from medicine itself. But at the same time, medicine is becoming more reliant on data and information for all facets of its functioning.
<P>
<DD>Because of this situation, we have developed the first psychiatric informatics fellowship.
<P>
<DD>Medical informatics is the study of the acquisition, communication and use of information in medicine (Shortliffe 1990). It has a professional organization: the <A HREF="http://amia2.amia.org/">American Medical Informatics Association</A>. Whereas the importance of information and its study has been acknowledged for years within a number of medical areas, its significance has only recently become apparent in psychiatry. Information is vital in all areas concerning the development and maintenance of psychiatry. Billing and tracking of patient contacts inside complex health care systems have necessitated the use of advanced &quot;client-server&quot; data bases. The need to communicate about patients has spurred the use of electronic mail (e-mail) systems, bypassing traditional modes of communication (Bourke 1994).
<P>
<DD>With the further growth of managed care systems that demand convenience and increasingly universal access of care and information to guarantee its delivery, the electronic patient record will become a reality (Ball and Hannah 1994). This will make patient care data available potentially anywhere, anytime, by anyone who has authorized access. 
<P>
<DD>Laboratory information presented now in text-based formats will incorporate multimedia reports including digital video, graphics and sound. In psychiatry, these could include segments from actual clinical interviews taken throughout the course of an illness. 
<P>
<DD>More and more digital educational materials will become available. Medical students will visit &quot;virtual libraries&quot; of psychiatric data and advanced neuroimaging data bases. The first such data base is the &quot;Visible Human Project&quot; sponsored by the National Library of Medicine, found at the following World Wide Web (WWW) site: <A HREF="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/extramural_research.dir/visible_human.html">http://www.nlm.nih.gov/extramural_research.dir/visible_human.html</A>.
<P>
<DD>Information technology will profoundly influence research. It will not only expedite current research, but open up the development of new research areas. It will contribute to the evolution of nosology. We currently use text-based concepts which were developed in the late 19th century. Information technology will allow the study of psychiatric diseases in &quot;real time&quot;: The ability to sit at one's computer and send and receive instant messages from other on-line participants.
<P>
<DD>Many programs exist that provide informatics training. The primary focus of these programs is to develop applications related to specific areas of medicine. Despite the apparent evolving significance of information technologies and informatics within psychiatry, to our knowledge there are no such informatics training programs with psychiatry as a focus. Given the needed expertise to both comprehend and to make contributions in psychiatric informatics, a fellowship was needed.
<P>
<DD>Our psychiatric informatic fellowship is designed to teach the principles of informatics as well as foster research in the applications of informatics to psychiatry. The acquired experience is also meant to help prepare fellows for potential contributions in the development of and participation in the management of psychiatric organizations. 
<P>
<DD>The fellowship experience has three components: didactic course work, practical experience in dealing with real-world problems encountered in the development and maintenance of information systems and involvement in an informatics research project. 
<P>
<DD>Didactic course work involves both participation in an introductory course about informatics and elective courses. The fellowship provides participation in a year-long survey course about medical informatics. The principle areas covered are hospital information systems, medical library information systems, medical communications, medical instruction and medical decision-making. Electives include participation in a broad range of seminars, lectures and courses through the schools of engineering, library science, bioengineering, computer science, public health and business. Potential topics discussed include artificial intelligence, robotics, computer programming, networking, data base development, telecommunications, telemedi-cine and multimedia development. 
<P>
<DD>Real world problems are tackled in the fellowship through exposure to different treatment settings based at the University of Michigan. Inpatient, outpatient and managed care environments all have information processing needs. Fellows are involved in tracking how information flows through these systems and implementing ways that this flow can be monitored or made more efficient with computer-based tools. Fellows are also engaged in the important task of educating their psychiatrist colleagues about the process of information management and the use of information management tools, and working with residents and faculty in lectures and seminars.
<P>
<DD>Research for the informatics fellow is centered in three principle development areas: telecommunications, multimedia development and telemedicine. The primary focus of the telecommunications projects has been the development of Web sites for the <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/UMpsych/">department of psychiatry</A> and the <A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/aacap/">American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry</A>. These projects have entailed acquiring knowledge and skills about the Internet, LAN and WAN, and the WWW. The multimedia projects have entailed skills development in several areas including graphics, audio, digital video and the &quot;authoring&quot; programs necessary to compile these media into meaningful multimedia presentations such as videos or CD-ROMs. Telemedicine projects involve aspects of network hardware and video production in creating connections between different areas for clinical communications between physicians or between physicians and patients.
<P>
<DD>Another equally important aspect of all projects is gaining an appreciation for the significance of information technologies on those systems it affects. These psychological organizational factors often determine the success or failure of any project. 
<P>
<DD>The creation of this fellowship provides a unique opportunity not only for our program but for psychiatry as well. We hope to recruit fellows who can continue this tradition of creating effective demonstrations of information technology, as well as instructional skill in working with other psychiatrists. This may stimulate the development of similar informatics programs for psychiatry throughout the United States. 
<HR>
<A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/UMpsych/staff/mhuang/">Dr. Huang</A> is the first psychiatric informatics fellow trained at the University of Michigan; he maintains the Psychiatry Star Web site (e-mail address: <A HREF="mailto:mhuang@umich.edu">mhuang@umich.edu</A>).
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.psych.med.umich.edu/web/UMpsych/staff/nalessi/">Dr. Alessi</A> is division chief of child and adolescent psychiatry at the University of Michigan department of psychiatry and chief information officer for the department. He is director of the psychiatric informatics fellowship.
<HR>
<H2>References</H2>
1. Ball MH, Hannah KF. Aspects of the Computer- Based Patient Record. New York: Springer-Verlag; 1994. <BR>
2. Bourke M K. Strategy and Architecture of Healthcare Information Systems. New York: Springer-Verlag; 1994.<BR>
3. Shortliffe EH. The Computer Meets Medicine: Emergence of a Discipline. In: Shortliffe E H, Wiederhold GC, eds. Medical Informatics. Computer Applications in Health Care. Reading, Mass.: Addison-Wesley; 1990.<BR>
<P>
