<HEAD>
<TITLE>Psychstar Announcements</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#EEFFFF">
<B><A HREF="/">Home</A> | Up | <A HREF="/web/tools/">Tools</A> | <A HREF="/web/help/">Help</A> | <A HREF="/web/scripts/comment.acgi">Send a comment</A></B>
<HR>

<h1><IMG SRC="/web/images/pstaricn.gif" ALT="PsychStar Logo" ALIGN=RIGHT>Announcements</h1>

<font size=+1>

<H2>The School of Information</H2> will sponsor a colloquium with Joerg M. Haake and
Anja Haake of the Integrated Publication and Information Systems Institute
(IPSI) of the German National Research Center for Information Technology.
<P>
They will speak on "Hypermedia-based Collaboration Support" in a
presentation from 3:30-5 p.m. April 4. The program will be in the Ehrlicher
Room, 411 West Hall, and is open to the public.
<P>
Over the past, the areas of hypermedia and CSCW have been developing fairly
independently. Recently, researchers have started to work on hypermedia
systems for supporting collaboration or to employ hypermedia features in
collaborative systems. This is due to the flexibility of the hypermedia
concept, that can be used as both the product of collaboration (namely a
hyperdocument) as well as a medium through which collaboration can be
achieved (by representing tasks, plans, and the document/information under
cooperative development).
<P>
Researchers at the Integrated Publication and Information Systems Institute
of the German National Research Center for Information Technology (GMD)
have worked in these areas since 1989. Results were, for example, the
cooperative hypermedia authoring environment SEPIA and, most recently, the
DOLPHIN hypermedia-based meeting support environment.
<P>
The first part of the talk will introduce the research activities of IPSI
in the area of hypermedia-based collaboration support systems. As one
example of a hypermedia-based collaboration support environment it will
present the DOLPHIN meeting support system in more detail.
<P>
The second part will then present an evaluation of the DOLPHIN system with
an emphasis on the use of hypermedia in group problem solving.
<P>
The third part of the talk will present recent work on version support for
hypermedia documents and show how this work has been used to extend DOLPHIN
with version support.
<P>
Joerg M. Haake earned a master's degree in computer science at Dortmund
University in Germany and got his doctoral degree at the Technical
University of Darmstadt in Germany. He has conducted research on hypermedia
authoring support, the design of hypermedia documents and the development
of hypermedia-based collaboration environments at GMD-IPSI since 1989, and
has served as a department manager since 1994.
<P>
Anja Haake earned a master's degree in computer science at Dortmund
University  and is about to finish her doctoral degree at the Technical
University of Darmstadt. She has conducted research on integrated
environments for the production of electronic publications (e.g., projects
on an individualized electronic newspaper, a hypermedia reference work on
art history, a production environment for news agencies) with an emphasis
on providing version support for structured hyperdocuments (e.g., CoVer
Contextual Version Server, VerSE Flexible Version Support Environment) at
GMD-IPSI since 1989.
<P>
(Apologies to those who might be in more than one list. If you reply to ask
a question about the program, please do so ONLY to the original sender of
this message and not to all recipients.)


</dl>

</font>

